{"title_page": "Zanzibar", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{distinguish|Zinjibar}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Semi-autonomous part of Tanzania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name = Zanzibar\n| native_name = Zanzibar ([[Swahili language|Swahili]])<br/>{{lang|ar|\u0632\u0650\u0646\u0652\u062c\u0650\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0631}} ([[Arabic]])<br />''Zinjib\u0101r''\n| image_flag = Flag of Zanzibar.svg\n| image_coat = Coat of arms of Zanzibar.png\n| national_motto = \n| national_anthem = {{native phrase|sw|[[Mungu ametubarikia]]|nolink=on}}<br/>''God has blessed us''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalanthems.info/znz.htm |accessdate=29 Jan 2015 |date=2014 \n|title=Zanzibar\n|first=David\n|last=Kendall |work=nationalanthems.info}}</ref>\n| image_map = Spice Islands (Zanzibar highlighted) sv.svg\n| alt_map = \n| map_caption = Location of Zanzibar within Tanzania.\n| image_map2 = Map of Zanzibar Archipelago-en.svg\n| alt_map2 = \n| map_caption2 = The major islands of [[Unguja]] and [[Pemba Island|Pemba]] in the Indian Ocean.\n| capital = [[Zanzibar City]]\n| latd = \n| latm = \n| latNS = \n| longd = \n| longm = \n| longEW = <!--capital's latitude and longitude in degrees/minutes/direction-->\n| official_languages = {{unbulleted list |\n[[Swahili language|Swahili]]| [[Arabic language|Arabic]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| ethnic_groups= {{unbulleted list |[[Arabs]]|[[Hadimu]]|[[Swahili people|Swahili]]|[[Tumbatu]]}}\n| ethnic_groups_year = \n| demonym = Zanzibari\n| government_type = [[Revolutionary Government of Zanzibar|Federacy]]\n| leader_title1 = [[President of Zanzibar|President]]\n| leader_name1 = [[Ali Mohamed Shein]]\n| leader_title2 = First VP\n| leader_name2 =\n| leader_title3 = Second VP\n| leader_name3 = [[Seif Ali Iddi]]\n| legislature = [[Zanzibar House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]\n| sovereignty_type = Independence {{nobold|from the [[United Kingdom]]}}\n| sovereignty_note = \n| established_event1 = [[Sultanate of Zanzibar|Constitutional monarchy]]\n| established_date1 = 10 December 1963\n| established_event2 = [[Zanzibar Revolution|Revolution]]\n| established_date2 = 12 January 1964\n| established_event3 = [[United Republic of Tanganyika and Zanzibar|Merger]]\n| established_date3 = 26 April 1964\n| area_km2 = 2462\n| area_label = Total{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n| area_rank = \n| percent_water = \n| area_label2 = <!--Label below area_label (optional)-->\n| area_data2 = <!--Text after area_label2 (optional)-->\n| population_estimate = \n| population_census = 1,303,569<ref>{{cite news |last=MWACHANG`A\n|first=DEVOTA\n|date= 23 May 2014\n|title=Kikwete to grace launch of 2012 statistics report |url=http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/?l=68141\n|newspaper=\n|location=\n|publisher=[[IPP Media]] }}</ref>\n| population_estimate_year = \n| population_estimate_rank = \n| population_census_year = 2012\n| population_density_km2 = 529.7\n| population_density_sq_mi = \n| population_density_rank = \n| GDP_PPP = <!--(Gross Domestic Product from Purchasing Power Parity)-->\n| GDP_PPP_year = \n| GDP_PPP_rank = \n| GDP_PPP_per_capita = \n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank = \n| GDP_nominal = $860 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kushnirs.org/macroeconomics/gdp/gdp_zanzibar.html|title=Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in Zanzibar|website=www.ushnirs.org|accessdate=2014-07-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016054112/http://kushnirs.org/macroeconomics/gdp/gdp_zanzibar.html|archive-date=16 October 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| GDP_nominal_year = 2012\n| GDP_nominal_rank = \n| GDP_nominal_per_capita = $656\n| GDP_nominal_per_capita_rank = \n| Gini = <!--(Gini measure of income inequality;input number only; valid values are between 0 and 100)-->\n| Gini_year = \n| Gini_ref = <!--(for any ref/s to associate with Gini number)-->\n| Gini_rank = \n| HDI = 0.640\n| HDI_year = 2017\n| HDI_change = \n| HDI_ref = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hdi.globaldatalab.org/areadata/shdi/|title=Sub-national HDI - Area Database - Global Data Lab|website=hdi.globaldatalab.org|access-date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n| HDI_rank = \n| currency = [[Tanzanian shilling]]\n| currency_code = TZS\n| time_zone = [[East Africa Time|EAT]]\n| utc_offset = +3\n| utc_offset_DST = +3\n| time_zone_DST = not observed\n| antipodes = <!--Place/s exactly on the opposite side of the world to country/territory-->\n| drives_on = Right\n| calling_code = [[+255]]\n| iso3166code = <!--Use to override default from common_name parameter above; omit using \"omit\".-->\n| cctld = [[.tz]]\n| footnote_a = <!--For any footnote <sup>a</sup> used above-->\n| status = [[Autonomous administrative division|Semi-autonomous]] [[Regions of Tanzania|region]] of [[Tanzania]]\n| englishmotto = \n| loctext = \n| religion = {{unbulleted list | [[Islam]] (99%)|[[Christianity]] (1%)}}\n| area_magnitude = \n| area = \n| nummembers = <!--An alternative to population for a micronation-->\n| coordinates = \n}}\n\n'''Zanzibar''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|z|\u00e6|n|z|\u1d7b|b|\u0251\u02d0r}}; {{Lang-sw|Zanzibar}}; {{Lang-ar|\u0632\u0650\u0646\u0652\u062c\u0650\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0631|Zinjib\u0101r}}) is a [[Autonomous administrative division|semi-autonomous region]] of [[Tanzania]]. It is composed of the [[Zanzibar Archipelago]] in the [[Indian Ocean]], {{convert|25|-|50|km|mi}} off the coast of the [[mainland]], and consists of many small islands and two large ones: [[Unguja]] (the main island, referred to informally as Zanzibar) and [[Pemba Island]]. The capital is [[Zanzibar City]], located on the island of Unguja. Its historic centre is [[Stone Town]], which is a [[World Heritage Site]].\n\nZanzibar's main [[industry|industries]] are [[spice]]s, [[raffia palm|raffia]], and [[tourism]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Exotic Zanzibar and its seafood | url = http://drshem.com/2011/05/21/exotic-zanzibar-and-its-seafood/ | accessdate =11 June 2011 }}</ref> In particular, the islands produce [[clove]]s, [[nutmeg]], [[cinnamon]], and [[black pepper]]. For this reason, the Zanzibar Archipelago, together with Tanzania's [[Mafia Island]], are sometimes referred to locally as the \"Spice Islands\" (a term borrowed from  the [[Maluku Islands]] of Indonesia).\n\nZanzibar is the home of the [[endemism|endemic]] [[Zanzibar red colobus]], the [[Zanzibar servaline genet]], and the [[extinction|extinct]] or rare [[Zanzibar leopard]].<ref name=\"InsideEdition 06-2018\">{{Cite news |last=Li |first=Joanna |title=Zanzibar Leopard Captured on Camera, Despite Being Declared Extinct |publisher=[[Inside Edition]] |url=https://www.insideedition.com/zanzibar-leopard-captured-camera-despite-being-declared-extinct-43962 |date=2018-06-07 |access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref name=\"MysteriousUniverse 06-2018\">{{Cite news |last=Seaburn |first=Paul |title=Extinct 'Evil' Zanzibar Leopard Seen Alive in Tanzania |publisher=Mysterious Universe |url=https://mysteriousuniverse.org/2018/06/extinct-evil-zanzibar-leopard-seen-alive-in-tanzania/ |date=2018-06-12 |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe word ''Zanzibar'' came from [[Arabic]] ''zanjib\u0101r'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u0646\u062c\u0628\u0627\u0631}} {{IPA|[zand\u0292iba\u02d0r]}}), which is in turn from [[Persian language|Persian]] ''zangb\u00e2r'' ({{lang|fa|\u0632\u0646\u06af\u0628\u0627\u0631}} {{IPA|[z\u00e6\u014bb\u0252\u02d0\u027e]}}), a compound of ''[[Zanj|Zang]]'' ({{lang|fa|\u0632\u0646\u06af}} {{IPA|[z\u00e6\u014b]}}, \"black\") + ''b\u00e2r'' ({{lang|fa|\u0628\u0627\u0631}} {{IPA|[b\u0252\u02d0\u027e]}}, \"coast\"),<ref>{{OEtymD|zanzibar}}</ref><ref name=\"Burton2010\">{{cite book|author=Richard F. Burton|title=The Lake Regions of Central Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D-ph9_ibicUC&pg=PA38|year=2010|publisher=Cosimo, Inc.|location=New York|isbn=978-1-61640-179-5|page=38}}</ref><ref name=\"Shokoohy2013\">{{cite book|author=Mehrdad Shokoohy|title=Muslim Architecture of South India: The Sultanate of Ma'bar and the Traditions of Maritime Settlers on the Malabar and Coromandel Coasts (Tamil Nadu, Kerala and Goa)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kqhddUCZ_BQC&pg=PA137|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-1-136-49977-7|page=137}}</ref> cf. the [[Sea of Zanj]]. The name is one of several [[toponyms]] sharing similar [[Placename etymology|etymologies]], ultimately meaning \"land of the blacks\" or similar meanings, in reference to the [[dark skin]] of the inhabitants.\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Zanzibar}}\n\n=== Pre-1498 ===\nThe presence of [[microlith]]s suggests that Zanzibar has been home to humans for at least 20,000 years,<ref>{{cite book|last=Hashim|first=Nadra O.|title=Language and Collective Mobilization: The Story of Zanzibar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LVFYmNO7BeEC&pg=PAxi|year=2009|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-3708-6|page=xi}}</ref> which was the beginning of the [[Later Stone Age]].\n\nA Greco-Roman text between the 1st and 3rd centuries, the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'', mentioned the island of ''Menuthias'' ({{lang-grc|\u039c\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03b8\u03b9\u03ac\u03c2}}), which is probably [[Unguja]].<ref name=\"Pearce\">{{Cite book|author=Francis Barrow Pearce|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XRRzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA81-IA2#v=onepage&q&f=true|title=Zanzibar: The Island Metropolis of Eastern Africa|date=1920|publisher=Dutton and Company|isbn=|location=New York City|pages=|author-link=Francis Barrow Pearce}}</ref> Zanzibar, like the nearby coast, was settled by Bantu-speakers at the outset of the first millennium. Archaeological finds at Fukuchani, on the north-west coast of Zanzibar, indicate a settled agricultural and fishing community from the 6th century CE at the latest. The considerable amount of [[Wattle and daub|daub]] found indicates timber buildings, and shell beads, bead grinders, and iron slag have been found at the site. There is evidence for limited engagement in long-distance trade: a small amount of imported pottery has been found, less than 1% of total pottery finds, mostly from the Gulf and dated to the 5th to 8th century. The similarity to contemporary sites such as Mkokotoni and Dar es Salaam indicate a unified group of communities that developed into the first center of coastal maritime culture. The coastal towns appear to have been engaged in Indian Ocean and inland African trade at this early period.<ref>Kusimba, Chapurukha, and Walz, Jonathan. (2018.) \"When did the Swahili become Maritime?: A Reply to Fleisher et al. (2015), and to the Resurgence in Maritime Myopia in the Archaeology of the East African Coast\", American Anthropologist 120(3).</ref> Trade rapidly increased in importance and quantity beginning in the mid-8th century and by the close of the 10th century Zanzibar was one of the central Swahili trading towns.<ref>Horton, Mark and Middleton, Tom. \"The Swahili: The Social Landscape of a Mercantile Community.\" (Oxford: Blackwell, 2010), 46.</ref>\n\nExcavations at nearby Pemba Island, but especially at Shanga in the Lamu Archipelago, provide the clearest picture of architectural development. Houses were originally built with timber (c. 1050) and later in mud with coral walls (c. 1150). The houses were continually rebuilt with more permanent materials. By the 13th century, houses were built with stone, and bonded with mud, and the 14th century saw the use of lime to bond stone. Only the wealthier patricians would have had stone and lime built houses, the strength of the materials allowing for flat roofs, while the majority of the population lived in single-story thatched houses similar to those from the 11th and 12th centuries. According to John Middleton and Mark Horton, the architectural style of these stone houses have no Arab or Persian elements, and should be viewed as an entirely indigenous development of local vernacular architecture. While much of Zanzibar Town's architecture was rebuilt during Omani rule, nearby sites elucidate the general development of Swahili, and Zanzibari, architecture before the 15th century.<ref>Horton, Mark and Middleton, John. \"The Swahili: The Social Landscape of a Mercantile Community.\" (Oxford: Blackwell, 2010), 119.</ref>\n\nPersian, Indian, and Arab traders used Zanzibar as a base for voyages between the Middle East, India, and Africa. Unguja, the larger island, offered a protected and defensible harbor, so although the archipelago offered few products of value, traders settled at [[Zanzibar City]] (\"[[Stone Town]]\") a convenient point from which to trade with the other [[Swahili coast]] towns.\n\nThe impact of these traders and immigrants on the [[Swahili culture]] is uncertain. During the [[Middle Ages]], Zanzibar and other settlements on the Swahili Coast were advanced. The littoral contained a number of autonomous trade cities. These towns grew in wealth as the [[Swahili people]] served as intermediaries and facilitators to local, inland mainland African, Arab, Persian, Indonesian, Malaysian, Indian, and Chinese merchants and traders.<ref>Kusimba, Chapurukha. \"The Rise and Decline of Swahili States.\" (Walnut Creek, California: Altamira, 1999).</ref> This interaction contributed in part to the evolution of the [[Swahili culture]], which developed its own written language. Although a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]], the [[Swahili language]] as a consequence today includes some elements that were borrowed from other civilizations, particularly [[loanword]]s from [[Arabic]]. With the wealth that they had acquired through trade, some of the Arab traders also became rulers of the coastal cities.<ref>[http://endingstereotypes.org/african_history.html The Swahili, African History, ''Ending Stereotypes for America''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130904200204/http://endingstereotypes.org/african_history.html |date=4 September 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Portuguese colonization===\n[[Vasco da Gama]]'s visit in 1498 marked the beginning of European influence. In 1503 or 1504, Zanzibar became part of the [[Portuguese Empire]] when Captain Ruy Louren\u00e7o Ravasco Marques landed and demanded and received tribute from the sultan{{who|date=March 2020}} in exchange for peace.<ref name=\"Ingrams\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oYhrCkGaxyUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Zanzibar: Its History and Its People|first=W. H.|last=Ingrams|date=1 June 1967|publisher=Psychology Press|accessdate=12 March 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780714611020}}</ref>{{rp|page: 99}} Zanzibar remained a possession of Portugal for almost two centuries. It initially became part of the Portuguese province of Arabia and Ethiopia and was administered by a governor general. Around 1571, Zanzibar became part of the western division of the Portuguese empire and was administered from Mozambique.<ref name=\"Eliot\"/>{{rp|page: 15}} It appears, however, that the Portuguese did not closely administer Zanzibar. The first English ship to visit Unguja, the ''Edward Bonaventure'' in 1591, found that there was no Portuguese fort or garrison. The extent of their occupation was a trade depot where produce was purchased and collected for shipment to Mozambique. \"In other respects, the affairs of the island were managed by the local 'king', the predecessor of the Mwinyi Mkuu of Dunga.\"<ref name=\"Pearce\"/>{{rp|page: 81}} This hands-off approach ended when Portugal established a fort on Pemba Island around 1635 in response to the Sultan of [[Mombasa]]'s slaughter of Portuguese residents several years earlier. Portugal had long considered Pemba to be a troublesome launching point for rebellions in Mombasa against Portuguese rule.<ref name=\"Pearce\"/>{{rp|page: 85}}\n\nThe precise origins of the sultans of Unguja are uncertain. However, their capital at [[Unguja Ukuu]] is believed to have been an extensive town. Possibly constructed by locals, it was composed mainly of perishable materials.<ref name=\"Pearce\"/>{{rp|page: 89}}\n\n=== Sultanate of Zanzibar ===\n{{Main|Sultanate of Zanzibar}}\n[[File:The old castle in Zanzibar.JPG|thumb|right|250px|The castle in Zanzibar]]\n[[File:The Harem and Tower Harbour of Zanzibar (p.234, 1890) - Copy.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Harem and Tower Harbour of Zanzibar (p.234), London Missionary Society<ref name=LMS>{{cite journal|title=The Harem and Tower Harbour of Zanzibar|journal=Chronicles of the London Missionary Society|date=1890|url=https://archive.org/details/chroniclelondon00unkngoog|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>]]\n\nThe Portuguese arrived in East Africa in 1498, where they found a series of independent towns on the coast, with Muslim Arabic-speaking elites. While the Portuguese travelers describe them as 'black' they made a clear distinction between the Muslim and non-Muslim populations.<ref>Prestholdt, Jeremy. \"Portuguese Conceptual Categories and the \u201cOther\u201d Encounter on the Swahili Coast.\" Journal of Asian American Studies, Volume 36, Issue 4, 390.</ref> Their relations with these leaders were mostly hostile, but during the sixteenth century they firmly established their power, and ruled with the aid of tributary sultans. The Portuguese presence was relatively limited, leaving administration in the hands of preexisting local leaders and power structures. This system lasted until 1631, when the Sultan of Mombasa massacred the Portuguese inhabitants. For the remainder of their rule, the Portuguese appointed European governors. The strangling of trade and diminished local power led the Swahili elites in Mombasa and Zanzibar to invite Omani aristocrats to assist them in driving the Europeans out.<ref name=\"Eliot\">Sir Charles Eliot, K.C.M.G., [https://archive.org/details/eastafricaprotec00eliouoft ''The East Africa Protectorate''], London: Edward Arnold, 1905, digitized by the Internet Archive in 2008 ([[PDF]] format).</ref>{{rp|page: 9}}\n\nIn 1698, Zanzibar came under the influence of the [[Oman|Sultanate of Oman]].<ref>N. S. Kharusi, [http://etn.sagepub.com/content/12/3/335 \"The ethnic label Zinjibari: Politics and language choice implications among Swahili speakers in Oman\"], ''Ethnicities'', 12(3) 335\u2013353, 2012.</ref> There was a [[Oman\u2013Zanzibar war|brief revolt]] against Omani rule in 1784. Local elites invited Omani merchant princes to settle on Zanzibar in the first half of the nineteenth century, preferring them to the Portuguese. Many locals today continue to emphasize that indigenous Zanzibaris had invited [[Seyyid Said]], the first Busaidi sultan, to their island,{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} claiming a patron-client relationship with powerful families was a strategy used by many Swahili coast towns since at least the fifteenth century.<ref>Meier, Prita. \"Swahili Port Cities: The Architecture of Elsewhere.\" (Bloomington Indiana: Indiana University press, 2016) Pg. 103.</ref>\n\n[[File:The narrow alley in the stone city of Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|A narrow pedestrian alleyway in [[Stone Town]], Zanzibar.]]\nIn 1832,<ref name=\"Ingrams\"/>{{rp|page: 162}} or 1840<ref name=\"Appiah\">{{citation|editor1-last=Appiah|editor2-last=Gates|editor1-link=Kwame Anthony Appiah|editor2-first=Henry Louis Jr.|editor2-link=Henry Louis Gates, Jr.|year=1999|title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|location=[[New York City|New York]]|isbn=0-465-00071-1|oclc=41649745|url=https://archive.org/details/africanaencyclop00appi}}</ref>{{rp|page: 2,045}} (the date varies among sources), [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman]] moved his capital from [[Muscat, Oman]] to Stone Town. After Said's death in June 1856, two of his sons, [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini bin Said]] and [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]], struggled over the [[order of succession|succession]]. Said's will divided his dominions into two separate [[principality|principalities]], with Thuwaini to become the Sultan of Oman and Majid to become the first [[Sultan of Zanzibar]], the brothers quarreled about the will, which was eventually upheld by [[Charles Canning, 1st Earl Canning]], Great Britain's [[Governor-General of India|Viceroy and Governor-General of India]].<ref name=\"Ingrams\"/>{{rp|pages: 163\u20134}}<ref name=\"Eliot\"/>{{rp|pages: 22\u20133}}\n\n[[File:Zanzslgwch.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Zanj]] slave gang in Zanzibar (1889)]]\nUntil around 1890, the sultans of Zanzibar controlled a substantial portion of the Swahili coast known as [[Zanj]], which included Mombasa and [[Dar es Salaam]]. Beginning in 1886, Great Britain and Germany plotted to obtain parts of the Zanzibar sultanate for their own empires.<ref name=\"Appiah\"/>{{rp|page: 188}}\nIn October 1886, a British-German border commission established the Zanj as a {{convert|10|nmi|km|adj=mid|-wide}} strip along most of the [[African Great Lakes]] region's coast, an area stretching from [[Cape Delgado]] (now in [[Mozambique]]) to [[Kipini]] (now in [[Kenya]]), including Mombasa and Dar es Salaam. Over the next few years, however, almost all of these mainland possessions were lost to European imperial powers.\n\nThe sultans developed an economy of trade and [[cash crop]]s in the Zanzibar Archipelago with a ruling Arab elite. [[Ivory]] was a major trade good. The archipelago, sometimes referred to by locals as the Spice Islands, was famous worldwide for its cloves and other spices, and plantations were developed to grow them. The archipelago's commerce gradually fell into the hands of traders from the [[Indian subcontinent]], whom Said bin Sultan encouraged to settle on the islands.\n\nDuring his 14-year reign as sultan, Majid bin Said consolidated his power around the [[Arab slave trade]]. Malindi in Zanzibar City was the Swahili Coast's main port for the slave trade with the Middle East. In the mid-19th century, as many as 50,000 slaves passed annually through the port.\n{{quote|Many were captives of [[Tippu Tip|Tippu Tib]], a notorious Arab slave trader and ivory merchant. Tib led huge expeditions, some 4,000 strong, into the African interior, where chiefs sold him their villagers for next to nothing. These Tib used to caravan ivory back to Zanzibar, then sold them in the slave market for large profits. In time Tib became one of the wealthiest men in Zanzibar, the owner of multiple plantations and 10,000 slaves.<ref>[http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/data/2001/10/01/html/ft_20011001.6.html \"Swahili Coast: East Africa's Ancient Crossroads\", in a \"Did You Know?\"] sidebar by Christy Ullrich, ''National Geographic''.</ref>}}\n\nOne of Majid's brothers, [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash bin Said]], succeeded him and was forced to abolish the slave trade in the Zanzibar Archipelago by the British. He largely developed Unguja's infrastructure.<ref>{{citation|last=Michler|first=Ian|title=Zanzibar: The Insider's Guide|publisher=Struik Publishers|location=Cape Town|year=2007|edition=2nd|page=137|isbn=978-1-77007-014-1|oclc=165410708}}</ref> Another brother of Majid, [[Khalifah bin Said of Zanzibar|Khalifa bin Said]], was the third sultan of Zanzibar and furthered the relationship with the British which led to the archipelago's progress toward abolishing slavery.<ref name=\"Ingrams\"/>{{rp|page: 172}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== British protectorate ===\n[[File:Monument to Slaves.jpg|Monument to the [[slave]]s in Zanzibar|200px|thumb]]\n\nControl of Zanzibar eventually came into the hands of the [[British Empire]]; part of the political impetus for this was the 19th century movement for the [[Abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolition of the slave trade]]. Zanzibar was the centre of the [[Arab slave trade]], and in 1822, the British [[consul]] in Muscat put pressure on Sultan Said to end the slave trade. The first of a series of anti-slavery treaties with Britain was signed by Said which prohibited slave transport south and east of the [[Moresby Treaty|Moresby Line]], from Cape Delgado in Africa to Diu Head on the coast of India.<ref name=\"McIntyre\">Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013). \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p. 10.</ref> Said lost the revenue he would have received as duty on all slaves sold, so to make up for this shortfall he encouraged the development of the slave trade in Zanzibar itself.<ref name=\"McIntyre\"/> Said came under increasing pressure from the British to abolish slavery, and in 1842 the British government told the Zanzibari ruler it wished to abolish the slave trade to Arabia, Oman, Persia, and the Red Sea.<ref>Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013), \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p.13.</ref>\n\n[[File:Zanzibar stamp.png|thumb|The post office in Zanzibar was initially managed by the postal service of British India. Before dedicated Zanzibar stamps could be manufactured, Indian stamps were locally overprinted. This item is from a pre-printed Indian envelope or postcard, overprinted at the offices of the Zanzibar Gazette, which had the only printing press in the territory.]]\n\nShips from the [[Royal Navy]] were employed to enforce the anti-slavery treaties by capturing any [[dhow]]s carrying slaves, but with only four ships patrolling a huge area of sea, the British navy found it hard to enforce the treaties as ships from France, Spain, Portugal, and the United States continued to carry slaves.<ref>Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013), \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p. 14.</ref> In 1856, Sultan [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid]] consolidated his power around the [[African Great Lakes]] slave trade, and in 1873 Sir [[John Kirk (explorer)|John Kirk]] informed his successor, Sultan [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash]], that a total blockade of Zanzibar was imminent, and Barghash reluctantly signed the Anglo-Zanzibari treaty which abolished the slave trade in the sultan's territories, closed all slave markets and protected liberated slaves.<ref>Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013). \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p. 19.</ref>\n\nThe relationship between Britain and the [[German Empire]], at that time the nearest relevant colonial power, was formalized by the 1890 [[Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty]], in which Germany agreed to \"recognize the British protectorate over ... the islands of Zanzibar and Pemba\".<ref>[http://germanhistorydocs.ghi-dc.org/pdf/eng/606_Anglo-German%20Treaty_110.pdf Article XI, Anglo-German Treaty (Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty)], 1 July 1890 ([[PDF]] format).</ref>\n[[File:Zanzibar 1900 to 1920.jpg|thumb|A street scene in Zanzibar during the early 20th century]]\nIn 1890 Zanzibar became a [[protectorate]] (not a colony) of Britain. This status meant it continued to be under the sovereignty of the [[Sultan of Zanzibar]]. [[British Prime Minister]] [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|Salisbury]] explained his position:\n:The condition of a protected dependency is more acceptable to the half civilised races, and more suitable for them than direct dominion.  It is cheaper, simpler, less wounding to their self-esteem, gives them more career as public officials, and spares of unnecessary contact with white men.<ref>Andrew Roberts, ''Salisbury: Victorian Titan'' (1999) p 529</ref>\n\nFrom 1890 to 1913, traditional [[viziers]] were in charge; they were supervised by advisors appointed by the Colonial Office.  However, in 1913 a switch was made to a system of direct rule through residents (effectively governors) from 1913.  The death of the pro-British [[Sultan]] [[Hamad bin Thuwaini]] on 25 August 1896 and the succession of Sultan [[Khalid bin Barghash of Zanzibar|Khalid bin Barghash]], whom the British did not approve of, led to the [[Anglo-Zanzibar War]]. On the morning of 27 August 1896, ships of the [[Royal Navy]] destroyed the Beit al Hukum Palace. A [[cease fire]] was declared 38&nbsp;minutes later, and to this day the bombardment stands as the shortest war in history.<ref>{{cite book|author=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldre000guin|title=Guinness World Records 2008|date=7 August 2007|publisher=Guinness World Records|isbn=978-1-904994-19-0|editor-last=Craig Glenday|edition=|location=London|page=[https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldre000guin/page/118 118]|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n===Zanzibar revolution and merger with Tanganyika===\n{{main|Zanzibar Revolution}}\n[[File:Abeid Karume 1964.jpg|thumb|upright|President [[Abeid Karume]]]]\n\nOn 10 December 1963,<ref>Zanzibar Act 1963 of the United Kingdom - Note that the title of this Act was not the Zanzibar Independence Act because the UK was not conferring independence as it did not have sovereignty; it was ending the Protectorate over that territory and providing for its fully responsible government</ref> the Protectorate that had existed over Zanzibar since 1890 was terminated by the United Kingdom. The United Kingdom did not grant Zanzibar independence, as such, because the UK had never had sovereignty over Zanzibar. Rather, by the Zanzibar Act 1963 of the United Kingdom, the UK ended the Protectorate and made provision for full self-government in Zanzibar as an independent country within the Commonwealth. Upon the Protectorate being abolished, Zanzibar became a [[constitutional monarchy]] under the Sultan.<ref name=\"DeptofStatep986\">{{Harvnb|United States Department of State|1975|p=986}}</ref>\n\nHowever, just a month later, on 12 January 1964 Sultan [[Jamshid bin Abdullah of Zanzibar|Jamshid bin Abdullah]] was [[deposition (politics)|deposed]] during the [[Zanzibar Revolution]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Ayany|1970|p=122}}</ref> The Sultan fled into exile, and the Sultanate was replaced by the [[People's Republic of Zanzibar and Pemba]], a [[State socialism|socialist government]] led by the [[Afro-Shirazi Party]] (ASP). Over 20,000 people were killed and refugees, especially Arabs and Indians, escaped the island as a consequence of the revolution.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The forgotten genocide of the Zanzibar revolution - Speak Magazine|url = http://speakjhr.com/2014/01/forgotten-genocide-zanzibar-revolution/|website = Speak Magazine|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1964, the republic merged with mainland [[Tanganyika]]. This United Republic of Tanganyika and Zanzibar was soon renamed, [[blend word|blend]]ing the two names, as the United Republic of [[Tanzania]], within which Zanzibar remains a semi-autonomous region.\n\n== Demography==\n[[File:Zanzibar Stone Town11.jpg|thumb|A street scene in Stone Town]]\n[[File:Zanzibar Stone Town02.jpg|thumb|Produce vendors at a market]]\n\nThe 2002 census is the most recent census for which results have been reported. The total population of Zanzibar was 984,625<ref name=\"2002 Census Zanzibar S\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/south_unguja.htm|title=2002 Population and Housing General Report: South Unguja|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040318024855/http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/south_unguja.htm|archivedate=18 March 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref> \u2013 with an annual growth rate of 3.1 percent.<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zanzibar-travel-guide.com/bradt_guide.asp?bradt=1844 |title=People and Culture \u2013 Zanzibar Travel Guide |publisher=Zanzibar-travel-guide.com |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref> The population of [[Zanzibar City]], which was the largest city, was 205,870.<ref name=guide/>\n\nAround two thirds of the people, 622,459, lived on [[Unguja]] (Zanzibar Island), with most settled in the densely populated west. Besides Zanzibar City, other towns on Unguja include [[Chaani, Tanzania|Chaani]], [[Mbweni, Zanzibar|Mbweni]], [[Mangapwani]], [[Chwaka]], and [[Nungwi]]. Outside of these towns, most people live in small villages and are engaged in farming or fishing.<ref name=guide/>\n\nThe population of [[Pemba Island]] was 362,166.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/districts/pemba.htm|title=2002 Population and Housing Census General Report: Pemba|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610161809/http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/pemba.htm|archivedate=10 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The largest town on the island was [[Chake-Chake]], with a population of 19,283. The smaller towns are [[Wete]] and [[Mkoani]].<ref name=guide/>\n\n[[Mafia Island]], the other major island of the Zanzibar Archipelago but administered by mainland Tanzania (Tanganyka), had a total population of 40,801.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/districts/mafia.htm|title=2002 Population and Housing Census General Report: Mafia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610180829/http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/districts/mafia.htm|archivedate=10 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Census\n!Population<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Tanzania-Cities.html|title=Tanzania: Regions and Cities - Population Statistics in Maps and Charts|website=www.citypopulation.de|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|1978\n|476,111\n|-\n|1988\n|640,685\n|-\n|2002\n|981,754\n|-\n|2012\n|1,303,569\n|}\n\n=== Ethnic origins ===\nThe people of Zanzibar are of diverse ethnic origins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/people/people.html |title=Zanzibar People and Culture |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045310/http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/people/people.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first permanent residents of Zanzibar seem to have been the ancestors of the [[Bantus|Bantu]] [[Hadimu]] and [[Tumbatu]], who began arriving from the [[African Great Lakes]] mainland around AD 1000. They belonged to various mainland ethnic groups and on Zanzibar, generally lived in small villages. They did not coalesce to form larger political units.\n\nDuring Zanzibar's brief period of independence in the early 1960s, the major political cleavage was between the [[Shirazi people|Shirazi]] (Zanzibar Africans), who made up approximately 56% of the population, and the Zanzibar Arabs, who made up approximately 17%.<ref name=growup1>{{cite web |author=GROWup - Geographical Research On War, Unified Platform |title=Ethnicity in Zanzibar |url=https://growup.ethz.ch/atlas/Zanzibar |publisher=ETH Zurich |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=growup2>{{cite journal |author=Sheriff, Abdul |title=Race and Class in the Politics of Zanzibar |journal=Africa Spectrum |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=301\u2013318 |jstor=40174901 |year=2001 }}</ref> Today, Zanzibar is inhabited mostly by ethnic [[Swahili people|Swahili]], a [[Bantu peoples|Bantu]] population of sub-Saharan Africans.<ref name=\"guide\"/> There are also a number of [[Arabs]], as well as some ethnic [[Persian people|Persian]] and [[Indian diaspora in Southeast Africa|Indian]] people.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/outofdate/bgn/tanzania/127939.htm Tanzania (08/09)] . U.S. Department of State.</ref>\n\n=== Languages ===\nZanzibaris speak [[Swahili language|Swahili]] (Kiswahili), a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]] that is extensively spoken in the [[African Great Lakes]] region. Swahili is the de facto [[National language|national]] and [[official language]] of Tanzania. Many local residents also speak [[Arabic]], [[French language|French]] and/or [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref>Chris McIntyre and Susan McIntyre, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zlqv0gSkk-kC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=purest+form+of+swahili+zanzibar&source=bl&ots=mO3h6Xd7Ao&sig=yPmOLFlSPZC44LfT6c_vyOKooKw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fRvPUOHFM67piwLy6YD4Bg&ved=0CGgQ6AEwCg#v=onepage&q=purest%20form%20of%20swahili%20zanzibar&f=false \"Zanzibar, Pemba, and Mafia\"], ''Bradt Travel Guide'', 2009, p. 36.</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\n{{See also|Islam in Zanzibar}}\n[[File:The mosque and church are located closely in the stone city of Zanzibar.jpg|left|100px|thumb|The main mosque and Anglican cathedral in [[Stone Town]]]]\n{{Bar box\n| title=Zanzibar Religions (2010 est.)\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| float=right\n| bars=\n{{Bar percent|Islam|green|98.9}}\n{{Bar percent|Christianity|blue|0.6}}\n{{Bar percent|Indigenous|brown|0.5}}\n|caption=Source: [[CIA World Factbook]].<ref name=\"cia.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tz.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nZanzibar's population is almost entirely Muslim, with a small Christian minority containing around 22 000 Christians.<ref name=\"cia.gov\"/> Other religious groups that are represented include [[Hindus]], [[Jainism|Jains]] and [[Sikhs]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keshodkar|first=Akbar|date=2010-03-29|title=Marriage as the Means to Preserve 'Asian-ness': The Post-Revolutionary Experience of the Asians of Zanzibar|journal=Journal of Asian and African Studies|volume=45|issue=2|pages=226\u2013240|doi=10.1177/0021909609357418|issn=0021-9096}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Anglican Diocese of Zanzibar]] was founded in 1892. The first Bishop of Zanzibar was [[Charles Smythies]], who was translated from his former post as Bishop of [[Nyasaland]]. The cathedral, located in [[Stone Town]], Zanzibar City, is a prominent landmark, and a national heritage asset.\n\nIt had fallen into poor condition by the late 20th century, but it was fully restored in 2016, at a cost of one million Euros, with a world heritage visitor centre. The restoration was supported by the Tanzanian and Zanzibari governments, and overseen by the diocese in partnership with the [[World Monuments Fund]].<ref>Progress report and photographs at [http://www.zanzibaranglican.or.tz/progress-update/ this] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628101223/http://www.zanzibaranglican.or.tz/progress-update/ |date=28 June 2017 }} webpage.</ref> The restoration of the spire, clock, and historic [[Henry Willis & Sons|Willis]] organ are still outstanding. Historically the diocese included mainland locations in [[Tanganyika]]. In 1963 it was renamed as the Diocese of Zanzibar & Dar es Salaam. Two years later, in 1965, Dar es Salaam became a separate diocese. The original jurisdiction was renamed as the Diocese of Zanzibar & Tanga. In 2001 the mainland links were finally ended, and it is now known as the Diocese of Zanzibar. The diocese includes parishioners on the neighbouring island of [[Pemba Island|Pemba]]. Ten bishops have served in the diocese from 1892 to the present day. The bishop is [[Michael Hafidh]]. It is part of the Province of Tanzania, under the Archbishop of All Tanzania, based at Dodoma.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Zanzibar]] was established in 1980. An apostolic vicariate of Zanzibar had been established in 1906, from a much larger East African jurisdiction. This was suppressed in 1953, when the territory was out under control of the Kenyan church, but it was restored in 1964 after independence. The church created a diocese here shortly before Easter 1980. The bishop is [[Augustine Ndeliakyama Shao]]. Zanzibar is part of the Roman Catholic Province of Dar es Salaam, under the Archbishop of Dar es Salaam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daressalaamarchdiocese.or.tz/en/historical-background/|title=Historical Background|last=|first=|date=|website=Dar es Salaam Archdiocese|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther Christian denominations include the Evangelical Lutheran Church of Tanzania which arrived in Zanzibar town in the 1960s,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Lutheran Church on the coast of Tanzania, 1887-1914 : with special reference to the Evangelical Lutheran Church in Tanzania, Synod of Uzaramo-Uluguru|last=Sicard, Sigvard von.|date=1970|publisher=Gleerup|oclc=1100148145}}</ref> and a wide range of Pentecostal-Charismatic Christian churches such as the Tanzania Assemblies of God, the Free Pentecostal Church of Tanzania, the Evangelical Assemblies of God, the Pentecostal Church of Tanzania, the Victory Church and the Pentecostal Evangelistic Fellowship of Africa. Pentecostal-Charismatic churches have been present and growing in Zanzibar since the 1980s in relation to economic liberalization and increased labor migration from mainland Tanzania in connection to Zanzibar's expanding tourist sector. There are also [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh Day Adventist]] and [[Baptists|Baptist]] churches.<ref>{{Citation|last=Olsson|first=Hans|chapter=Narratives of Pentecostal (Non-)Belonging|date=2019-07-04|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-40681-0|doi=10.1163/9789004410367_008|title=Jesus for Zanzibar: Narratives of Pentecostal (Non-)Belonging, Islam, and Nation}}</ref> \n\nSince 2005 there is also an inter-religious body called the Joint Committee of Religious Leaders for Peace (in Swahili ''Juhudi za Viongozi wa Dini kuimarisha Amani'') with representatives from Muslim institutions such as the Islamic law (''Kadhi'' courts), religious property (the ''Wakf'' and Trust commission), education (the Muslim academy) and the ''[[Mufti]]''\u2019s office as well as representatives from the Roman Catholic, the Anglican and the Lutheran church.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Peace in Zanzibar|last=Lang\u00e5s|first=Arngeir|date=2019-04-12|publisher=Peter Lang US|isbn=978-1-4331-5969-5|doi=10.3726/b14434}}</ref> \n----\n\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Government ==\n{{Politics of Tanzania}}\nAs a semi-autonomous part of [[Tanzania]], Zanzibar has its own government, known as the [[Revolutionary Government of Zanzibar]]. It is made up of the [[Revolutionary Council (Zanzibar)|Revolutionary Council]] and [[House of Representatives of Zanzibar|House of Representatives]].\nThe House of Representatives has a similar composition to the [[National Assembly of Tanzania]]. Fifty members are elected directly from constituencies to serve five-year terms; 10 members are appointed by the [[President of Zanzibar]]; 15 special seats are for women members of political parties that have representation in the House of Representatives; six members serve ''[[ex officio member|ex officio]]'', including all regional commissioners and the attorney general.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zanzibarassembly.go.tz/composition.html |title=Composition |publisher=The House of Representatives - Zanzibar |accessdate=23 October 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Five of these 81 members are then elected to represent Zanzibar in the National Assembly.<ref>[http://www.parliament.go.tz/index.php/home/pages/6 Composition, Parliament of Tanzania] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021211837/http://www.parliament.go.tz/index.php/home/pages/6 |date=21 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nUnguja has three administrative regions: [[Zanzibar Central/South]], [[Zanzibar North]] and [[Zanzibar Urban/West]]. Pemba has two: [[Pemba North]] and [[Pemba South]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statoids.com/utz.html|title=Tanzania Regions|website=www.statoids.com|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the independence and sovereignty of Zanzibar, Tanzania Prime Minister [[Mizengo Pinda]] said on 3 July 2008 that there was \"nothing like the sovereignty of Zanzibar in the Union Government unless the Constitution is changed in future\". Zanzibar House of Representatives members from both the ruling party, [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]], and the opposition party, [[Civic United Front]], disagreed and stood firmly in recognizing Zanzibar as a fully autonomous state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unpo.org/article/8392 |title=Zanzibar: Premier under fire on Zanzibar status |date=10 July 2008 |publisher=Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization |accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\n{{see also|Zanzibar independence movement}}\n[[File:12 Jan. 2004, festivities at 40th anniversary of the Zanzibar Revolution. President Karume enters Amani Stadium in ceremonial Hummer.JPG|thumb|180px|left|12 Jan 2004: President Karume of Zanzibar enters Amani Stadium for the celebration of the 40th anniversary of Zanzibar's 1964 revolution]]\n\nZanzibar has a government of national unity, with the president of Zanzibar being [[Ali Mohamed Shein]], since 1 November 2010. There are many political parties in Zanzibar, but the most popular parties are the [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] (CCM) and the [[Civic United Front]] (CUF). Since the early 1990s, the politics of the archipelago have been marked by repeated clashes between these two parties.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nContested elections in October 2000 led to a massacre on 27 January 2001 when, according to [[Human Rights Watch]], the army and police shot into crowds of protestors, killing at least 35 and wounding more than 600. Those forces, accompanied by ruling party officials and militias, also went on a house-to-house rampage, indiscriminately arresting, beating, and sexually abusing residents. Approximately 2,000 temporarily fled to Kenya.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://hrw.org/english/docs/2002/04/10/tanzan3838.htm |title=Tanzania: Zanzibar Election Massacres Documented |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=10 April 2002 |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nViolence erupted again after [[Tanzanian general election, 2005|another contested election]] on 31 October 2005, with the CUF claiming that its rightful victory had been stolen from it. Nine people were killed.<ref>[http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2002597738_webzanzibar01.html \"Nine killed in Zanzibar election violence\", ''Seattle Times'', reported by Chris Tomlinson, The Associated Press, 1 November 2005] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006165946/http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2002597738_webzanzibar01.html |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.karelprinsloo.com/#/works/zanzibar-election-violence-2005?i=386|title=Zimbabwe Farm Evictions 2000|website=karelprinsloo karel prinsloo}}</ref>\n\nFollowing 2005, negotiations between the two parties aiming at the long-term resolution of the tensions and a power-sharing accord took place, but they suffered repeated setbacks. The most notable of these took place in April 2008, when the CUF walked away from the negotiating table following a CCM call for a referendum to approve of what had been presented as a done deal on the power-sharing agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tzaffairs.org/2008/05/zanzibar-a-big-disappointment|title=Tanzanian Affairs \u00bb ZANZIBAR \u2013 A BIG DISAPPOINTMENT|website=www.tzaffairs.org|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, the then-president of Zanzibar, [[Amani Abeid Karume]], met with CUF secretary-general [[Seif Sharif Hamad]] at the State House to discuss how to save Zanzibar from future political turmoil and to end the animosity between them.<ref name=\"Karume\">[http://zirppo.wordpress.com/2009/11/19/karume-no-elections-next-year-in-zanzibar-if \"Karume: No elections next year in Zanzibar if\u2026\", Zanzibar Institute for Research and Public Policy, reported by Salma Said, reprinted from an original article in ''The Citizen'', 19 November 2009]</ref> This move was welcomed by many, including the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zanzibar-tanzania.usvpp.gov/ |title=Welcome to VPP Zanzibar, Tanzania |work=United States Virtual Presence Post |publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]] |accessdate=27 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203094450/http://zanzibar-tanzania.usvpp.gov/ |archive-date=3 February 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was the first time since the [[multi-party system]] was introduced in Zanzibar that the CUF agreed to recognize Karume as the legitimate president of Zanzibar.<ref name=\"Karume\"/>\n\nA proposal to amend Zanzibar's constitution to allow rival parties to form governments of national unity was adopted by 66.2 percent of voters on 31 July 2010.<ref>[http://www.eisa.org.za/WEP/zan2010referendum.htm \"Zanzibar: 2010 Constitutional referendum results\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105050420/https://eisa.org.za/wep/zan2010referendum.htm |date=5 January 2016 }}, Electoral Institute for the Sustainability of Democracy in Africa, updated August 2010.</ref>\n\nThe autonomous status of Zanzibar is viewed as comparable to [[Hong Kong]] as suggested by some scholars, and  being recognized as the \"African Hong Kong\".<ref>Simon Shen, ''One country, two systems: Zanaibar'', Ming Pao Weekly, Sep 2016.</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Geography ==\n{{Main|Zanzibar Archipelago}}\n[[File:Approaching Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|Coastline off Zanzibar]]\n[[File:A bird's view of the stone city in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|A bird's view of the stone city in Zanzibar]]\n\nZanzibar is one of the [[List of Indian Ocean islands|Indian Ocean islands]]. It is situated on the [[Swahili Coast]], adjacent to [[Tanganyika]] (mainland Tanzania).\n\nThe northern tip of Unguja island is located at 5.72 degrees south, 39.30 degrees east, with the southernmost point at 6.48 degrees south, 39.51 degrees east.<ref name=\"L&L\">{{cite web|url=http://www.findlatitudeandlongitude.com|title=Find Latitude and Longitude|website=www.findlatitudeandlongitude.com|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> The island is separated from the Tanzanian mainland by a channel, which at its narrowest point is {{convert|36.5|km|mi}} across.<ref name=\"Zanzinet\">[http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/visiwa.html Zanzibar Archipelago, Zanzinet Forum: Where Zanzibaris Meet] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223120539/http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/visiwa.html |date=23 December 2015 }}</ref> The island is about {{convert|85|km|mi}} long and {{convert|39|km|mi}} wide,<ref name=\"Zanzinet\"/> with an area of {{convert|1464|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Guide\">{{cite web |url= http://www.africaguide.com/country/zanzibar/ |title= The Africa Guide \u2013 Zanzibar |work=web page |publisher= africaguide.com |accessdate =26 October 2012}}</ref> Unguja is mainly low lying, with its highest point being {{convert|120|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"Guide\"/> Unguja is characterised by beautiful sandy beaches with fringing coral reefs.<ref name=\"Guide\"/> The reefs are rich in marine biodiversity.<ref>Molly Moynihan, [http://digitalcollections.sit.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1828&context=isp_collection \"Water Quality and Eutrophication: The Effects of Sewage Outfalls on Waters and Reefs Surrounding Stone Town, Zanzibar\"], Independent Study Project Collection, 2010, p. 8.</ref>\n\nThe northern tip of Pemba island is located at 4.87 degrees south, 39.68 degrees east, and the southernmost point is located at 5.47 degrees south, 39.72 degrees east.<ref name=\"L&L\"/> The island is separated from the Tanzanian mainland by a channel some {{convert|56|km|mi}} wide.<ref name=\"Zanzinet\"/> The island is about {{convert|67|km|mi}} long and {{convert|23|km|mi}} wide, with an area of {{convert|985|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Zanzinet\"/> Pemba is also mainly low lying, with its highest point being {{convert|95|m|ft}}.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/582817/Tanzania/37556/Zanzibar-and-Pemba \"Tanzania: Zanzibar and Pemba\", ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'']</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\n{{see also|Climate of Tanzania}}\nThe heat of summer (corresponding to the Northern Hemisphere winter) is often cooled by strong sea breezes associated with the [[northeast monsoon]] (known as ''Kaskazi'' in Kiswahili), particularly on the north and east coasts. Being near to the equator, the islands are warm year round. The rainfall regime is split into two main seasons, a primary maximum in March, April, and May in association with the [[southwest monsoon]] (known locally as ''Kusi'' in Kiswahili), and a secondary maximum in November and December.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/nature/hali_ya_hewa.html |title=Climate and Soils |work=Zanzinet Forum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006230003/http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/nature/hali_ya_hewa.html |archivedate=2014-10-06}}</ref> The months in between receive less rain, with a minimum in July.\n\n{{Weather box|location = Zanzibar\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 90\n|Feb high F = 91\n|Mar high F = 91\n|Apr high F = 86\n|May high F = 84\n|Jun high F = 83\n|Jul high F = 82\n|Aug high F = 83\n|Sep high F = 84\n|Oct high F = 86\n|Nov high F = 89\n|Dec high F = 89\n|year high F = 87\n|Jan low F = 76\n|Feb low F = 76\n|Mar low F = 77\n|Apr low F = 77\n|May low F = 75\n|Jun low F = 74\n|Jul low F = 72\n|Aug low F = 72\n|Sep low F = 72\n|Oct low F = 73\n|Nov low F = 75\n|Dec low F = 76\n|year low F = 75\n|Jan precipitation inch = 2.3\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.6\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.8\n|Apr precipitation inch = 12.6\n|May precipitation inch = 11.4\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.1\n|Jul precipitation inch = 1.1\n|Aug precipitation inch = 1.2\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.6\n|Oct precipitation inch = 2.6\n|Nov precipitation inch = 6.7\n|Dec precipitation inch = 5.5\n|year precipitation inch = 55.5\n|source 1 = [[Weatherbase]]<ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web |url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=7836&refer=wikipedia |title =Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Zanzibar, Tanzania |publisher=[[Weatherbase]] |year=2011 |accessdate=24 November 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Wildlife ==\n{{Main|Wildlife of Zanzibar}}\n\n=== Unguja ===\n[[File:Dolphin leap.JPG|thumb|A dolphin in the Indian Ocean, off the coast of Zanzibar]]\n[[File:Papilio Demodocus Citrus Swallowtail Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Papilio demodocus]]'' in Zanzibar, Nungwi.]]\n\nThe main island of Zanzibar, [[Unguja]], has a fauna reflecting its connection to the African mainland during the [[last glacial period|last Ice Age]].<ref name=\"Pakenham1984\">{{Cite book|author = Pakenham, R. H. W. |year = 1984 |url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/14538645/The-Mammals-of-Zanzibar-and-Pemba |title = The Mammals of Zanzibar and Pemba Islands |location = Harpenden |publisher = privately printed |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Walsh2007\">{{Cite journal|author= Walsh, Martin T. |year=2007 |title= Island Subsistence: Hunting, Trapping and the Translocation of Wildlife in the Western Indian Ocean |journal= Azania |volume= 42 |pages= 83\u2013113 |url= https://www.scribd.com/doc/14444883/Island-Subsistence-Hunting-Trapping-and-the-Translocation-of-Wildlife-in-the-Western-Indian-Ocean/|accessdate=27 August 2010|doi=10.1080/00672700709480452}}</ref>\n\nEndemic mammals with continental relatives include the [[Zanzibar red colobus]] (''Procolobus kirkii''), one of Africa's rarest primates, with perhaps only 1,500 existing. Isolated on this island for at least 1,000 years, this colobus is recognized as a distinct species, with different coat patterns, calls, and food habits from related colobus species on the mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galenfrysinger.com/red_colobus.htm |title=Red Colobus |publisher=galenfrysinger.com |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref> The Zanzibar red colobus lives in a wide variety of drier areas of coastal thickets and coral rag scrub, as well as [[mangrove swamp]]s and agricultural areas. About one third of them live in and around [[Jozani Chwaka Bay National Park|Jozani Forest]]. The easiest place to see the colobus is farmland adjacent to the reserve. They are accustomed to people and the low vegetation means they come close to the ground.\n\nRare native animals include the [[Zanzibar leopard]],<ref name=\"InsideEdition 06-2018\"/><ref name=\"MysteriousUniverse 06-2018\"/> which is critically endangered, and the recently described [[Zanzibar servaline genet]]. There are no large wild animals in Unguja. Forested areas such as Jozani are inhabited by monkeys, bushpigs, small antelopes, [[African civet]]s, and, as shown by a [[camera trap]] in June 2018,<ref name=\"InsideEdition 06-2018\"/><ref name=\"MysteriousUniverse 06-2018\"/> the elusive leopard. Various species of mongoose can also be found on the island. There is a wide variety of birdlife and a large number of butterflies in rural areas.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Pemba ===\n[[Pemba Island]] is separated from Unguja island and the African continent by deep channels and has a correspondingly restricted fauna, reflecting its comparative isolation from the mainland.<ref name=Pakenham1984/><ref name=Walsh2007/> The island is home to the [[Pemba flying fox]].\n\n{{wide image|Zanzibar Panorama.jpg|1100px|A panorama of Stone Town taken from the Indian Ocean. Seen in the picture are the [[Palace Museum, Zanzibar|Sultan's palace]], [[House of Wonders]], [[Forodhani Gardens]], and [[St. Joseph's Cathedral, Zanzibar|St. Joseph's Cathedral]]}}\n\n== Standard of living and health ==\n[[File:Poster prevenzione.jpg|thumb|Prophylaxis poster in Zanzibar, 2008]]\nConsiderable disparities exist in the [[standard of living]] for inhabitants of Pemba and Unguja, as well as the disparity between urban and rural populations. The average annual income is US$250. About half the population lives below the poverty line.\n\nDespite a relatively high standard of primary health care and education, [[infant mortality]] in Zanzibar is 54 out of 1,000 live births, which is 10.0 percent lower than the rate in mainland Tanzania. The [[child mortality]] rate in Zanzibar is 73 out of 1,000 live births, which is 21.5 percent lower than the rate in mainland Tanzania.<ref>[http://www.measuredhs.com/pubs/pdf/FR243/FR243%5B24June2011%5D.pdf \"Tanzania Demographic and Health Survey 2010\", National Bureau of Statistics, Dar es Salaam, published April 2011, page 120] ([[PDF]] format).</ref>\n\nIt is estimated that 7% of children on Zanzibar have acute [[malnutrition]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dhsprogram.com/pubs/pdf/FR321/FR321.pdf |title=Tanzania Demographic and Health Survey and Malaria Indicator Survey 2015-2016 - Final Report |website=DHS Program |accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Life expectancy]] at birth is 57 years,<ref>\"Zanzibar: Social Protection Expenditure\nand Performance Review and Social Budget\", Social Security Department, International Labour Office, Geneva, Switzerland, January 2010, page 22</ref> which is significantly lower than the 2010 world average of 67.2.\n\nThe general prevalence of [[HIV/AIDS]] in the population of Zanzibar aged 15-64 is 0.5 percent, with the rate much higher in females (0.9 percent) than males (less than 0.1 percent).<ref>https://phia.icap.columbia.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/FINAL_THIS-2016-2017_Final-Report__06.21.19_for-web_TS.pdf</ref>\n\n== Environment ==\nThe northern part of the island presents elevated volumes of trash in the streets, beaches and the ocean\u2014mostly plastic bottles, other plastics and cigarette butts. There is indiscriminate dumping in residential areas. Medical equipment waste is a particular problem on the island.<ref>[http://www.ijcrar.com/special/1/Biubwa%20Ally,%20et%20al.pdf IJCRAR]</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Gift of the Ocean.jpg|thumb|Seaweed farming in [[Jambiani]]]]\n[[File:Aquakulturen Rotalgen Sansibar 1.jpg|thumb|[[Aquaculture]] of red algae ([[Eucheuma]]), Jambiani]]\n[[File:Low Tide (7886864976).jpg|thumb|Tourism is one of the main sectors of the economy]]\n[[File:Zanzibar Stone Town01.jpg|thumb|Market stall in Zanzibar's Stone Town]]\n\nAncient [[pottery]] implies trade routes with Zanzibar as far back as the time of the ancient [[Assyria]]ns. Traders from the [[Arabian Peninsula]], the [[Persian Gulf]] region of modern-day [[Iran]] (especially [[Shiraz]]), and [[west India]] probably visited Zanzibar as early as the 1st century. They used the [[monsoon]] winds to sail across the Indian Ocean to land at the sheltered harbor located on the site of present-day Zanzibar City.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe [[clove]], originating from the [[Moluccan Islands]] (today in Indonesia), was introduced in Zanzibar by the Omani sultans in the first half of the 19th century.<ref>Professor Trevor Marchand. [http://www.archaeologicaltrs.com/me_oman.html Oman & Zanzibar: The Sultans of Oman] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031092051/http://www.archaeologicaltrs.com/me_oman.html |date=31 October 2013 }}. Archaeological Tours.</ref> Zanzibar, mainly [[Pemba Island]], was once the world's leading clove producer,<ref name=\"LAtimes\">{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/24/world/fg-cloves24 |title=Zanzibar Loses Some of Its Spice |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |author= Sanders, Edmund |date=24 November 2005 |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref> but annual clove sales have plummeted by 80 percent since the 1970s. Zanzibar's clove industry has been crippled by a [[terms of trade|fast-moving global market]], international competition, and a hangover from Tanzania's failed experiment with [[African socialism|socialism]] in the 1960s and 1970s, when the government [[Export control|controlled clove prices and exports]]. Zanzibar now ranks a distant third with Indonesia supplying 75 percent of the world's cloves compared to Zanzibar's 7 percent.<ref name=\"LAtimes\"/>\n\nZanzibar exports spices, seaweed and fine [[raffia]]. Beside the Zanzibar State Trading Cooperation, Zanj Spice Limited, also known as 1001 Organic, is the biggest organic spice exporter in Zanzibar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wo der Bio-Pfeffer w\u00e4chst|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/race-to-feed-the-world/wie-ein-schweizer-jurist-auf-sansibar-bio-gewuerze-anbaut-15947684.html/|publisher=www.faz.net|accessdate=23 December 2018}}</ref> Zanzibar also has a large fishing and [[dugout (boat)|dugout]] canoe production. Tourism is a major foreign currency earner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zanzibar Then and Now|url=http://www.zanzibarholidays.co.uk/zanzibar-then-and-now/|publisher=www.zanzibarholidays.co.uk|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Government of Zanzibar legalized foreign exchange bureaux on the islands before mainland Tanzania moved to do so. The effect was to increase the availability of consumer commodities. The government has also established a free port area, which provides the following benefits: contribution to economic diversification by providing a window for free trade as well as stimulating the establishment of support services; administration of a regime that imports, exports, and warehouses general merchandise; adequate storage facilities and other infrastructure to cater for effective operation of trade; and creation of an efficient management system for effective re-exportation of goods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/2843.htm |title=Background Note: Tanzania |author=Bureau of African Affairs |date=8 June 2010 |publisher= [[U.S. Department of State]] |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe island's manufacturing sector is limited mainly to import substitution industries, such as cigarettes, shoes, and processed agricultural products. In 1992, the government designated two export-producing zones and encouraged the development of offshore financial services. Zanzibar still imports much of its staple requirements, petroleum products, and manufactured articles.{{cn|date=June 2019}}\n\nThere is also a possibility of oil availability in Zanzibar on the island of Pemba, and efforts have been made by the Tanzanian Government and Zanzibar revolutionary Government to exploit what could be one of the most significant discoveries in recent memory. Oil would help boost the economy of Zanzibar, but there have been disagreements about dividends between the Tanzanian mainland and Zanzibar, the latter claiming the oil should be excluded in Union matters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tzbusinessnews.com/zanzibar-oil-and-the-union/|title=Economy|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n[[File:Dolphin tour in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|Tourists in boat are chasing dolphins in the Indian Ocean near Zanzibar]]\nIn 2007, a [[Norway|Norwegian]] consultancy firm went to Zanzibar to determine how the region could develop its [[oil]] potential.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecitizen.co.tz/newe.php?id=10276 |publisher=thecitizen.co.tz |accessdate=11 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502194550/http://thecitizen.co.tz/newe.php?id=10276 |archivedate=2 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The firm recommended that Zanzibar follow economist [[Hernando de Soto Polar]]'s ideas about the formalization of property rights for persons living on ancestral land for which they probably do not have a legal [[deed]].<ref name=\"Battle\">Chambi Chachage, [http://www.africanexecutive.com/modules/magazine/article_print.php?article=4864 \"Norway in Tanzania: The Battle Rages\"]{{Better source|reason=This poorly written opinion piece appears to be the only source on the internet for what would be quite an interesting development|date=November 2014}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053229/http://www.africanexecutive.com/modules/magazine/article_print.php?article=4864 |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''The African Executive''.</ref>\n\n=== Tourism ===\n{{Main|Tourism in Zanzibar}}\n\nIn 1984, fewer than 20,000 tourists visited Zanzibar. Five times more visitors travelled to the island in 2000. The events of [[September 11, 2001]] reduced the inflow of tourists, which was restored only after 2004. Zanzibar has at least 6,200 beds across six classes of accommodation. However, there is a disproportionately large number in ungraded, one and two star categories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzaniainvest.com/telecoms/zanzibar-tourism-sector-profile|title=Tanzania Invest - Zanzibar Tourism Sector|last=|first=|date=9 January 2006|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Energy ===\nThe energy sector in Zanzibar consists of unreliable electric power, petroleum and petroleum products; it is also supplemented by firewood and its related products. Coal and gas are rarely used for either domestic and industrial purposes.\n\nUnguja (Zanzibar Island) gets most of its electric power from mainland Tanzania through a 39-kilometer, 100-megawatt submarine cable from Ras Kiromoni (near Dar es Salaam) to Ras Fumba on Unguja. The laying of the cable was begun on 10 October 2012 by the [[Viscas Corporation]] of Japan and was funded by a US$28.1 million grant from the United States through the [[Millennium Challenge Corporation]].<ref>[http://tanzania.usembassy.gov/pr_10102012c.html \"Ambassador Lenhardt Participates in Ceremony to Install 100 Megawatt Submarine Power to Zanzibar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217123714/http://tanzania.usembassy.gov/pr_10102012c.html |date=17 February 2013 }}. Press Release, Embassy of the United States, Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 10 October 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.salem.co.tz/projects/data?project=229&featured=1 132kV Sabmarine Cable - Zanzibar Iterconnector at Ras Kiromoni and Ras Fumba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728124453/http://salem.co.tz/projects/data?project=229&featured=1 |date=28 July 2013 }}, Featured Project, Salem Construction, Ltd.</ref> The cable became operational on 13 April 2013.<ref>Yussuf, Issa (24 April 2013). [http://allafrica.com/stories/201304240892.html \"Tanzania: Reliable Power to Accelerate Development in Isles President Ali\"].  ''[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]]'' (via [[AllAfrica.com]]).  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> The previous 45-megawatt cable, which was seldom-maintained, was completed by Norway in 1980.<ref>[http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08DARESSALAAM839 \"Zanzibar Power: Electrical And Political Shortages\", Cable from the United States Embassy in Dar Es Salaam to the United States Secretary of State] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502223345/http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08DARESSALAAM839 |date=2 May 2013 }}, reference identification 08DARESSALAAM839, 15 December 2008.</ref>\n\nSince May 2010, Pemba Island has had a 75-kilometer, 25-megawatt, subsea electrical link directly to mainland Tanzania. The cable project was financed through a 45 million euro grant from Norway and contributions of 8 million euros from the Zanzibar government and 4 million euros from the Tanzanian national government. The project ended years of dependence on unreliable and erratic diesel generation subject to frequent power cuts. Only about 20 percent of the cable's capacity was being used in January 2011, so it is anticipated that the cable will meet the island's needs for 20 to 25 years.<ref>Press release (3 June 2010). [http://www.nexans.com/eservice/Corporate-en/navigatepub_0_-25837/Nexans_completes_subsea_cable_link_to_provide_reli.html \"Nexans Completes Subsea Cable Link to Provide Reliable Power for Pemba Island in Zanzibar{{spaced ndash}} New 25 MVA Link to Mainland Grid Has Enabled the Local Population to End Years of Dependence on Unreliable Diesel Generators\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505225414/http://www.nexans.com/eservice/Corporate-en/navigatepub_0_-25837/Nexans_completes_subsea_cable_link_to_provide_reli.html |date=5 May 2013 }}. [[Nexans]].  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.norway.go.tz/News_and_events/Energy/Reliable-electricity-attracts-investors-to-Pemba \"Reliable electricity attracts investors to Pemba\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822050718/http://www.norway.go.tz/News_and_events/Energy/Reliable-electricity-attracts-investors-to-Pemba/ |date=22 August 2011 }}, Norway: The Official Site in Tanzania, 28 January 2011.</ref>\n\nBetween 70 and 75 percent of the electricity generated is used domestically while less than 20 percent is used industrially. Fuel wood, charcoal and kerosene are widely used as sources of energy for cooking and lighting for most rural and urban areas. The consumption capacity of petroleum, gas, oil, kerosene and industrial diesel oil is increasing annually, going from a total of 5,650 tons consumed in 1997 to more than 7,500 tons in 1999.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\nFrom 21 May to 19 June 2008, Unguja suffered a [[2008 Zanzibar Power blackout|major failure of its electricity system]], which left the island without electrical service and mostly dependent on diesel generators. The failure originated in mainland Tanzania.<ref>{{cite news| author = Staff | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7427957.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | title=Melting in Zanzibar's Blackout | date=30 May 2008 | accessdate= 14 September 2013}}</ref> Another blackout happened from 10 December 2009 to 23 March 2010, caused by a problem with the submarine cable that formerly supplied electricity from mainland Tanzania.<ref>O'Connor, Maura R. (1 April 2010; updated 30 May 2010).  [http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/africa/100331/zanzibar-tanzania-electricity-shortage \"Zanzibar's Three-Month Blackout{{spaced ndash}} Indian Ocean islands Go for 90 Days Without Power, Causing Business Problems and Water Shortages\"]. [[GlobalPost]].  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> This led to a serious shock to Unguja's fragile economy, which is heavily dependent on foreign tourism.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Bububu railway train, circa 1905.jpg|thumb|A train operating on the railway between [[Bububu]] and [[Stone Town]] in Zanzibar, circa 1905]]\n\n===Roads===\nZanzibar has 1,600&nbsp;kilometres of roads, of which 85 percent are tarmacked or semi-tarmacked. The remainder are earth roads, which are rehabilitated annually to make them passable throughout the year.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}. Zanzibar, to ensure the roads are passable at all times and are maintained had established a Road Fund Board, situated at maisala which collects funds and disburses to Ministry of Communication, whom is the Road Agency at this time through the Department of Road Maintenance, known as UUB.\n\nThe Road Fund Board, oversees a Performance Agreement entered between the Ministry of Communication and Infrastructure, while all the procurements and maintenances are assumed by the later.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Public transportation ===\nThere is no government-owned public transportation in Zanzibar. The privately owned [[Dala-dala|Daladala]], as it is officially known in Zanzibar, is the only kind of public transportation. The term Daladala originated from the Kiswahili word DALA(Dollar) or five shillings during the 1970s and 1980s when public transport cost five shillings to travel to the nearest town. Therefore, travelling to town will cost a Dollar(\u201cDala\u201d) and returning will again cost a Dollar, hence the term Daladala originated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mzfn.org/Zanzibar.html|title=MZF {{!}} About Zanzibar|website=www.mzfn.org|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Stone Town]] is the main hub for [[Dala dala|Daladalas]] on Zanzibar and nearly all journeys will either start or end here.  There are two main Dala Dala stations in Stone Town: Darajani market and Mwanakwerekwe market.  The Darajani market terminus serves the North and North East of the island and the Mwanakwerekwe market terminus serves the South and South East.  As with most of East African transport, the buses do not run on set schedules - instead departing when full.  As there is no fixed schedule, it is not possible to book tickets in advance (with the exception of [http://www.thezanzibus.com The Zanzibus]).  There are plans of implementing a government-operated bus service on the island, which will bring the ground transportations more in line with the relatively developed water and air transport infrastructure, but there is currently no timeline available for this project.  With Zanzibar visitor numbers set to top 1,000,000 annually, there will be increasing pressure on the current transportation network - the bus network will reduce the number of vehicles on the road and help reduce environmental impact of tourism on the Zanzibar.\n\n=== Maritime transport ===\n\n==== Ports ====\n[[File:Zanzibar Harbour.jpg|thumb|right|Zanzibar Harbour]]\nThere are five ports in the islands of Unguja and Pemba, all operated and developed by the [[Zanzibar Ports Corporation]].\n\nThe main port at Malindi, which handles 90 percent of Zanzibar's trade, was built in 1925. The port was rehabilitated between 1989 and 1992 with financial assistance from the [[European Union]]. The Italian contractor, [[Impregilo|Salini Impregilo S.p.A.]], was supposed to build wharves that lasted 60 years; however, the wharves lasted only 11 years before crumbling and degenerating because the company deviated from the specifications.<ref name=\"Malindi port\">{{cite web |last=Yusof |first=Issa |date=17 October 2012 |url=http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/10593-malindi-port-gradually-sinking |title=Malindi Port Gradually Sinking |work=[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503004846/http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/10593-malindi-port-gradually-sinking |archivedate=2013-05-03}}</ref> After a long legal battle, the company was required in 2005 by the [[International Court of Arbitration]] to pay Zanzibar US$11.6 million in damages.<ref>Staff (29 November 2008). [http://www.worldcargonews.com/htm/w20081129.879920.htm \"Zanzibar (Malindi) Nears Completion\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909035715/http://www.worldcargonews.com/htm/w20081129.879920.htm |date=9 September 2014 }}, ''[[World Cargo News]]''. Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> The port was again rehabilitated between 2004 and 2009 with a 31 million euro grant from the European Union. The contract was awarded to M/S E. Phil and Sons of Denmark. The then-director of the contractor suggested that the rehabilitation would last a minimum of 50 years. But the port is again facing problems, including sinking.<ref name=\"Malindi port\"/>\n\n;Ferry accidents\nThe MV ''Faith'', which began its final journey at the port of Dar es Salaam, sank in May 2009 shortly before docking at the port of Malindi. Six of the 25 people aboard lost their lives.<ref>Hutson, Terry (30 July 2009). [http://ports.co.za/news/article_2009_07_29_3609.html \"Fire Guts Passenger Ferry in Dar es Salaam\"]. Ports & Ships Maritime News.  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\nThe [[sinking of the MV Spice Islander I]] on 10 September 2011, after departing from [[Unguja]] island for [[Pemba Island]], was the worst disaster in Tanzanian history. In a report to the [[Zanzibar House of Representatives]] on 14 October 2011, Zanzibar's Second Vice President, Ambassador [[Seif Ali Iddi]], said that 2,764 people were missing, 203 bodies had been recovered, and 619 passengers were rescued. It was the worst maritime disaster in Tanzanian history.<ref>Sadallah, Mwinyi (16 October 2011). [http://ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=34437 \"Confirmed: 2,900 People Died in Zanzibar's Ferry Tragedy\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112035114/http://ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=34437 |date=12 January 2016 }}. [[IPP Media]].  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> A presidential commission, however, reported three months later that 1,370 people were missing, 203 bodies had been recovered, and 941 passengers survived. Severe overloading caused the ferry to sink.<ref>Sadallah, Mwinyi (21 January 2012).  [http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=37681 \"Nine Charged over MV ''Spice Islander'' Sinking\"], [[IPP Media]]. Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\nThe [[MV Skagit|MV ''Skagit'']], which also began its final journey at the port of Dar es Salaam, capsized in rough seas near [[Chumbe]] island on 18 July 2012. The ferry had 447 passengers, with 81 dead, 212 missing and presumed drowned, and 154 rescued. The ferry left port despite warnings from the [[Tanzania Meteorological Agency]] for ships not to attempt the crossing from Dar es Salaam to [[Unguja]] island because of the rough seas. A presidential commission reported in October 2012 that overloading was the cause of the disaster.<ref>Staff (19 July 2012). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18899397 \"Zanzibar Ferry Disaster: Hopes Fade for Missing\"]. [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref><ref>Yussuf, Issa (12 October 2012). [http://allafrica.com/stories/201210120139.html \"Tanzania: Overloading Blamed for Ill-Fated Boat\"]. ''[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]]'' (via [[AllAfrica.com]]).  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Airport ===\n[[File:Abeid Amani Karume International Airport, 2013.jpg|thumb|right|Zanzibar Airport Terminal I]]\n\nZanzibar's main airport, [[Abeid Amani Karume International Airport]], has been able to handle large passenger planes since 2011, which has resulted in an increase in passenger and cargo inflows and outflows. Since another increase in capacity by the end of 2013, it can serve up to 1.5 million passengers per year.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.businesstimes.co.tz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1121:zanzibar-forms-airports-authority-modernises-aviation-infrastructure&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=57 | title = Zanzibar forms Airports Authority, modernises aviation infrastructure | publisher =Business Times (Tanzania) | accessdate = 17 January 2013}}</ref> The island can be reached by flights operated by [[Auric Air]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.auricair.com |title= Auric Air |date= March 30, 2012 |accessdate= March 30, 2012 |work= Auric Air Services Ltd}}</ref> [[Kenya Airways]],<ref>[[Kenya Airways]]</ref> [[Qatar Airways]], [[Turkish Airlines]], [[FlyDubai]], [[Mango (airline)|Mango Airline]] and Coastal Aviation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coastal.co.tz |title= Coastal Aviation|date= 2015 |accessdate= January 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:A view of the clock tower in House of Wonders through Islamic styled door in the Stoen City of Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|A view of the clock tower in House of Wonders through Islamic styled door in the Stone City]]\n[[File:Zanzibar International Film Festival 2013.jpg|thumb|ZIFF, 2013]]\n\nZanzibar's most famous event is the [[Zanzibar International Film Festival]], also known as the Festival of the Dhow Countries. Every July, this event showcases the best of the Swahili Coast arts scene, including Zanzibar's favorite music, [[taarab]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziff.or.tz/ |title=? }}</ref>\n\nImportant architectural features in Stone Town are the Livingstone house, [[The Old dispensary of Zanzibar]], the Guliani Bridge, Ngome kongwe (The [[Old fort of Zanzibar]]) and the [[House of Wonders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zanzibarheritage.go.tz/House%20of%20Wonders%20Museum.htm |title=? |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116053540/http://www.zanzibarheritage.go.tz/House%20of%20Wonders%20Museum.htm |archivedate=16 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The town of [[Kidichi]] features the [[Hamamni Persian Baths]], built by immigrants from [[Shiraz, Iran|Shiraz]], Iran during the reign of [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash bin Said]].\n\nZanzibar also is the only place in Eastern African countries to have the longest settlement houses formally known as [[Michenzani]] flats which were built by the aid from East Germany during the 1970s to solve housing problems in Zanzibar.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Duthel|first=Heinz|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AtRfDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT125&lpg=PT125&dq=Michenzani+flats+which+were+built+by+the+aid+from+East+Germany+during+the+1970s+to+solve+housing+problems+in+Zanzibar#v=onepage&q=Michenzani%20flats%20which%20were%20built%20by%20the%20aid%20from%20East%20Germany%20during%20the%201970s%20to%20solve%20housing%20problems%20in%20Zanzibar&f=false|title=Discover Entdecke D\u00e9couvrir Seychelles Travelogue: Wie Du Deinen Traum leben kannst, findest Du hie|date=2018-06-10|publisher=neobooks|isbn=978-3-7427-3476-1|language=es}}</ref>\n\n=== Media and communication ===\nIn 1973, Zanzibar introduced the first colour television service in sub-Saharan Africa.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7h1DAQAAIAAJ&dq=Zanzibar+colour+tv+in+Africa+1973.&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Zanzibar+ ''Mass Media, Towards the Millennium: The South African Handbook of Mass Communication''], Arrie De Beer, J.L. van Schaik, 1998, page 56</ref> Because of longstanding opposition to television by President [[Julius Nyerere]], the first television service on mainland Tanzania was not introduced until 1994.<ref>Martin Stumer, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110626211052/http://www.tanzania.at/mht/The_Media_History_of_Tanzania.pdf \"The Media History of Tanzania\"], Salzburg, Austria: Ndanda Mission Press, 1998, pp. 191, 194, 295.</ref> The broadcaster in Zanzibar called Television Zanzibar ([[TVZ]]) had recently changed name to Zanzibar Broadcasting Corporation (ZBC).<ref>[http://www.tvz.co.tz/tvz.html Karume House: Television Zanzibar] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703181848/http://www.tvz.co.tz/tvz.html |date=3 July 2013 }}</ref> following an enactment of an act to make it a public corporation, monitored under the Ministry of Finance by the treasurer registrar. Among the famous reporters of TVZ during the 1980s and 1990s were the late Alwiya Alawi 1961\u20131996 (the elder sister of Inat Alawi, famous Taarab singer during the 1980s), Neema Mussa, Sharifa Maulid, Fatma Mzee, Zaynab Ali, Ramadhan Ali, and Khamis.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nZanzibar has one AM radio station<ref>[http://www.radio-africa.org/am/fm.php?itu=Tanzania&region=zbw AM radio stations in Tanzania: Directory of AM radio stations in Zanzibar West region] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221632/http://www.radio-africa.org/am/fm.php?itu=Tanzania&region=zbw |date=3 March 2016 }}</ref> and 21 FM radio stations.<ref>[http://www.radio-africa.org/fm/reg.php?itu=Tanzania FM radio stations in Tanzania] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033728/http://www.radio-africa.org/fm/reg.php?itu=Tanzania |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn terms of [[landline]] communications, Zanzibar is served by the [[Tanzania Telecommunications Company Limited]] and Zantel Tanzania.\n\nAlmost all mobile and Internet companies serving mainland Tanzania are also available in Zanzibar.\n\n=== Education ===\n[[File:Zanzibar 2012 06 06 4220 (7592226526).jpg|thumb|Institute of Marine Sciences, [[UDSM]]]]\n\nIn 2000 there were 207 government schools and 118 privately owned schools in Zanzibar.<ref name=\"sacmeq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |title=Education in Zanzibar \u2013 Southern and Eastern African Consortium for Monitoring Educational Quality |publisher=Sacmeq.org |accessdate=4 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702114713/http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |archive-date=2 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Zanzibar has three fully accredited Universities: [[Zanzibar University]], the [[State University of Zanzibar]] (SUZA) and Sumait University (previously University College of Education, Chukwani).<ref>[http://www.tcu.go.tz/universities.html Tanzania Commission for Universities] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619083810/http://www.tcu.go.tz/universities.html |date=19 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSUZA was established in 1999, and is located in Stone Town, in the buildings of the former Institute of Kiswahili and Foreign Language (TAKILUKI).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suza.ac.tz/ |title=SUZA website |publisher=Suza.ac.tz |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref> It is the only public institution for higher learning in Zanzibar, the other two institutions being private. In 2004, the three institutions had a total enrollment of 948 students, of whom 207 were female.<ref>[http://zanzibar.go.tz/10%20Higher%20education.php Higher education \u2013 zanzibar.go.tz] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707084022/http://zanzibar.go.tz/10%20Higher%20education.php |date=7 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe primary and secondary education system in Zanzibar is slightly different from that of the Tanzanian mainland. On the mainland, education is only compulsory for the seven years of primary education, while in Zanzibar an additional three years of secondary education are compulsory and free.<ref name=sacmeq/> Students in Zanzibar score significantly less on standardized tests for reading and mathematics than students on the mainland.<ref name=sacmeq/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |title=Tanzania entry \u2013 SACMEQ |publisher=Sacmeq.org |accessdate=4 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702114713/http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |archive-date=2 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s, [[national service]] after secondary education was necessary, but it is now voluntary and few students volunteer. Most choose to seek employment or attend teacher's colleges.\n\n=== Sports ===\n[[File:A bird's view of Amaan Stadium in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|A bird's view of Amaan Stadium in Zanzibar.]]\n[[Association Football|Football]] is the most popular sport in Zanzibar, overseen by the [[Zanzibar Football Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tanzaniasports.com/?p=3115 |title=? |accessdate=11 August 2010|date=8 September 2009 }}</ref> Zanzibar is an associate member of the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF), but not of [[FIFA]]. This means that the [[Zanzibar national football team]] is not eligible to enter national CAF competitions, such as the [[African Nations Cup]], but Zanzibar's Football Clubs get representation at the [[CAF Confederation Cup]] and the [[CAF Champions League]].\n\nThe national team participates in [[non-FIFA Football]] tournaments such as the [[FIFI Wild Cup]], and the [[ELF Cup]]. Because Zanzibar is not a member of [[FIFA]], their team is not eligible for the [[FIFA World Cup]].\n\nThe Zanzibar Football Association also has a [[Zanzibar Premier League|Premier League]] for the top clubs, which was created in 1981.\n\nSince 1992, there has also been [[judo]] in Zanzibar. The founder, Tsuyoshi Shimaoka, established a team that participates in national and international competitions. In 1999, Zanzibar Judo Association (Z.J.A.) was registered and became an active member of the Tanzania Olympic Committee {{Citation needed|date=October 2011}} and International Judo Federation.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Farouque Abdillahi]], who was [[Princess Diana]]'s designer<ref>{{cite web|title=Fashion Designers: Farouque Abdela|url=http://fashionweekzanzibar.com/Designer-Farouque-Abdela.php|website=Fashion Week Zanzibar|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Annie Allen (missionary)|Annie Allen]], Englishwoman who came to call Zanzibar home after doing extensive medical missionary work there.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The History of the Universities' Mission to Central, 1859-1909.|last=Anderson-Morshead|first=Anne|publisher=|year=1897|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n* [[Freddie Mercury]] (born Farrokh Bulsara), British singer of the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], was born in [[Stone Town]], Zanzibar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/2015/10/the-wonders-of-zanzibars-stone-town/|title=The wonders of Zanzibar's Stone Town - The Spectator|date=17 October 2015|website=spectator.co.uk|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> At the age of 18, he fled with his family to the [[United Kingdom]] during the [[Zanzibar Revolution]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/9523701/Exclusive-interview-Freddie-Mercurys-mother-on-her-dear-boy.html|title=Exclusive interview: Freddie Mercury's mother on her 'dear boy'|first=Angela|last=Levin|date=8 September 2012|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> \n* Abdulrazak Gurnah, Novelist, was born in Zanzibar in 1948 and emigrated to Britain as a student in 1968 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/abdulrazak-gurnah|title=Abdulrazak Gurnah - Literature|website=literature.britishcouncil.org|access-date=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediaofafroeuropeanstudies.eu/encyclopedia/abdulrazak-gurnah/|title=Abdulrazak Gurnah|website=www.encyclopediaofafroeuropeanstudies.eu|access-date=2017-12-12}}</ref>\n* [[Lubaina Himid]], artist and winner of the 2017 [[Turner Prize]], born 1954.\n* [[Bi Kidude]], [[Taarab]] singer, queen of [[Taarab]] and [[Unyago]] music, received [[WOMEX]] award in 2005.\n* [[Siti binti Saad]], pioneering artist in [[Taarab]].\n\n== Places of worship ==\nThe [[places of worship]] in the city are predominantly [[Islam|Muslim]] mosques. <ref> Britannica,\n[https://www.britannica.com/place/Tanzania Tanzania], britannica.com, USA, accessed on January 5, 2020</ref> There are also [[Christianity|Christian]] churches and temples: [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Zanzibar]] ([[Catholic Church]]), [[Anglican Church of Tanzania]] ([[Anglican Communion]]), [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in Tanzania]] ([[Lutheran World Federation]]), [[Baptist Convention of Tanzania]] ([[Baptist World Alliance]]), [[Assemblies of God]].\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:ZanzibarBeach.jpg|A Zanzibar beach\nFile:Zanzibar from sea.jpg|Stone Town\nFile:Zanzibar sultan palace.jpg|Stone Town with Sultan's Palace\nFile:Zanzibar Red Colobus Monkey.jpg|The red colobus of Zanzibar (''Procolobus kirkii''), taken at Jozani Forest, Zanzibar, Tanzania.\nFile:Cloves-spice.jpg|[[Clove]]s have played a significant role in Zanzibar's historic economy\nFile:Zanzibarsultanpalace22.JPG|House of Wonders undergoing refurbishment.\nFile:Zanzibar east coast pristine beach.JPG|Zanzibar East Coast beach\nFile:Red-Knobbed_Starfish_Nungwi.jpg|Red-knobbed starfish on the beach in Nungwi, northern Zanzibar\nFile:TipputipPortrait.jpg|Zanzibari slave trader [[Tippu Tip]]\nFile:ZanzibarOmaniRuler.jpg|[[Oman]]i Sultan of Zanzibar\nFile:View of ferry docked at Zanzibar Old Town's Ferry Terminal.JPG|View of ferry docked at the Zanzibar Ferry Terminal\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[German East Africa]]\n* [[List of Sultans of Zanzibar]]\n* [[Zanzibari cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Chapurukha Kusimba, ''The Rise and Decline of Swahili States'' (Walnut Creek, California: AltaMira Press, 1999)\n* Don Petterson, ''Revolution in Zanzibar'' (Boulder, Colorado: Westview Press, 2002)\n* [[Emily Ruete]], ''[http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11754/ Memoirs of an Arabian Princess from Zanzibar]'', 1888 (many reprints). The author (1844\u20131924) was born Princess Salme of Zanzibar and Oman and was a daughter of Sayyid Said.\n* H. S. Newman, ''Banani: the Transition from Slavery to Freedom in Zanzibar and Pemba'' (London, 1898)\n* W. W. A. FitzGerald, ''Travels in the Coastlands of British East Africa'' (London, 1898)\n* R. N. Lyne, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_HtENAAAAIAAJ ''Zanzibar in Contemporary Times''] (London, 1905)\n* J. E. E. Craster, ''Pemba: The Spice Island of Zanzibar'' (London, 1913)\n* [[Godfrey Mwakikagile]], ''Nyerere and Africa: End of an Era'' (Pretoria, South Africa: New Africa Press, 2010); ''Tanzania under Mwalimu Nyerere: Reflections on an African Statesman'' (Pretoria, South Africa: New Africa Press, 2006); ''Why Tanganyika united with Zanzibar to form Tanzania'' (Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 2014); ''The Union of Tanganyika and Zanzibar: Formation of Tanzania and its Challenges'' (Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 2016) \n* Pearce, Francis Barrow (1920). [https://archive.org/details/zanzibarislandme00pear ''Zanzibar, the Island Metropolis of Eastern Africa''] New York, NY: E. P. Dutton and Company.\n* ''Hatice U\u011fur, Osmanl\u0131 Afrikas\u0131'nda Bir Sultanl\u0131k: Zengibar'' (Zanzibar as a Sultanate in the Ottoman Africa), \u0130stanbul: K\u00fcre Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, 2005. [https://web.archive.org/web/20080220110433/http://www.kureyayinlari.com/Icindekiler.aspx?KID=23 kureyayinlari.com] For its English version, see [http://seyhan.library.boun.edu.tr:80/record=b1268198 Boun.edu]\n* Wolfgang Scholz, ''Challenges of Informal Urbanisation. The Case of Zanzibar/Tanzania'' (Dortmund, 2008) [https://www.amazon.de/dp/3934525504 Amazon.de]\n* Christopher Gallop, ''Letters from East Africa'' (UK, Grosvenor House Publishing 2013) {{ISBN|978-1781486283}} [https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/178148628X]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Sister project links | b=no | n=no | q=no | v=no | voy=Zanzibar | species=no | d=Q1774 | mw=no | display=Zanzibar}}\n* [http://www.wunderground.com/weather-forecast/TN/Zanzibar.html Current and forecast weather for Zanzibar]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091213041637/http://zanzibar.go.tz/ Government of Zanzibar]\n* [http://www.ikuluzanzibar.go.tz/ President's office]\n\n{{Zanzibar topics}}\n{{Portuguese overseas empire}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n{{Tanzania topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|6|08|S|39|19|E|display=title|type:adm1st}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zanzibar}}\n[[Category:Zanzibar| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Zanzibar Archipelago|*]]\n[[Category:Islands of Zanzibar| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Islands of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Former member states of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Arabic-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:Former Portuguese colonies]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1963]]\n[[Category:Swahili city-states]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{distinguish|Zinjibar}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Semi-autonomous part of Tanzania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name = Zanzibar\n| native_name = Zanzibar ([[Swahili language|Swahili]])<br/>{{lang|ar|\u0632\u0650\u0646\u0652\u062c\u0650\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0631}} ([[Arabic]])<br />''Zinjib\u0101r''\n| image_flag = Flag of Zanzibar.svg\n| image_coat = Coat of arms of Zanzibar.png\n| national_motto = \n| national_anthem = {{native phrase|sw|[[Mungu ametubarikia]]|nolink=on}}<br/>''God has blessed us''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalanthems.info/znz.htm |accessdate=29 Jan 2015 |date=2014 \n|title=Zanzibar\n|first=David\n|last=Kendall |work=nationalanthems.info}}</ref>\n| image_map = Spice Islands (Zanzibar highlighted) sv.svg\n| alt_map = \n| map_caption = Location of Zanzibar within Tanzania.\n| image_map2 = Map of Zanzibar Archipelago-en.svg\n| alt_map2 = \n| map_caption2 = The major islands of [[Unguja]] and [[Pemba Island|Pemba]] in the Indian Ocean.\n| capital = [[Zanzibar City]]\n| latd = \n| latm = \n| latNS = \n| longd = \n| longm = \n| longEW = <!--capital's latitude and longitude in degrees/minutes/direction-->\n| official_languages = {{unbulleted list |\n[[Swahili language|Swahili]]| [[Arabic language|Arabic]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| ethnic_groups= {{unbulleted list |[[Arabs]]|[[Hadimu]]|[[Swahili people|Swahili]]|[[Tumbatu]]}}\n| ethnic_groups_year = \n| demonym = Zanzibari\n| government_type = [[Revolutionary Government of Zanzibar|Federacy]]\n| leader_title1 = [[President of Zanzibar|President]]\n| leader_name1 = [[Ali Mohamed Shein]]\n| leader_title2 = First VP\n| leader_name2 =\n| leader_title3 = Second VP\n| leader_name3 = [[Seif Ali Iddi]]\n| legislature = [[Zanzibar House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]\n| sovereignty_type = Independence {{nobold|from the [[United Kingdom]]}}\n| sovereignty_note = \n| established_event1 = [[Sultanate of Zanzibar|Constitutional monarchy]]\n| established_date1 = 10 December 1963\n| established_event2 = [[Zanzibar Revolution|Revolution]]\n| established_date2 = 12 January 1964\n| established_event3 = [[United Republic of Tanganyika and Zanzibar|Merger]]\n| established_date3 = 26 April 1964\n| area_km2 = 2462\n| area_label = Total{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n| area_rank = \n| percent_water = \n| area_label2 = <!--Label below area_label (optional)-->\n| area_data2 = <!--Text after area_label2 (optional)-->\n| population_estimate = \n| population_census = 1,303,569<ref>{{cite news |last=MWACHANG`A\n|first=DEVOTA\n|date= 23 May 2014\n|title=Kikwete to grace launch of 2012 statistics report |url=http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/?l=68141\n|newspaper=\n|location=\n|publisher=[[IPP Media]] }}</ref>\n| population_estimate_year = \n| population_estimate_rank = \n| population_census_year = 2012\n| population_density_km2 = 529.7\n| population_density_sq_mi = \n| population_density_rank = \n| GDP_PPP = <!--(Gross Domestic Product from Purchasing Power Parity)-->\n| GDP_PPP_year = \n| GDP_PPP_rank = \n| GDP_PPP_per_capita = \n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank = \n| GDP_nominal = $860 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kushnirs.org/macroeconomics/gdp/gdp_zanzibar.html|title=Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in Zanzibar|website=www.ushnirs.org|accessdate=2014-07-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016054112/http://kushnirs.org/macroeconomics/gdp/gdp_zanzibar.html|archive-date=16 October 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| GDP_nominal_year = 2012\n| GDP_nominal_rank = \n| GDP_nominal_per_capita = $656\n| GDP_nominal_per_capita_rank = \n| Gini = <!--(Gini measure of income inequality;input number only; valid values are between 0 and 100)-->\n| Gini_year = \n| Gini_ref = <!--(for any ref/s to associate with Gini number)-->\n| Gini_rank = \n| HDI = 0.640\n| HDI_year = 2017\n| HDI_change = \n| HDI_ref = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hdi.globaldatalab.org/areadata/shdi/|title=Sub-national HDI - Area Database - Global Data Lab|website=hdi.globaldatalab.org|access-date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n| HDI_rank = \n| currency = [[Tanzanian shilling]]\n| currency_code = TZS\n| time_zone = [[East Africa Time|EAT]]\n| utc_offset = +3\n| utc_offset_DST = +3\n| time_zone_DST = not observed\n| antipodes = <!--Place/s exactly on the opposite side of the world to country/territory-->\n| drives_on = Left\n| calling_code = [[+255]]\n| iso3166code = <!--Use to override default from common_name parameter above; omit using \"omit\".-->\n| cctld = [[.tz]]\n| footnote_a = <!--For any footnote <sup>a</sup> used above-->\n| status = [[Autonomous administrative division|Semi-autonomous]] [[Regions of Tanzania|region]] of [[Tanzania]]\n| englishmotto = \n| loctext = \n| religion = {{unbulleted list | [[Islam]] (99%)|[[Christianity]] (1%)}}\n| area_magnitude = \n| area = \n| nummembers = <!--An alternative to population for a micronation-->\n| coordinates = \n}}\n\n'''Zanzibar''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|z|\u00e6|n|z|\u1d7b|b|\u0251\u02d0r}}; {{Lang-sw|Zanzibar}}; {{Lang-ar|\u0632\u0650\u0646\u0652\u062c\u0650\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0631|Zinjib\u0101r}}) is a [[Autonomous administrative division|semi-autonomous region]] of [[Tanzania]]. It is composed of the [[Zanzibar Archipelago]] in the [[Indian Ocean]], {{convert|25|-|50|km|mi}} off the coast of the [[mainland]], and consists of many small islands and two large ones: [[Unguja]] (the main island, referred to informally as Zanzibar) and [[Pemba Island]]. The capital is [[Zanzibar City]], located on the island of Unguja. Its historic centre is [[Stone Town]], which is a [[World Heritage Site]].\n\nZanzibar's main [[industry|industries]] are [[spice]]s, [[raffia palm|raffia]], and [[tourism]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Exotic Zanzibar and its seafood | url = http://drshem.com/2011/05/21/exotic-zanzibar-and-its-seafood/ | accessdate =11 June 2011 }}</ref> In particular, the islands produce [[clove]]s, [[nutmeg]], [[cinnamon]], and [[black pepper]]. For this reason, the Zanzibar Archipelago, together with Tanzania's [[Mafia Island]], are sometimes referred to locally as the \"Spice Islands\" (a term borrowed from  the [[Maluku Islands]] of Indonesia).\n\nZanzibar is the home of the [[endemism|endemic]] [[Zanzibar red colobus]], the [[Zanzibar servaline genet]], and the [[extinction|extinct]] or rare [[Zanzibar leopard]].<ref name=\"InsideEdition 06-2018\">{{Cite news |last=Li |first=Joanna |title=Zanzibar Leopard Captured on Camera, Despite Being Declared Extinct |publisher=[[Inside Edition]] |url=https://www.insideedition.com/zanzibar-leopard-captured-camera-despite-being-declared-extinct-43962 |date=2018-06-07 |access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref name=\"MysteriousUniverse 06-2018\">{{Cite news |last=Seaburn |first=Paul |title=Extinct 'Evil' Zanzibar Leopard Seen Alive in Tanzania |publisher=Mysterious Universe |url=https://mysteriousuniverse.org/2018/06/extinct-evil-zanzibar-leopard-seen-alive-in-tanzania/ |date=2018-06-12 |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe word ''Zanzibar'' came from [[Arabic]] ''zanjib\u0101r'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u0646\u062c\u0628\u0627\u0631}} {{IPA|[zand\u0292iba\u02d0r]}}), which is in turn from [[Persian language|Persian]] ''zangb\u00e2r'' ({{lang|fa|\u0632\u0646\u06af\u0628\u0627\u0631}} {{IPA|[z\u00e6\u014bb\u0252\u02d0\u027e]}}), a compound of ''[[Zanj|Zang]]'' ({{lang|fa|\u0632\u0646\u06af}} {{IPA|[z\u00e6\u014b]}}, \"black\") + ''b\u00e2r'' ({{lang|fa|\u0628\u0627\u0631}} {{IPA|[b\u0252\u02d0\u027e]}}, \"coast\"),<ref>{{OEtymD|zanzibar}}</ref><ref name=\"Burton2010\">{{cite book|author=Richard F. Burton|title=The Lake Regions of Central Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D-ph9_ibicUC&pg=PA38|year=2010|publisher=Cosimo, Inc.|location=New York|isbn=978-1-61640-179-5|page=38}}</ref><ref name=\"Shokoohy2013\">{{cite book|author=Mehrdad Shokoohy|title=Muslim Architecture of South India: The Sultanate of Ma'bar and the Traditions of Maritime Settlers on the Malabar and Coromandel Coasts (Tamil Nadu, Kerala and Goa)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kqhddUCZ_BQC&pg=PA137|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-1-136-49977-7|page=137}}</ref> cf. the [[Sea of Zanj]]. The name is one of several [[toponyms]] sharing similar [[Placename etymology|etymologies]], ultimately meaning \"land of the blacks\" or similar meanings, in reference to the [[dark skin]] of the inhabitants.\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Zanzibar}}\n\n=== Pre-1498 ===\nThe presence of [[microlith]]s suggests that Zanzibar has been home to humans for at least 20,000 years,<ref>{{cite book|last=Hashim|first=Nadra O.|title=Language and Collective Mobilization: The Story of Zanzibar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LVFYmNO7BeEC&pg=PAxi|year=2009|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-3708-6|page=xi}}</ref> which was the beginning of the [[Later Stone Age]].\n\nA Greco-Roman text between the 1st and 3rd centuries, the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'', mentioned the island of ''Menuthias'' ({{lang-grc|\u039c\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03b8\u03b9\u03ac\u03c2}}), which is probably [[Unguja]].<ref name=\"Pearce\">{{Cite book|author=Francis Barrow Pearce|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XRRzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA81-IA2#v=onepage&q&f=true|title=Zanzibar: The Island Metropolis of Eastern Africa|date=1920|publisher=Dutton and Company|isbn=|location=New York City|pages=|author-link=Francis Barrow Pearce}}</ref> Zanzibar, like the nearby coast, was settled by Bantu-speakers at the outset of the first millennium. Archaeological finds at Fukuchani, on the north-west coast of Zanzibar, indicate a settled agricultural and fishing community from the 6th century CE at the latest. The considerable amount of [[Wattle and daub|daub]] found indicates timber buildings, and shell beads, bead grinders, and iron slag have been found at the site. There is evidence for limited engagement in long-distance trade: a small amount of imported pottery has been found, less than 1% of total pottery finds, mostly from the Gulf and dated to the 5th to 8th century. The similarity to contemporary sites such as Mkokotoni and Dar es Salaam indicate a unified group of communities that developed into the first center of coastal maritime culture. The coastal towns appear to have been engaged in Indian Ocean and inland African trade at this early period.<ref>Kusimba, Chapurukha, and Walz, Jonathan. (2018.) \"When did the Swahili become Maritime?: A Reply to Fleisher et al. (2015), and to the Resurgence in Maritime Myopia in the Archaeology of the East African Coast\", American Anthropologist 120(3).</ref> Trade rapidly increased in importance and quantity beginning in the mid-8th century and by the close of the 10th century Zanzibar was one of the central Swahili trading towns.<ref>Horton, Mark and Middleton, Tom. \"The Swahili: The Social Landscape of a Mercantile Community.\" (Oxford: Blackwell, 2010), 46.</ref>\n\nExcavations at nearby Pemba Island, but especially at Shanga in the Lamu Archipelago, provide the clearest picture of architectural development. Houses were originally built with timber (c. 1050) and later in mud with coral walls (c. 1150). The houses were continually rebuilt with more permanent materials. By the 13th century, houses were built with stone, and bonded with mud, and the 14th century saw the use of lime to bond stone. Only the wealthier patricians would have had stone and lime built houses, the strength of the materials allowing for flat roofs, while the majority of the population lived in single-story thatched houses similar to those from the 11th and 12th centuries. According to John Middleton and Mark Horton, the architectural style of these stone houses have no Arab or Persian elements, and should be viewed as an entirely indigenous development of local vernacular architecture. While much of Zanzibar Town's architecture was rebuilt during Omani rule, nearby sites elucidate the general development of Swahili, and Zanzibari, architecture before the 15th century.<ref>Horton, Mark and Middleton, John. \"The Swahili: The Social Landscape of a Mercantile Community.\" (Oxford: Blackwell, 2010), 119.</ref>\n\nPersian, Indian, and Arab traders used Zanzibar as a base for voyages between the Middle East, India, and Africa. Unguja, the larger island, offered a protected and defensible harbor, so although the archipelago offered few products of value, traders settled at [[Zanzibar City]] (\"[[Stone Town]]\") a convenient point from which to trade with the other [[Swahili coast]] towns.\n\nThe impact of these traders and immigrants on the [[Swahili culture]] is uncertain. During the [[Middle Ages]], Zanzibar and other settlements on the Swahili Coast were advanced. The littoral contained a number of autonomous trade cities. These towns grew in wealth as the [[Swahili people]] served as intermediaries and facilitators to local, inland mainland African, Arab, Persian, Indonesian, Malaysian, Indian, and Chinese merchants and traders.<ref>Kusimba, Chapurukha. \"The Rise and Decline of Swahili States.\" (Walnut Creek, California: Altamira, 1999).</ref> This interaction contributed in part to the evolution of the [[Swahili culture]], which developed its own written language. Although a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]], the [[Swahili language]] as a consequence today includes some elements that were borrowed from other civilizations, particularly [[loanword]]s from [[Arabic]]. With the wealth that they had acquired through trade, some of the Arab traders also became rulers of the coastal cities.<ref>[http://endingstereotypes.org/african_history.html The Swahili, African History, ''Ending Stereotypes for America''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130904200204/http://endingstereotypes.org/african_history.html |date=4 September 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Portuguese colonization===\n[[Vasco da Gama]]'s visit in 1498 marked the beginning of European influence. In 1503 or 1504, Zanzibar became part of the [[Portuguese Empire]] when Captain Ruy Louren\u00e7o Ravasco Marques landed and demanded and received tribute from the sultan{{who|date=March 2020}} in exchange for peace.<ref name=\"Ingrams\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oYhrCkGaxyUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Zanzibar: Its History and Its People|first=W. H.|last=Ingrams|date=1 June 1967|publisher=Psychology Press|accessdate=12 March 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780714611020}}</ref>{{rp|page: 99}} Zanzibar remained a possession of Portugal for almost two centuries. It initially became part of the Portuguese province of Arabia and Ethiopia and was administered by a governor general. Around 1571, Zanzibar became part of the western division of the Portuguese empire and was administered from Mozambique.<ref name=\"Eliot\"/>{{rp|page: 15}} It appears, however, that the Portuguese did not closely administer Zanzibar. The first English ship to visit Unguja, the ''Edward Bonaventure'' in 1591, found that there was no Portuguese fort or garrison. The extent of their occupation was a trade depot where produce was purchased and collected for shipment to Mozambique. \"In other respects, the affairs of the island were managed by the local 'king', the predecessor of the Mwinyi Mkuu of Dunga.\"<ref name=\"Pearce\"/>{{rp|page: 81}} This hands-off approach ended when Portugal established a fort on Pemba Island around 1635 in response to the Sultan of [[Mombasa]]'s slaughter of Portuguese residents several years earlier. Portugal had long considered Pemba to be a troublesome launching point for rebellions in Mombasa against Portuguese rule.<ref name=\"Pearce\"/>{{rp|page: 85}}\n\nThe precise origins of the sultans of Unguja are uncertain. However, their capital at [[Unguja Ukuu]] is believed to have been an extensive town. Possibly constructed by locals, it was composed mainly of perishable materials.<ref name=\"Pearce\"/>{{rp|page: 89}}\n\n=== Sultanate of Zanzibar ===\n{{Main|Sultanate of Zanzibar}}\n[[File:The old castle in Zanzibar.JPG|thumb|right|250px|The castle in Zanzibar]]\n[[File:The Harem and Tower Harbour of Zanzibar (p.234, 1890) - Copy.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Harem and Tower Harbour of Zanzibar (p.234), London Missionary Society<ref name=LMS>{{cite journal|title=The Harem and Tower Harbour of Zanzibar|journal=Chronicles of the London Missionary Society|date=1890|url=https://archive.org/details/chroniclelondon00unkngoog|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>]]\n\nThe Portuguese arrived in East Africa in 1498, where they found a series of independent towns on the coast, with Muslim Arabic-speaking elites. While the Portuguese travelers describe them as 'black' they made a clear distinction between the Muslim and non-Muslim populations.<ref>Prestholdt, Jeremy. \"Portuguese Conceptual Categories and the \u201cOther\u201d Encounter on the Swahili Coast.\" Journal of Asian American Studies, Volume 36, Issue 4, 390.</ref> Their relations with these leaders were mostly hostile, but during the sixteenth century they firmly established their power, and ruled with the aid of tributary sultans. The Portuguese presence was relatively limited, leaving administration in the hands of preexisting local leaders and power structures. This system lasted until 1631, when the Sultan of Mombasa massacred the Portuguese inhabitants. For the remainder of their rule, the Portuguese appointed European governors. The strangling of trade and diminished local power led the Swahili elites in Mombasa and Zanzibar to invite Omani aristocrats to assist them in driving the Europeans out.<ref name=\"Eliot\">Sir Charles Eliot, K.C.M.G., [https://archive.org/details/eastafricaprotec00eliouoft ''The East Africa Protectorate''], London: Edward Arnold, 1905, digitized by the Internet Archive in 2008 ([[PDF]] format).</ref>{{rp|page: 9}}\n\nIn 1698, Zanzibar came under the influence of the [[Oman|Sultanate of Oman]].<ref>N. S. Kharusi, [http://etn.sagepub.com/content/12/3/335 \"The ethnic label Zinjibari: Politics and language choice implications among Swahili speakers in Oman\"], ''Ethnicities'', 12(3) 335\u2013353, 2012.</ref> There was a [[Oman\u2013Zanzibar war|brief revolt]] against Omani rule in 1784. Local elites invited Omani merchant princes to settle on Zanzibar in the first half of the nineteenth century, preferring them to the Portuguese. Many locals today continue to emphasize that indigenous Zanzibaris had invited [[Seyyid Said]], the first Busaidi sultan, to their island,{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} claiming a patron-client relationship with powerful families was a strategy used by many Swahili coast towns since at least the fifteenth century.<ref>Meier, Prita. \"Swahili Port Cities: The Architecture of Elsewhere.\" (Bloomington Indiana: Indiana University press, 2016) Pg. 103.</ref>\n\n[[File:The narrow alley in the stone city of Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|A narrow pedestrian alleyway in [[Stone Town]], Zanzibar.]]\nIn 1832,<ref name=\"Ingrams\"/>{{rp|page: 162}} or 1840<ref name=\"Appiah\">{{citation|editor1-last=Appiah|editor2-last=Gates|editor1-link=Kwame Anthony Appiah|editor2-first=Henry Louis Jr.|editor2-link=Henry Louis Gates, Jr.|year=1999|title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|location=[[New York City|New York]]|isbn=0-465-00071-1|oclc=41649745|url=https://archive.org/details/africanaencyclop00appi}}</ref>{{rp|page: 2,045}} (the date varies among sources), [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman]] moved his capital from [[Muscat, Oman]] to Stone Town. After Said's death in June 1856, two of his sons, [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini bin Said]] and [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]], struggled over the [[order of succession|succession]]. Said's will divided his dominions into two separate [[principality|principalities]], with Thuwaini to become the Sultan of Oman and Majid to become the first [[Sultan of Zanzibar]], the brothers quarreled about the will, which was eventually upheld by [[Charles Canning, 1st Earl Canning]], Great Britain's [[Governor-General of India|Viceroy and Governor-General of India]].<ref name=\"Ingrams\"/>{{rp|pages: 163\u20134}}<ref name=\"Eliot\"/>{{rp|pages: 22\u20133}}\n\n[[File:Zanzslgwch.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Zanj]] slave gang in Zanzibar (1889)]]\nUntil around 1890, the sultans of Zanzibar controlled a substantial portion of the Swahili coast known as [[Zanj]], which included Mombasa and [[Dar es Salaam]]. Beginning in 1886, Great Britain and Germany plotted to obtain parts of the Zanzibar sultanate for their own empires.<ref name=\"Appiah\"/>{{rp|page: 188}}\nIn October 1886, a British-German border commission established the Zanj as a {{convert|10|nmi|km|adj=mid|-wide}} strip along most of the [[African Great Lakes]] region's coast, an area stretching from [[Cape Delgado]] (now in [[Mozambique]]) to [[Kipini]] (now in [[Kenya]]), including Mombasa and Dar es Salaam. Over the next few years, however, almost all of these mainland possessions were lost to European imperial powers.\n\nThe sultans developed an economy of trade and [[cash crop]]s in the Zanzibar Archipelago with a ruling Arab elite. [[Ivory]] was a major trade good. The archipelago, sometimes referred to by locals as the Spice Islands, was famous worldwide for its cloves and other spices, and plantations were developed to grow them. The archipelago's commerce gradually fell into the hands of traders from the [[Indian subcontinent]], whom Said bin Sultan encouraged to settle on the islands.\n\nDuring his 14-year reign as sultan, Majid bin Said consolidated his power around the [[Arab slave trade]]. Malindi in Zanzibar City was the Swahili Coast's main port for the slave trade with the Middle East. In the mid-19th century, as many as 50,000 slaves passed annually through the port.\n{{quote|Many were captives of [[Tippu Tip|Tippu Tib]], a notorious Arab slave trader and ivory merchant. Tib led huge expeditions, some 4,000 strong, into the African interior, where chiefs sold him their villagers for next to nothing. These Tib used to caravan ivory back to Zanzibar, then sold them in the slave market for large profits. In time Tib became one of the wealthiest men in Zanzibar, the owner of multiple plantations and 10,000 slaves.<ref>[http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/data/2001/10/01/html/ft_20011001.6.html \"Swahili Coast: East Africa's Ancient Crossroads\", in a \"Did You Know?\"] sidebar by Christy Ullrich, ''National Geographic''.</ref>}}\n\nOne of Majid's brothers, [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash bin Said]], succeeded him and was forced to abolish the slave trade in the Zanzibar Archipelago by the British. He largely developed Unguja's infrastructure.<ref>{{citation|last=Michler|first=Ian|title=Zanzibar: The Insider's Guide|publisher=Struik Publishers|location=Cape Town|year=2007|edition=2nd|page=137|isbn=978-1-77007-014-1|oclc=165410708}}</ref> Another brother of Majid, [[Khalifah bin Said of Zanzibar|Khalifa bin Said]], was the third sultan of Zanzibar and furthered the relationship with the British which led to the archipelago's progress toward abolishing slavery.<ref name=\"Ingrams\"/>{{rp|page: 172}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== British protectorate ===\n[[File:Monument to Slaves.jpg|Monument to the [[slave]]s in Zanzibar|200px|thumb]]\n\nControl of Zanzibar eventually came into the hands of the [[British Empire]]; part of the political impetus for this was the 19th century movement for the [[Abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolition of the slave trade]]. Zanzibar was the centre of the [[Arab slave trade]], and in 1822, the British [[consul]] in Muscat put pressure on Sultan Said to end the slave trade. The first of a series of anti-slavery treaties with Britain was signed by Said which prohibited slave transport south and east of the [[Moresby Treaty|Moresby Line]], from Cape Delgado in Africa to Diu Head on the coast of India.<ref name=\"McIntyre\">Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013). \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p. 10.</ref> Said lost the revenue he would have received as duty on all slaves sold, so to make up for this shortfall he encouraged the development of the slave trade in Zanzibar itself.<ref name=\"McIntyre\"/> Said came under increasing pressure from the British to abolish slavery, and in 1842 the British government told the Zanzibari ruler it wished to abolish the slave trade to Arabia, Oman, Persia, and the Red Sea.<ref>Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013), \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p.13.</ref>\n\n[[File:Zanzibar stamp.png|thumb|The post office in Zanzibar was initially managed by the postal service of British India. Before dedicated Zanzibar stamps could be manufactured, Indian stamps were locally overprinted. This item is from a pre-printed Indian envelope or postcard, overprinted at the offices of the Zanzibar Gazette, which had the only printing press in the territory.]]\n\nShips from the [[Royal Navy]] were employed to enforce the anti-slavery treaties by capturing any [[dhow]]s carrying slaves, but with only four ships patrolling a huge area of sea, the British navy found it hard to enforce the treaties as ships from France, Spain, Portugal, and the United States continued to carry slaves.<ref>Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013), \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p. 14.</ref> In 1856, Sultan [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid]] consolidated his power around the [[African Great Lakes]] slave trade, and in 1873 Sir [[John Kirk (explorer)|John Kirk]] informed his successor, Sultan [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash]], that a total blockade of Zanzibar was imminent, and Barghash reluctantly signed the Anglo-Zanzibari treaty which abolished the slave trade in the sultan's territories, closed all slave markets and protected liberated slaves.<ref>Chris McIntyre, Susan McIntyre (2013). \"Zanzibar\", Bradt Travel Guides, p. 19.</ref>\n\nThe relationship between Britain and the [[German Empire]], at that time the nearest relevant colonial power, was formalized by the 1890 [[Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty]], in which Germany agreed to \"recognize the British protectorate over ... the islands of Zanzibar and Pemba\".<ref>[http://germanhistorydocs.ghi-dc.org/pdf/eng/606_Anglo-German%20Treaty_110.pdf Article XI, Anglo-German Treaty (Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty)], 1 July 1890 ([[PDF]] format).</ref>\n[[File:Zanzibar 1900 to 1920.jpg|thumb|A street scene in Zanzibar during the early 20th century]]\nIn 1890 Zanzibar became a [[protectorate]] (not a colony) of Britain. This status meant it continued to be under the sovereignty of the [[Sultan of Zanzibar]]. [[British Prime Minister]] [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|Salisbury]] explained his position:\n:The condition of a protected dependency is more acceptable to the half civilised races, and more suitable for them than direct dominion.  It is cheaper, simpler, less wounding to their self-esteem, gives them more career as public officials, and spares of unnecessary contact with white men.<ref>Andrew Roberts, ''Salisbury: Victorian Titan'' (1999) p 529</ref>\n\nFrom 1890 to 1913, traditional [[viziers]] were in charge; they were supervised by advisors appointed by the Colonial Office.  However, in 1913 a switch was made to a system of direct rule through residents (effectively governors) from 1913.  The death of the pro-British [[Sultan]] [[Hamad bin Thuwaini]] on 25 August 1896 and the succession of Sultan [[Khalid bin Barghash of Zanzibar|Khalid bin Barghash]], whom the British did not approve of, led to the [[Anglo-Zanzibar War]]. On the morning of 27 August 1896, ships of the [[Royal Navy]] destroyed the Beit al Hukum Palace. A [[cease fire]] was declared 38&nbsp;minutes later, and to this day the bombardment stands as the shortest war in history.<ref>{{cite book|author=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldre000guin|title=Guinness World Records 2008|date=7 August 2007|publisher=Guinness World Records|isbn=978-1-904994-19-0|editor-last=Craig Glenday|edition=|location=London|page=[https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldre000guin/page/118 118]|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n===Zanzibar revolution and merger with Tanganyika===\n{{main|Zanzibar Revolution}}\n[[File:Abeid Karume 1964.jpg|thumb|upright|President [[Abeid Karume]]]]\n\nOn 10 December 1963,<ref>Zanzibar Act 1963 of the United Kingdom - Note that the title of this Act was not the Zanzibar Independence Act because the UK was not conferring independence as it did not have sovereignty; it was ending the Protectorate over that territory and providing for its fully responsible government</ref> the Protectorate that had existed over Zanzibar since 1890 was terminated by the United Kingdom. The United Kingdom did not grant Zanzibar independence, as such, because the UK had never had sovereignty over Zanzibar. Rather, by the Zanzibar Act 1963 of the United Kingdom, the UK ended the Protectorate and made provision for full self-government in Zanzibar as an independent country within the Commonwealth. Upon the Protectorate being abolished, Zanzibar became a [[constitutional monarchy]] under the Sultan.<ref name=\"DeptofStatep986\">{{Harvnb|United States Department of State|1975|p=986}}</ref>\n\nHowever, just a month later, on 12 January 1964 Sultan [[Jamshid bin Abdullah of Zanzibar|Jamshid bin Abdullah]] was [[deposition (politics)|deposed]] during the [[Zanzibar Revolution]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Ayany|1970|p=122}}</ref> The Sultan fled into exile, and the Sultanate was replaced by the [[People's Republic of Zanzibar and Pemba]], a [[State socialism|socialist government]] led by the [[Afro-Shirazi Party]] (ASP). Over 20,000 people were killed and refugees, especially Arabs and Indians, escaped the island as a consequence of the revolution.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The forgotten genocide of the Zanzibar revolution - Speak Magazine|url = http://speakjhr.com/2014/01/forgotten-genocide-zanzibar-revolution/|website = Speak Magazine|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1964, the republic merged with mainland [[Tanganyika]]. This United Republic of Tanganyika and Zanzibar was soon renamed, [[blend word|blend]]ing the two names, as the United Republic of [[Tanzania]], within which Zanzibar remains a semi-autonomous region.\n\n== Demography==\n[[File:Zanzibar Stone Town11.jpg|thumb|A street scene in Stone Town]]\n[[File:Zanzibar Stone Town02.jpg|thumb|Produce vendors at a market]]\n\nThe 2002 census is the most recent census for which results have been reported. The total population of Zanzibar was 984,625<ref name=\"2002 Census Zanzibar S\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/south_unguja.htm|title=2002 Population and Housing General Report: South Unguja|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040318024855/http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/south_unguja.htm|archivedate=18 March 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref> \u2013 with an annual growth rate of 3.1 percent.<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zanzibar-travel-guide.com/bradt_guide.asp?bradt=1844 |title=People and Culture \u2013 Zanzibar Travel Guide |publisher=Zanzibar-travel-guide.com |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref> The population of [[Zanzibar City]], which was the largest city, was 205,870.<ref name=guide/>\n\nAround two thirds of the people, 622,459, lived on [[Unguja]] (Zanzibar Island), with most settled in the densely populated west. Besides Zanzibar City, other towns on Unguja include [[Chaani, Tanzania|Chaani]], [[Mbweni, Zanzibar|Mbweni]], [[Mangapwani]], [[Chwaka]], and [[Nungwi]]. Outside of these towns, most people live in small villages and are engaged in farming or fishing.<ref name=guide/>\n\nThe population of [[Pemba Island]] was 362,166.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/districts/pemba.htm|title=2002 Population and Housing Census General Report: Pemba|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610161809/http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/pemba.htm|archivedate=10 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The largest town on the island was [[Chake-Chake]], with a population of 19,283. The smaller towns are [[Wete]] and [[Mkoani]].<ref name=guide/>\n\n[[Mafia Island]], the other major island of the Zanzibar Archipelago but administered by mainland Tanzania (Tanganyka), had a total population of 40,801.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/districts/mafia.htm|title=2002 Population and Housing Census General Report: Mafia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610180829/http://www.tanzania.go.tz/census/census/districts/mafia.htm|archivedate=10 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Census\n!Population<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Tanzania-Cities.html|title=Tanzania: Regions and Cities - Population Statistics in Maps and Charts|website=www.citypopulation.de|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|1978\n|476,111\n|-\n|1988\n|640,685\n|-\n|2002\n|981,754\n|-\n|2012\n|1,303,569\n|}\n\n=== Ethnic origins ===\nThe people of Zanzibar are of diverse ethnic origins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/people/people.html |title=Zanzibar People and Culture |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045310/http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/people/people.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first permanent residents of Zanzibar seem to have been the ancestors of the [[Bantus|Bantu]] [[Hadimu]] and [[Tumbatu]], who began arriving from the [[African Great Lakes]] mainland around AD 1000. They belonged to various mainland ethnic groups and on Zanzibar, generally lived in small villages. They did not coalesce to form larger political units.\n\nDuring Zanzibar's brief period of independence in the early 1960s, the major political cleavage was between the [[Shirazi people|Shirazi]] (Zanzibar Africans), who made up approximately 56% of the population, and the Zanzibar Arabs, who made up approximately 17%.<ref name=growup1>{{cite web |author=GROWup - Geographical Research On War, Unified Platform |title=Ethnicity in Zanzibar |url=https://growup.ethz.ch/atlas/Zanzibar |publisher=ETH Zurich |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=growup2>{{cite journal |author=Sheriff, Abdul |title=Race and Class in the Politics of Zanzibar |journal=Africa Spectrum |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=301\u2013318 |jstor=40174901 |year=2001 }}</ref> Today, Zanzibar is inhabited mostly by ethnic [[Swahili people|Swahili]], a [[Bantu peoples|Bantu]] population of sub-Saharan Africans.<ref name=\"guide\"/> There are also a number of [[Arabs]], as well as some ethnic [[Persian people|Persian]] and [[Indian diaspora in Southeast Africa|Indian]] people.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/outofdate/bgn/tanzania/127939.htm Tanzania (08/09)] . U.S. Department of State.</ref>\n\n=== Languages ===\nZanzibaris speak [[Swahili language|Swahili]] (Kiswahili), a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]] that is extensively spoken in the [[African Great Lakes]] region. Swahili is the de facto [[National language|national]] and [[official language]] of Tanzania. Many local residents also speak [[Arabic]], [[French language|French]] and/or [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref>Chris McIntyre and Susan McIntyre, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zlqv0gSkk-kC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=purest+form+of+swahili+zanzibar&source=bl&ots=mO3h6Xd7Ao&sig=yPmOLFlSPZC44LfT6c_vyOKooKw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fRvPUOHFM67piwLy6YD4Bg&ved=0CGgQ6AEwCg#v=onepage&q=purest%20form%20of%20swahili%20zanzibar&f=false \"Zanzibar, Pemba, and Mafia\"], ''Bradt Travel Guide'', 2009, p. 36.</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\n{{See also|Islam in Zanzibar}}\n[[File:The mosque and church are located closely in the stone city of Zanzibar.jpg|left|100px|thumb|The main mosque and Anglican cathedral in [[Stone Town]]]]\n{{Bar box\n| title=Zanzibar Religions (2010 est.)\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| float=right\n| bars=\n{{Bar percent|Islam|green|98.9}}\n{{Bar percent|Christianity|blue|0.6}}\n{{Bar percent|Indigenous|brown|0.5}}\n|caption=Source: [[CIA World Factbook]].<ref name=\"cia.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tz.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nZanzibar's population is almost entirely Muslim, with a small Christian minority containing around 22 000 Christians.<ref name=\"cia.gov\"/> Other religious groups that are represented include [[Hindus]], [[Jainism|Jains]] and [[Sikhs]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keshodkar|first=Akbar|date=2010-03-29|title=Marriage as the Means to Preserve 'Asian-ness': The Post-Revolutionary Experience of the Asians of Zanzibar|journal=Journal of Asian and African Studies|volume=45|issue=2|pages=226\u2013240|doi=10.1177/0021909609357418|issn=0021-9096}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Anglican Diocese of Zanzibar]] was founded in 1892. The first Bishop of Zanzibar was [[Charles Smythies]], who was translated from his former post as Bishop of [[Nyasaland]]. The cathedral, located in [[Stone Town]], Zanzibar City, is a prominent landmark, and a national heritage asset.\n\nIt had fallen into poor condition by the late 20th century, but it was fully restored in 2016, at a cost of one million Euros, with a world heritage visitor centre. The restoration was supported by the Tanzanian and Zanzibari governments, and overseen by the diocese in partnership with the [[World Monuments Fund]].<ref>Progress report and photographs at [http://www.zanzibaranglican.or.tz/progress-update/ this] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628101223/http://www.zanzibaranglican.or.tz/progress-update/ |date=28 June 2017 }} webpage.</ref> The restoration of the spire, clock, and historic [[Henry Willis & Sons|Willis]] organ are still outstanding. Historically the diocese included mainland locations in [[Tanganyika]]. In 1963 it was renamed as the Diocese of Zanzibar & Dar es Salaam. Two years later, in 1965, Dar es Salaam became a separate diocese. The original jurisdiction was renamed as the Diocese of Zanzibar & Tanga. In 2001 the mainland links were finally ended, and it is now known as the Diocese of Zanzibar. The diocese includes parishioners on the neighbouring island of [[Pemba Island|Pemba]]. Ten bishops have served in the diocese from 1892 to the present day. The bishop is [[Michael Hafidh]]. It is part of the Province of Tanzania, under the Archbishop of All Tanzania, based at Dodoma.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Zanzibar]] was established in 1980. An apostolic vicariate of Zanzibar had been established in 1906, from a much larger East African jurisdiction. This was suppressed in 1953, when the territory was out under control of the Kenyan church, but it was restored in 1964 after independence. The church created a diocese here shortly before Easter 1980. The bishop is [[Augustine Ndeliakyama Shao]]. Zanzibar is part of the Roman Catholic Province of Dar es Salaam, under the Archbishop of Dar es Salaam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daressalaamarchdiocese.or.tz/en/historical-background/|title=Historical Background|last=|first=|date=|website=Dar es Salaam Archdiocese|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther Christian denominations include the Evangelical Lutheran Church of Tanzania which arrived in Zanzibar town in the 1960s,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Lutheran Church on the coast of Tanzania, 1887-1914 : with special reference to the Evangelical Lutheran Church in Tanzania, Synod of Uzaramo-Uluguru|last=Sicard, Sigvard von.|date=1970|publisher=Gleerup|oclc=1100148145}}</ref> and a wide range of Pentecostal-Charismatic Christian churches such as the Tanzania Assemblies of God, the Free Pentecostal Church of Tanzania, the Evangelical Assemblies of God, the Pentecostal Church of Tanzania, the Victory Church and the Pentecostal Evangelistic Fellowship of Africa. Pentecostal-Charismatic churches have been present and growing in Zanzibar since the 1980s in relation to economic liberalization and increased labor migration from mainland Tanzania in connection to Zanzibar's expanding tourist sector. There are also [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh Day Adventist]] and [[Baptists|Baptist]] churches.<ref>{{Citation|last=Olsson|first=Hans|chapter=Narratives of Pentecostal (Non-)Belonging|date=2019-07-04|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-40681-0|doi=10.1163/9789004410367_008|title=Jesus for Zanzibar: Narratives of Pentecostal (Non-)Belonging, Islam, and Nation}}</ref> \n\nSince 2005 there is also an inter-religious body called the Joint Committee of Religious Leaders for Peace (in Swahili ''Juhudi za Viongozi wa Dini kuimarisha Amani'') with representatives from Muslim institutions such as the Islamic law (''Kadhi'' courts), religious property (the ''Wakf'' and Trust commission), education (the Muslim academy) and the ''[[Mufti]]''\u2019s office as well as representatives from the Roman Catholic, the Anglican and the Lutheran church.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Peace in Zanzibar|last=Lang\u00e5s|first=Arngeir|date=2019-04-12|publisher=Peter Lang US|isbn=978-1-4331-5969-5|doi=10.3726/b14434}}</ref> \n----\n\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Government ==\n{{Politics of Tanzania}}\nAs a semi-autonomous part of [[Tanzania]], Zanzibar has its own government, known as the [[Revolutionary Government of Zanzibar]]. It is made up of the [[Revolutionary Council (Zanzibar)|Revolutionary Council]] and [[House of Representatives of Zanzibar|House of Representatives]].\nThe House of Representatives has a similar composition to the [[National Assembly of Tanzania]]. Fifty members are elected directly from constituencies to serve five-year terms; 10 members are appointed by the [[President of Zanzibar]]; 15 special seats are for women members of political parties that have representation in the House of Representatives; six members serve ''[[ex officio member|ex officio]]'', including all regional commissioners and the attorney general.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zanzibarassembly.go.tz/composition.html |title=Composition |publisher=The House of Representatives - Zanzibar |accessdate=23 October 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Five of these 81 members are then elected to represent Zanzibar in the National Assembly.<ref>[http://www.parliament.go.tz/index.php/home/pages/6 Composition, Parliament of Tanzania] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021211837/http://www.parliament.go.tz/index.php/home/pages/6 |date=21 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nUnguja has three administrative regions: [[Zanzibar Central/South]], [[Zanzibar North]] and [[Zanzibar Urban/West]]. Pemba has two: [[Pemba North]] and [[Pemba South]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statoids.com/utz.html|title=Tanzania Regions|website=www.statoids.com|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the independence and sovereignty of Zanzibar, Tanzania Prime Minister [[Mizengo Pinda]] said on 3 July 2008 that there was \"nothing like the sovereignty of Zanzibar in the Union Government unless the Constitution is changed in future\". Zanzibar House of Representatives members from both the ruling party, [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]], and the opposition party, [[Civic United Front]], disagreed and stood firmly in recognizing Zanzibar as a fully autonomous state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unpo.org/article/8392 |title=Zanzibar: Premier under fire on Zanzibar status |date=10 July 2008 |publisher=Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization |accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\n{{see also|Zanzibar independence movement}}\n[[File:12 Jan. 2004, festivities at 40th anniversary of the Zanzibar Revolution. President Karume enters Amani Stadium in ceremonial Hummer.JPG|thumb|180px|left|12 Jan 2004: President Karume of Zanzibar enters Amani Stadium for the celebration of the 40th anniversary of Zanzibar's 1964 revolution]]\n\nZanzibar has a government of national unity, with the president of Zanzibar being [[Ali Mohamed Shein]], since 1 November 2010. There are many political parties in Zanzibar, but the most popular parties are the [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] (CCM) and the [[Civic United Front]] (CUF). Since the early 1990s, the politics of the archipelago have been marked by repeated clashes between these two parties.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nContested elections in October 2000 led to a massacre on 27 January 2001 when, according to [[Human Rights Watch]], the army and police shot into crowds of protestors, killing at least 35 and wounding more than 600. Those forces, accompanied by ruling party officials and militias, also went on a house-to-house rampage, indiscriminately arresting, beating, and sexually abusing residents. Approximately 2,000 temporarily fled to Kenya.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://hrw.org/english/docs/2002/04/10/tanzan3838.htm |title=Tanzania: Zanzibar Election Massacres Documented |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=10 April 2002 |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nViolence erupted again after [[Tanzanian general election, 2005|another contested election]] on 31 October 2005, with the CUF claiming that its rightful victory had been stolen from it. Nine people were killed.<ref>[http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2002597738_webzanzibar01.html \"Nine killed in Zanzibar election violence\", ''Seattle Times'', reported by Chris Tomlinson, The Associated Press, 1 November 2005] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006165946/http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2002597738_webzanzibar01.html |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.karelprinsloo.com/#/works/zanzibar-election-violence-2005?i=386|title=Zimbabwe Farm Evictions 2000|website=karelprinsloo karel prinsloo}}</ref>\n\nFollowing 2005, negotiations between the two parties aiming at the long-term resolution of the tensions and a power-sharing accord took place, but they suffered repeated setbacks. The most notable of these took place in April 2008, when the CUF walked away from the negotiating table following a CCM call for a referendum to approve of what had been presented as a done deal on the power-sharing agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tzaffairs.org/2008/05/zanzibar-a-big-disappointment|title=Tanzanian Affairs \u00bb ZANZIBAR \u2013 A BIG DISAPPOINTMENT|website=www.tzaffairs.org|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, the then-president of Zanzibar, [[Amani Abeid Karume]], met with CUF secretary-general [[Seif Sharif Hamad]] at the State House to discuss how to save Zanzibar from future political turmoil and to end the animosity between them.<ref name=\"Karume\">[http://zirppo.wordpress.com/2009/11/19/karume-no-elections-next-year-in-zanzibar-if \"Karume: No elections next year in Zanzibar if\u2026\", Zanzibar Institute for Research and Public Policy, reported by Salma Said, reprinted from an original article in ''The Citizen'', 19 November 2009]</ref> This move was welcomed by many, including the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zanzibar-tanzania.usvpp.gov/ |title=Welcome to VPP Zanzibar, Tanzania |work=United States Virtual Presence Post |publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]] |accessdate=27 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203094450/http://zanzibar-tanzania.usvpp.gov/ |archive-date=3 February 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was the first time since the [[multi-party system]] was introduced in Zanzibar that the CUF agreed to recognize Karume as the legitimate president of Zanzibar.<ref name=\"Karume\"/>\n\nA proposal to amend Zanzibar's constitution to allow rival parties to form governments of national unity was adopted by 66.2 percent of voters on 31 July 2010.<ref>[http://www.eisa.org.za/WEP/zan2010referendum.htm \"Zanzibar: 2010 Constitutional referendum results\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105050420/https://eisa.org.za/wep/zan2010referendum.htm |date=5 January 2016 }}, Electoral Institute for the Sustainability of Democracy in Africa, updated August 2010.</ref>\n\nThe autonomous status of Zanzibar is viewed as comparable to [[Hong Kong]] as suggested by some scholars, and  being recognized as the \"African Hong Kong\".<ref>Simon Shen, ''One country, two systems: Zanaibar'', Ming Pao Weekly, Sep 2016.</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Geography ==\n{{Main|Zanzibar Archipelago}}\n[[File:Approaching Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|Coastline off Zanzibar]]\n[[File:A bird's view of the stone city in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|A bird's view of the stone city in Zanzibar]]\n\nZanzibar is one of the [[List of Indian Ocean islands|Indian Ocean islands]]. It is situated on the [[Swahili Coast]], adjacent to [[Tanganyika]] (mainland Tanzania).\n\nThe northern tip of Unguja island is located at 5.72 degrees south, 39.30 degrees east, with the southernmost point at 6.48 degrees south, 39.51 degrees east.<ref name=\"L&L\">{{cite web|url=http://www.findlatitudeandlongitude.com|title=Find Latitude and Longitude|website=www.findlatitudeandlongitude.com|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> The island is separated from the Tanzanian mainland by a channel, which at its narrowest point is {{convert|36.5|km|mi}} across.<ref name=\"Zanzinet\">[http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/visiwa.html Zanzibar Archipelago, Zanzinet Forum: Where Zanzibaris Meet] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223120539/http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/visiwa.html |date=23 December 2015 }}</ref> The island is about {{convert|85|km|mi}} long and {{convert|39|km|mi}} wide,<ref name=\"Zanzinet\"/> with an area of {{convert|1464|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Guide\">{{cite web |url= http://www.africaguide.com/country/zanzibar/ |title= The Africa Guide \u2013 Zanzibar |work=web page |publisher= africaguide.com |accessdate =26 October 2012}}</ref> Unguja is mainly low lying, with its highest point being {{convert|120|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"Guide\"/> Unguja is characterised by beautiful sandy beaches with fringing coral reefs.<ref name=\"Guide\"/> The reefs are rich in marine biodiversity.<ref>Molly Moynihan, [http://digitalcollections.sit.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1828&context=isp_collection \"Water Quality and Eutrophication: The Effects of Sewage Outfalls on Waters and Reefs Surrounding Stone Town, Zanzibar\"], Independent Study Project Collection, 2010, p. 8.</ref>\n\nThe northern tip of Pemba island is located at 4.87 degrees south, 39.68 degrees east, and the southernmost point is located at 5.47 degrees south, 39.72 degrees east.<ref name=\"L&L\"/> The island is separated from the Tanzanian mainland by a channel some {{convert|56|km|mi}} wide.<ref name=\"Zanzinet\"/> The island is about {{convert|67|km|mi}} long and {{convert|23|km|mi}} wide, with an area of {{convert|985|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Zanzinet\"/> Pemba is also mainly low lying, with its highest point being {{convert|95|m|ft}}.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/582817/Tanzania/37556/Zanzibar-and-Pemba \"Tanzania: Zanzibar and Pemba\", ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'']</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\n{{see also|Climate of Tanzania}}\nThe heat of summer (corresponding to the Northern Hemisphere winter) is often cooled by strong sea breezes associated with the [[northeast monsoon]] (known as ''Kaskazi'' in Kiswahili), particularly on the north and east coasts. Being near to the equator, the islands are warm year round. The rainfall regime is split into two main seasons, a primary maximum in March, April, and May in association with the [[southwest monsoon]] (known locally as ''Kusi'' in Kiswahili), and a secondary maximum in November and December.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/nature/hali_ya_hewa.html |title=Climate and Soils |work=Zanzinet Forum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006230003/http://www.zanzinet.org/zanzibar/nature/hali_ya_hewa.html |archivedate=2014-10-06}}</ref> The months in between receive less rain, with a minimum in July.\n\n{{Weather box|location = Zanzibar\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 90\n|Feb high F = 91\n|Mar high F = 91\n|Apr high F = 86\n|May high F = 84\n|Jun high F = 83\n|Jul high F = 82\n|Aug high F = 83\n|Sep high F = 84\n|Oct high F = 86\n|Nov high F = 89\n|Dec high F = 89\n|year high F = 87\n|Jan low F = 76\n|Feb low F = 76\n|Mar low F = 77\n|Apr low F = 77\n|May low F = 75\n|Jun low F = 74\n|Jul low F = 72\n|Aug low F = 72\n|Sep low F = 72\n|Oct low F = 73\n|Nov low F = 75\n|Dec low F = 76\n|year low F = 75\n|Jan precipitation inch = 2.3\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.6\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.8\n|Apr precipitation inch = 12.6\n|May precipitation inch = 11.4\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.1\n|Jul precipitation inch = 1.1\n|Aug precipitation inch = 1.2\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.6\n|Oct precipitation inch = 2.6\n|Nov precipitation inch = 6.7\n|Dec precipitation inch = 5.5\n|year precipitation inch = 55.5\n|source 1 = [[Weatherbase]]<ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web |url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=7836&refer=wikipedia |title =Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Zanzibar, Tanzania |publisher=[[Weatherbase]] |year=2011 |accessdate=24 November 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Wildlife ==\n{{Main|Wildlife of Zanzibar}}\n\n=== Unguja ===\n[[File:Dolphin leap.JPG|thumb|A dolphin in the Indian Ocean, off the coast of Zanzibar]]\n[[File:Papilio Demodocus Citrus Swallowtail Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Papilio demodocus]]'' in Zanzibar, Nungwi.]]\n\nThe main island of Zanzibar, [[Unguja]], has a fauna reflecting its connection to the African mainland during the [[last glacial period|last Ice Age]].<ref name=\"Pakenham1984\">{{Cite book|author = Pakenham, R. H. W. |year = 1984 |url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/14538645/The-Mammals-of-Zanzibar-and-Pemba |title = The Mammals of Zanzibar and Pemba Islands |location = Harpenden |publisher = privately printed |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Walsh2007\">{{Cite journal|author= Walsh, Martin T. |year=2007 |title= Island Subsistence: Hunting, Trapping and the Translocation of Wildlife in the Western Indian Ocean |journal= Azania |volume= 42 |pages= 83\u2013113 |url= https://www.scribd.com/doc/14444883/Island-Subsistence-Hunting-Trapping-and-the-Translocation-of-Wildlife-in-the-Western-Indian-Ocean/|accessdate=27 August 2010|doi=10.1080/00672700709480452}}</ref>\n\nEndemic mammals with continental relatives include the [[Zanzibar red colobus]] (''Procolobus kirkii''), one of Africa's rarest primates, with perhaps only 1,500 existing. Isolated on this island for at least 1,000 years, this colobus is recognized as a distinct species, with different coat patterns, calls, and food habits from related colobus species on the mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galenfrysinger.com/red_colobus.htm |title=Red Colobus |publisher=galenfrysinger.com |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref> The Zanzibar red colobus lives in a wide variety of drier areas of coastal thickets and coral rag scrub, as well as [[mangrove swamp]]s and agricultural areas. About one third of them live in and around [[Jozani Chwaka Bay National Park|Jozani Forest]]. The easiest place to see the colobus is farmland adjacent to the reserve. They are accustomed to people and the low vegetation means they come close to the ground.\n\nRare native animals include the [[Zanzibar leopard]],<ref name=\"InsideEdition 06-2018\"/><ref name=\"MysteriousUniverse 06-2018\"/> which is critically endangered, and the recently described [[Zanzibar servaline genet]]. There are no large wild animals in Unguja. Forested areas such as Jozani are inhabited by monkeys, bushpigs, small antelopes, [[African civet]]s, and, as shown by a [[camera trap]] in June 2018,<ref name=\"InsideEdition 06-2018\"/><ref name=\"MysteriousUniverse 06-2018\"/> the elusive leopard. Various species of mongoose can also be found on the island. There is a wide variety of birdlife and a large number of butterflies in rural areas.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Pemba ===\n[[Pemba Island]] is separated from Unguja island and the African continent by deep channels and has a correspondingly restricted fauna, reflecting its comparative isolation from the mainland.<ref name=Pakenham1984/><ref name=Walsh2007/> The island is home to the [[Pemba flying fox]].\n\n{{wide image|Zanzibar Panorama.jpg|1100px|A panorama of Stone Town taken from the Indian Ocean. Seen in the picture are the [[Palace Museum, Zanzibar|Sultan's palace]], [[House of Wonders]], [[Forodhani Gardens]], and [[St. Joseph's Cathedral, Zanzibar|St. Joseph's Cathedral]]}}\n\n== Standard of living and health ==\n[[File:Poster prevenzione.jpg|thumb|Prophylaxis poster in Zanzibar, 2008]]\nConsiderable disparities exist in the [[standard of living]] for inhabitants of Pemba and Unguja, as well as the disparity between urban and rural populations. The average annual income is US$250. About half the population lives below the poverty line.\n\nDespite a relatively high standard of primary health care and education, [[infant mortality]] in Zanzibar is 54 out of 1,000 live births, which is 10.0 percent lower than the rate in mainland Tanzania. The [[child mortality]] rate in Zanzibar is 73 out of 1,000 live births, which is 21.5 percent lower than the rate in mainland Tanzania.<ref>[http://www.measuredhs.com/pubs/pdf/FR243/FR243%5B24June2011%5D.pdf \"Tanzania Demographic and Health Survey 2010\", National Bureau of Statistics, Dar es Salaam, published April 2011, page 120] ([[PDF]] format).</ref>\n\nIt is estimated that 7% of children on Zanzibar have acute [[malnutrition]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dhsprogram.com/pubs/pdf/FR321/FR321.pdf |title=Tanzania Demographic and Health Survey and Malaria Indicator Survey 2015-2016 - Final Report |website=DHS Program |accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Life expectancy]] at birth is 57 years,<ref>\"Zanzibar: Social Protection Expenditure\nand Performance Review and Social Budget\", Social Security Department, International Labour Office, Geneva, Switzerland, January 2010, page 22</ref> which is significantly lower than the 2010 world average of 67.2.\n\nThe general prevalence of [[HIV/AIDS]] in the population of Zanzibar aged 15-64 is 0.5 percent, with the rate much higher in females (0.9 percent) than males (less than 0.1 percent).<ref>https://phia.icap.columbia.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/FINAL_THIS-2016-2017_Final-Report__06.21.19_for-web_TS.pdf</ref>\n\n== Environment ==\nThe northern part of the island presents elevated volumes of trash in the streets, beaches and the ocean\u2014mostly plastic bottles, other plastics and cigarette butts. There is indiscriminate dumping in residential areas. Medical equipment waste is a particular problem on the island.<ref>[http://www.ijcrar.com/special/1/Biubwa%20Ally,%20et%20al.pdf IJCRAR]</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Gift of the Ocean.jpg|thumb|Seaweed farming in [[Jambiani]]]]\n[[File:Aquakulturen Rotalgen Sansibar 1.jpg|thumb|[[Aquaculture]] of red algae ([[Eucheuma]]), Jambiani]]\n[[File:Low Tide (7886864976).jpg|thumb|Tourism is one of the main sectors of the economy]]\n[[File:Zanzibar Stone Town01.jpg|thumb|Market stall in Zanzibar's Stone Town]]\n\nAncient [[pottery]] implies trade routes with Zanzibar as far back as the time of the ancient [[Assyria]]ns. Traders from the [[Arabian Peninsula]], the [[Persian Gulf]] region of modern-day [[Iran]] (especially [[Shiraz]]), and [[west India]] probably visited Zanzibar as early as the 1st century. They used the [[monsoon]] winds to sail across the Indian Ocean to land at the sheltered harbor located on the site of present-day Zanzibar City.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe [[clove]], originating from the [[Moluccan Islands]] (today in Indonesia), was introduced in Zanzibar by the Omani sultans in the first half of the 19th century.<ref>Professor Trevor Marchand. [http://www.archaeologicaltrs.com/me_oman.html Oman & Zanzibar: The Sultans of Oman] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031092051/http://www.archaeologicaltrs.com/me_oman.html |date=31 October 2013 }}. Archaeological Tours.</ref> Zanzibar, mainly [[Pemba Island]], was once the world's leading clove producer,<ref name=\"LAtimes\">{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/24/world/fg-cloves24 |title=Zanzibar Loses Some of Its Spice |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |author= Sanders, Edmund |date=24 November 2005 |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref> but annual clove sales have plummeted by 80 percent since the 1970s. Zanzibar's clove industry has been crippled by a [[terms of trade|fast-moving global market]], international competition, and a hangover from Tanzania's failed experiment with [[African socialism|socialism]] in the 1960s and 1970s, when the government [[Export control|controlled clove prices and exports]]. Zanzibar now ranks a distant third with Indonesia supplying 75 percent of the world's cloves compared to Zanzibar's 7 percent.<ref name=\"LAtimes\"/>\n\nZanzibar exports spices, seaweed and fine [[raffia]]. Beside the Zanzibar State Trading Cooperation, Zanj Spice Limited, also known as 1001 Organic, is the biggest organic spice exporter in Zanzibar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wo der Bio-Pfeffer w\u00e4chst|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/race-to-feed-the-world/wie-ein-schweizer-jurist-auf-sansibar-bio-gewuerze-anbaut-15947684.html/|publisher=www.faz.net|accessdate=23 December 2018}}</ref> Zanzibar also has a large fishing and [[dugout (boat)|dugout]] canoe production. Tourism is a major foreign currency earner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zanzibar Then and Now|url=http://www.zanzibarholidays.co.uk/zanzibar-then-and-now/|publisher=www.zanzibarholidays.co.uk|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Government of Zanzibar legalized foreign exchange bureaux on the islands before mainland Tanzania moved to do so. The effect was to increase the availability of consumer commodities. The government has also established a free port area, which provides the following benefits: contribution to economic diversification by providing a window for free trade as well as stimulating the establishment of support services; administration of a regime that imports, exports, and warehouses general merchandise; adequate storage facilities and other infrastructure to cater for effective operation of trade; and creation of an efficient management system for effective re-exportation of goods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/2843.htm |title=Background Note: Tanzania |author=Bureau of African Affairs |date=8 June 2010 |publisher= [[U.S. Department of State]] |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe island's manufacturing sector is limited mainly to import substitution industries, such as cigarettes, shoes, and processed agricultural products. In 1992, the government designated two export-producing zones and encouraged the development of offshore financial services. Zanzibar still imports much of its staple requirements, petroleum products, and manufactured articles.{{cn|date=June 2019}}\n\nThere is also a possibility of oil availability in Zanzibar on the island of Pemba, and efforts have been made by the Tanzanian Government and Zanzibar revolutionary Government to exploit what could be one of the most significant discoveries in recent memory. Oil would help boost the economy of Zanzibar, but there have been disagreements about dividends between the Tanzanian mainland and Zanzibar, the latter claiming the oil should be excluded in Union matters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tzbusinessnews.com/zanzibar-oil-and-the-union/|title=Economy|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n[[File:Dolphin tour in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|Tourists in boat are chasing dolphins in the Indian Ocean near Zanzibar]]\nIn 2007, a [[Norway|Norwegian]] consultancy firm went to Zanzibar to determine how the region could develop its [[oil]] potential.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecitizen.co.tz/newe.php?id=10276 |publisher=thecitizen.co.tz |accessdate=11 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502194550/http://thecitizen.co.tz/newe.php?id=10276 |archivedate=2 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The firm recommended that Zanzibar follow economist [[Hernando de Soto Polar]]'s ideas about the formalization of property rights for persons living on ancestral land for which they probably do not have a legal [[deed]].<ref name=\"Battle\">Chambi Chachage, [http://www.africanexecutive.com/modules/magazine/article_print.php?article=4864 \"Norway in Tanzania: The Battle Rages\"]{{Better source|reason=This poorly written opinion piece appears to be the only source on the internet for what would be quite an interesting development|date=November 2014}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053229/http://www.africanexecutive.com/modules/magazine/article_print.php?article=4864 |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''The African Executive''.</ref>\n\n=== Tourism ===\n{{Main|Tourism in Zanzibar}}\n\nIn 1984, fewer than 20,000 tourists visited Zanzibar. Five times more visitors travelled to the island in 2000. The events of [[September 11, 2001]] reduced the inflow of tourists, which was restored only after 2004. Zanzibar has at least 6,200 beds across six classes of accommodation. However, there is a disproportionately large number in ungraded, one and two star categories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanzaniainvest.com/telecoms/zanzibar-tourism-sector-profile|title=Tanzania Invest - Zanzibar Tourism Sector|last=|first=|date=9 January 2006|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Energy ===\nThe energy sector in Zanzibar consists of unreliable electric power, petroleum and petroleum products; it is also supplemented by firewood and its related products. Coal and gas are rarely used for either domestic and industrial purposes.\n\nUnguja (Zanzibar Island) gets most of its electric power from mainland Tanzania through a 39-kilometer, 100-megawatt submarine cable from Ras Kiromoni (near Dar es Salaam) to Ras Fumba on Unguja. The laying of the cable was begun on 10 October 2012 by the [[Viscas Corporation]] of Japan and was funded by a US$28.1 million grant from the United States through the [[Millennium Challenge Corporation]].<ref>[http://tanzania.usembassy.gov/pr_10102012c.html \"Ambassador Lenhardt Participates in Ceremony to Install 100 Megawatt Submarine Power to Zanzibar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217123714/http://tanzania.usembassy.gov/pr_10102012c.html |date=17 February 2013 }}. Press Release, Embassy of the United States, Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 10 October 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.salem.co.tz/projects/data?project=229&featured=1 132kV Sabmarine Cable - Zanzibar Iterconnector at Ras Kiromoni and Ras Fumba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728124453/http://salem.co.tz/projects/data?project=229&featured=1 |date=28 July 2013 }}, Featured Project, Salem Construction, Ltd.</ref> The cable became operational on 13 April 2013.<ref>Yussuf, Issa (24 April 2013). [http://allafrica.com/stories/201304240892.html \"Tanzania: Reliable Power to Accelerate Development in Isles President Ali\"].  ''[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]]'' (via [[AllAfrica.com]]).  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> The previous 45-megawatt cable, which was seldom-maintained, was completed by Norway in 1980.<ref>[http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08DARESSALAAM839 \"Zanzibar Power: Electrical And Political Shortages\", Cable from the United States Embassy in Dar Es Salaam to the United States Secretary of State] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502223345/http://www.cablegatesearch.net/cable.php?id=08DARESSALAAM839 |date=2 May 2013 }}, reference identification 08DARESSALAAM839, 15 December 2008.</ref>\n\nSince May 2010, Pemba Island has had a 75-kilometer, 25-megawatt, subsea electrical link directly to mainland Tanzania. The cable project was financed through a 45 million euro grant from Norway and contributions of 8 million euros from the Zanzibar government and 4 million euros from the Tanzanian national government. The project ended years of dependence on unreliable and erratic diesel generation subject to frequent power cuts. Only about 20 percent of the cable's capacity was being used in January 2011, so it is anticipated that the cable will meet the island's needs for 20 to 25 years.<ref>Press release (3 June 2010). [http://www.nexans.com/eservice/Corporate-en/navigatepub_0_-25837/Nexans_completes_subsea_cable_link_to_provide_reli.html \"Nexans Completes Subsea Cable Link to Provide Reliable Power for Pemba Island in Zanzibar{{spaced ndash}} New 25 MVA Link to Mainland Grid Has Enabled the Local Population to End Years of Dependence on Unreliable Diesel Generators\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505225414/http://www.nexans.com/eservice/Corporate-en/navigatepub_0_-25837/Nexans_completes_subsea_cable_link_to_provide_reli.html |date=5 May 2013 }}. [[Nexans]].  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.norway.go.tz/News_and_events/Energy/Reliable-electricity-attracts-investors-to-Pemba \"Reliable electricity attracts investors to Pemba\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822050718/http://www.norway.go.tz/News_and_events/Energy/Reliable-electricity-attracts-investors-to-Pemba/ |date=22 August 2011 }}, Norway: The Official Site in Tanzania, 28 January 2011.</ref>\n\nBetween 70 and 75 percent of the electricity generated is used domestically while less than 20 percent is used industrially. Fuel wood, charcoal and kerosene are widely used as sources of energy for cooking and lighting for most rural and urban areas. The consumption capacity of petroleum, gas, oil, kerosene and industrial diesel oil is increasing annually, going from a total of 5,650 tons consumed in 1997 to more than 7,500 tons in 1999.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\nFrom 21 May to 19 June 2008, Unguja suffered a [[2008 Zanzibar Power blackout|major failure of its electricity system]], which left the island without electrical service and mostly dependent on diesel generators. The failure originated in mainland Tanzania.<ref>{{cite news| author = Staff | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7427957.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | title=Melting in Zanzibar's Blackout | date=30 May 2008 | accessdate= 14 September 2013}}</ref> Another blackout happened from 10 December 2009 to 23 March 2010, caused by a problem with the submarine cable that formerly supplied electricity from mainland Tanzania.<ref>O'Connor, Maura R. (1 April 2010; updated 30 May 2010).  [http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/africa/100331/zanzibar-tanzania-electricity-shortage \"Zanzibar's Three-Month Blackout{{spaced ndash}} Indian Ocean islands Go for 90 Days Without Power, Causing Business Problems and Water Shortages\"]. [[GlobalPost]].  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> This led to a serious shock to Unguja's fragile economy, which is heavily dependent on foreign tourism.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Bububu railway train, circa 1905.jpg|thumb|A train operating on the railway between [[Bububu]] and [[Stone Town]] in Zanzibar, circa 1905]]\n\n===Roads===\nZanzibar has 1,600&nbsp;kilometres of roads, of which 85 percent are tarmacked or semi-tarmacked. The remainder are earth roads, which are rehabilitated annually to make them passable throughout the year.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}. Zanzibar, to ensure the roads are passable at all times and are maintained had established a Road Fund Board, situated at maisala which collects funds and disburses to Ministry of Communication, whom is the Road Agency at this time through the Department of Road Maintenance, known as UUB.\n\nThe Road Fund Board, oversees a Performance Agreement entered between the Ministry of Communication and Infrastructure, while all the procurements and maintenances are assumed by the later.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Public transportation ===\nThere is no government-owned public transportation in Zanzibar. The privately owned [[Dala-dala|Daladala]], as it is officially known in Zanzibar, is the only kind of public transportation. The term Daladala originated from the Kiswahili word DALA(Dollar) or five shillings during the 1970s and 1980s when public transport cost five shillings to travel to the nearest town. Therefore, travelling to town will cost a Dollar(\u201cDala\u201d) and returning will again cost a Dollar, hence the term Daladala originated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mzfn.org/Zanzibar.html|title=MZF {{!}} About Zanzibar|website=www.mzfn.org|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Stone Town]] is the main hub for [[Dala dala|Daladalas]] on Zanzibar and nearly all journeys will either start or end here.  There are two main Dala Dala stations in Stone Town: Darajani market and Mwanakwerekwe market.  The Darajani market terminus serves the North and North East of the island and the Mwanakwerekwe market terminus serves the South and South East.  As with most of East African transport, the buses do not run on set schedules - instead departing when full.  As there is no fixed schedule, it is not possible to book tickets in advance (with the exception of [http://www.thezanzibus.com The Zanzibus]).  There are plans of implementing a government-operated bus service on the island, which will bring the ground transportations more in line with the relatively developed water and air transport infrastructure, but there is currently no timeline available for this project.  With Zanzibar visitor numbers set to top 1,000,000 annually, there will be increasing pressure on the current transportation network - the bus network will reduce the number of vehicles on the road and help reduce environmental impact of tourism on the Zanzibar.\n\n=== Maritime transport ===\n\n==== Ports ====\n[[File:Zanzibar Harbour.jpg|thumb|right|Zanzibar Harbour]]\nThere are five ports in the islands of Unguja and Pemba, all operated and developed by the [[Zanzibar Ports Corporation]].\n\nThe main port at Malindi, which handles 90 percent of Zanzibar's trade, was built in 1925. The port was rehabilitated between 1989 and 1992 with financial assistance from the [[European Union]]. The Italian contractor, [[Impregilo|Salini Impregilo S.p.A.]], was supposed to build wharves that lasted 60 years; however, the wharves lasted only 11 years before crumbling and degenerating because the company deviated from the specifications.<ref name=\"Malindi port\">{{cite web |last=Yusof |first=Issa |date=17 October 2012 |url=http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/10593-malindi-port-gradually-sinking |title=Malindi Port Gradually Sinking |work=[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503004846/http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/10593-malindi-port-gradually-sinking |archivedate=2013-05-03}}</ref> After a long legal battle, the company was required in 2005 by the [[International Court of Arbitration]] to pay Zanzibar US$11.6 million in damages.<ref>Staff (29 November 2008). [http://www.worldcargonews.com/htm/w20081129.879920.htm \"Zanzibar (Malindi) Nears Completion\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909035715/http://www.worldcargonews.com/htm/w20081129.879920.htm |date=9 September 2014 }}, ''[[World Cargo News]]''. Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> The port was again rehabilitated between 2004 and 2009 with a 31 million euro grant from the European Union. The contract was awarded to M/S E. Phil and Sons of Denmark. The then-director of the contractor suggested that the rehabilitation would last a minimum of 50 years. But the port is again facing problems, including sinking.<ref name=\"Malindi port\"/>\n\n;Ferry accidents\nThe MV ''Faith'', which began its final journey at the port of Dar es Salaam, sank in May 2009 shortly before docking at the port of Malindi. Six of the 25 people aboard lost their lives.<ref>Hutson, Terry (30 July 2009). [http://ports.co.za/news/article_2009_07_29_3609.html \"Fire Guts Passenger Ferry in Dar es Salaam\"]. Ports & Ships Maritime News.  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\nThe [[sinking of the MV Spice Islander I]] on 10 September 2011, after departing from [[Unguja]] island for [[Pemba Island]], was the worst disaster in Tanzanian history. In a report to the [[Zanzibar House of Representatives]] on 14 October 2011, Zanzibar's Second Vice President, Ambassador [[Seif Ali Iddi]], said that 2,764 people were missing, 203 bodies had been recovered, and 619 passengers were rescued. It was the worst maritime disaster in Tanzanian history.<ref>Sadallah, Mwinyi (16 October 2011). [http://ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=34437 \"Confirmed: 2,900 People Died in Zanzibar's Ferry Tragedy\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112035114/http://ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=34437 |date=12 January 2016 }}. [[IPP Media]].  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref> A presidential commission, however, reported three months later that 1,370 people were missing, 203 bodies had been recovered, and 941 passengers survived. Severe overloading caused the ferry to sink.<ref>Sadallah, Mwinyi (21 January 2012).  [http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=37681 \"Nine Charged over MV ''Spice Islander'' Sinking\"], [[IPP Media]]. Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\nThe [[MV Skagit|MV ''Skagit'']], which also began its final journey at the port of Dar es Salaam, capsized in rough seas near [[Chumbe]] island on 18 July 2012. The ferry had 447 passengers, with 81 dead, 212 missing and presumed drowned, and 154 rescued. The ferry left port despite warnings from the [[Tanzania Meteorological Agency]] for ships not to attempt the crossing from Dar es Salaam to [[Unguja]] island because of the rough seas. A presidential commission reported in October 2012 that overloading was the cause of the disaster.<ref>Staff (19 July 2012). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18899397 \"Zanzibar Ferry Disaster: Hopes Fade for Missing\"]. [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref><ref>Yussuf, Issa (12 October 2012). [http://allafrica.com/stories/201210120139.html \"Tanzania: Overloading Blamed for Ill-Fated Boat\"]. ''[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]]'' (via [[AllAfrica.com]]).  Retrieved 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Airport ===\n[[File:Abeid Amani Karume International Airport, 2013.jpg|thumb|right|Zanzibar Airport Terminal I]]\n\nZanzibar's main airport, [[Abeid Amani Karume International Airport]], has been able to handle large passenger planes since 2011, which has resulted in an increase in passenger and cargo inflows and outflows. Since another increase in capacity by the end of 2013, it can serve up to 1.5 million passengers per year.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.businesstimes.co.tz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1121:zanzibar-forms-airports-authority-modernises-aviation-infrastructure&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=57 | title = Zanzibar forms Airports Authority, modernises aviation infrastructure | publisher =Business Times (Tanzania) | accessdate = 17 January 2013}}</ref> The island can be reached by flights operated by [[Auric Air]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.auricair.com |title= Auric Air |date= March 30, 2012 |accessdate= March 30, 2012 |work= Auric Air Services Ltd}}</ref> [[Kenya Airways]],<ref>[[Kenya Airways]]</ref> [[Qatar Airways]], [[Turkish Airlines]], [[FlyDubai]], [[Mango (airline)|Mango Airline]] and Coastal Aviation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coastal.co.tz |title= Coastal Aviation|date= 2015 |accessdate= January 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:A view of the clock tower in House of Wonders through Islamic styled door in the Stoen City of Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|A view of the clock tower in House of Wonders through Islamic styled door in the Stone City]]\n[[File:Zanzibar International Film Festival 2013.jpg|thumb|ZIFF, 2013]]\n\nZanzibar's most famous event is the [[Zanzibar International Film Festival]], also known as the Festival of the Dhow Countries. Every July, this event showcases the best of the Swahili Coast arts scene, including Zanzibar's favorite music, [[taarab]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziff.or.tz/ |title=? }}</ref>\n\nImportant architectural features in Stone Town are the Livingstone house, [[The Old dispensary of Zanzibar]], the Guliani Bridge, Ngome kongwe (The [[Old fort of Zanzibar]]) and the [[House of Wonders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zanzibarheritage.go.tz/House%20of%20Wonders%20Museum.htm |title=? |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116053540/http://www.zanzibarheritage.go.tz/House%20of%20Wonders%20Museum.htm |archivedate=16 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The town of [[Kidichi]] features the [[Hamamni Persian Baths]], built by immigrants from [[Shiraz, Iran|Shiraz]], Iran during the reign of [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash bin Said]].\n\nZanzibar also is the only place in Eastern African countries to have the longest settlement houses formally known as [[Michenzani]] flats which were built by the aid from East Germany during the 1970s to solve housing problems in Zanzibar.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Duthel|first=Heinz|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AtRfDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT125&lpg=PT125&dq=Michenzani+flats+which+were+built+by+the+aid+from+East+Germany+during+the+1970s+to+solve+housing+problems+in+Zanzibar#v=onepage&q=Michenzani%20flats%20which%20were%20built%20by%20the%20aid%20from%20East%20Germany%20during%20the%201970s%20to%20solve%20housing%20problems%20in%20Zanzibar&f=false|title=Discover Entdecke D\u00e9couvrir Seychelles Travelogue: Wie Du Deinen Traum leben kannst, findest Du hie|date=2018-06-10|publisher=neobooks|isbn=978-3-7427-3476-1|language=es}}</ref>\n\n=== Media and communication ===\nIn 1973, Zanzibar introduced the first colour television service in sub-Saharan Africa.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7h1DAQAAIAAJ&dq=Zanzibar+colour+tv+in+Africa+1973.&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Zanzibar+ ''Mass Media, Towards the Millennium: The South African Handbook of Mass Communication''], Arrie De Beer, J.L. van Schaik, 1998, page 56</ref> Because of longstanding opposition to television by President [[Julius Nyerere]], the first television service on mainland Tanzania was not introduced until 1994.<ref>Martin Stumer, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110626211052/http://www.tanzania.at/mht/The_Media_History_of_Tanzania.pdf \"The Media History of Tanzania\"], Salzburg, Austria: Ndanda Mission Press, 1998, pp. 191, 194, 295.</ref> The broadcaster in Zanzibar called Television Zanzibar ([[TVZ]]) had recently changed name to Zanzibar Broadcasting Corporation (ZBC).<ref>[http://www.tvz.co.tz/tvz.html Karume House: Television Zanzibar] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703181848/http://www.tvz.co.tz/tvz.html |date=3 July 2013 }}</ref> following an enactment of an act to make it a public corporation, monitored under the Ministry of Finance by the treasurer registrar. Among the famous reporters of TVZ during the 1980s and 1990s were the late Alwiya Alawi 1961\u20131996 (the elder sister of Inat Alawi, famous Taarab singer during the 1980s), Neema Mussa, Sharifa Maulid, Fatma Mzee, Zaynab Ali, Ramadhan Ali, and Khamis.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nZanzibar has one AM radio station<ref>[http://www.radio-africa.org/am/fm.php?itu=Tanzania&region=zbw AM radio stations in Tanzania: Directory of AM radio stations in Zanzibar West region] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221632/http://www.radio-africa.org/am/fm.php?itu=Tanzania&region=zbw |date=3 March 2016 }}</ref> and 21 FM radio stations.<ref>[http://www.radio-africa.org/fm/reg.php?itu=Tanzania FM radio stations in Tanzania] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033728/http://www.radio-africa.org/fm/reg.php?itu=Tanzania |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn terms of [[landline]] communications, Zanzibar is served by the [[Tanzania Telecommunications Company Limited]] and Zantel Tanzania.\n\nAlmost all mobile and Internet companies serving mainland Tanzania are also available in Zanzibar.\n\n=== Education ===\n[[File:Zanzibar 2012 06 06 4220 (7592226526).jpg|thumb|Institute of Marine Sciences, [[UDSM]]]]\n\nIn 2000 there were 207 government schools and 118 privately owned schools in Zanzibar.<ref name=\"sacmeq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |title=Education in Zanzibar \u2013 Southern and Eastern African Consortium for Monitoring Educational Quality |publisher=Sacmeq.org |accessdate=4 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702114713/http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |archive-date=2 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Zanzibar has three fully accredited Universities: [[Zanzibar University]], the [[State University of Zanzibar]] (SUZA) and Sumait University (previously University College of Education, Chukwani).<ref>[http://www.tcu.go.tz/universities.html Tanzania Commission for Universities] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619083810/http://www.tcu.go.tz/universities.html |date=19 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSUZA was established in 1999, and is located in Stone Town, in the buildings of the former Institute of Kiswahili and Foreign Language (TAKILUKI).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suza.ac.tz/ |title=SUZA website |publisher=Suza.ac.tz |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref> It is the only public institution for higher learning in Zanzibar, the other two institutions being private. In 2004, the three institutions had a total enrollment of 948 students, of whom 207 were female.<ref>[http://zanzibar.go.tz/10%20Higher%20education.php Higher education \u2013 zanzibar.go.tz] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707084022/http://zanzibar.go.tz/10%20Higher%20education.php |date=7 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe primary and secondary education system in Zanzibar is slightly different from that of the Tanzanian mainland. On the mainland, education is only compulsory for the seven years of primary education, while in Zanzibar an additional three years of secondary education are compulsory and free.<ref name=sacmeq/> Students in Zanzibar score significantly less on standardized tests for reading and mathematics than students on the mainland.<ref name=sacmeq/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |title=Tanzania entry \u2013 SACMEQ |publisher=Sacmeq.org |accessdate=4 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702114713/http://www.sacmeq.org/education-zanzibar.htm |archive-date=2 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s, [[national service]] after secondary education was necessary, but it is now voluntary and few students volunteer. Most choose to seek employment or attend teacher's colleges.\n\n=== Sports ===\n[[File:A bird's view of Amaan Stadium in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|A bird's view of Amaan Stadium in Zanzibar.]]\n[[Association Football|Football]] is the most popular sport in Zanzibar, overseen by the [[Zanzibar Football Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tanzaniasports.com/?p=3115 |title=? |accessdate=11 August 2010|date=8 September 2009 }}</ref> Zanzibar is an associate member of the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF), but not of [[FIFA]]. This means that the [[Zanzibar national football team]] is not eligible to enter national CAF competitions, such as the [[African Nations Cup]], but Zanzibar's Football Clubs get representation at the [[CAF Confederation Cup]] and the [[CAF Champions League]].\n\nThe national team participates in [[non-FIFA Football]] tournaments such as the [[FIFI Wild Cup]], and the [[ELF Cup]]. Because Zanzibar is not a member of [[FIFA]], their team is not eligible for the [[FIFA World Cup]].\n\nThe Zanzibar Football Association also has a [[Zanzibar Premier League|Premier League]] for the top clubs, which was created in 1981.\n\nSince 1992, there has also been [[judo]] in Zanzibar. The founder, Tsuyoshi Shimaoka, established a team that participates in national and international competitions. In 1999, Zanzibar Judo Association (Z.J.A.) was registered and became an active member of the Tanzania Olympic Committee {{Citation needed|date=October 2011}} and International Judo Federation.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Farouque Abdillahi]], who was [[Princess Diana]]'s designer<ref>{{cite web|title=Fashion Designers: Farouque Abdela|url=http://fashionweekzanzibar.com/Designer-Farouque-Abdela.php|website=Fashion Week Zanzibar|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Annie Allen (missionary)|Annie Allen]], Englishwoman who came to call Zanzibar home after doing extensive medical missionary work there.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The History of the Universities' Mission to Central, 1859-1909.|last=Anderson-Morshead|first=Anne|publisher=|year=1897|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n* [[Freddie Mercury]] (born Farrokh Bulsara), British singer of the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], was born in [[Stone Town]], Zanzibar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/2015/10/the-wonders-of-zanzibars-stone-town/|title=The wonders of Zanzibar's Stone Town - The Spectator|date=17 October 2015|website=spectator.co.uk|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> At the age of 18, he fled with his family to the [[United Kingdom]] during the [[Zanzibar Revolution]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/9523701/Exclusive-interview-Freddie-Mercurys-mother-on-her-dear-boy.html|title=Exclusive interview: Freddie Mercury's mother on her 'dear boy'|first=Angela|last=Levin|date=8 September 2012|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> \n* Abdulrazak Gurnah, Novelist, was born in Zanzibar in 1948 and emigrated to Britain as a student in 1968 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/abdulrazak-gurnah|title=Abdulrazak Gurnah - Literature|website=literature.britishcouncil.org|access-date=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediaofafroeuropeanstudies.eu/encyclopedia/abdulrazak-gurnah/|title=Abdulrazak Gurnah|website=www.encyclopediaofafroeuropeanstudies.eu|access-date=2017-12-12}}</ref>\n* [[Lubaina Himid]], artist and winner of the 2017 [[Turner Prize]], born 1954.\n* [[Bi Kidude]], [[Taarab]] singer, queen of [[Taarab]] and [[Unyago]] music, received [[WOMEX]] award in 2005.\n* [[Siti binti Saad]], pioneering artist in [[Taarab]].\n\n== Places of worship ==\nThe [[places of worship]] in the city are predominantly [[Islam|Muslim]] mosques. <ref> Britannica,\n[https://www.britannica.com/place/Tanzania Tanzania], britannica.com, USA, accessed on January 5, 2020</ref> There are also [[Christianity|Christian]] churches and temples: [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Zanzibar]] ([[Catholic Church]]), [[Anglican Church of Tanzania]] ([[Anglican Communion]]), [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in Tanzania]] ([[Lutheran World Federation]]), [[Baptist Convention of Tanzania]] ([[Baptist World Alliance]]), [[Assemblies of God]].\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:ZanzibarBeach.jpg|A Zanzibar beach\nFile:Zanzibar from sea.jpg|Stone Town\nFile:Zanzibar sultan palace.jpg|Stone Town with Sultan's Palace\nFile:Zanzibar Red Colobus Monkey.jpg|The red colobus of Zanzibar (''Procolobus kirkii''), taken at Jozani Forest, Zanzibar, Tanzania.\nFile:Cloves-spice.jpg|[[Clove]]s have played a significant role in Zanzibar's historic economy\nFile:Zanzibarsultanpalace22.JPG|House of Wonders undergoing refurbishment.\nFile:Zanzibar east coast pristine beach.JPG|Zanzibar East Coast beach\nFile:Red-Knobbed_Starfish_Nungwi.jpg|Red-knobbed starfish on the beach in Nungwi, northern Zanzibar\nFile:TipputipPortrait.jpg|Zanzibari slave trader [[Tippu Tip]]\nFile:ZanzibarOmaniRuler.jpg|[[Oman]]i Sultan of Zanzibar\nFile:View of ferry docked at Zanzibar Old Town's Ferry Terminal.JPG|View of ferry docked at the Zanzibar Ferry Terminal\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[German East Africa]]\n* [[List of Sultans of Zanzibar]]\n* [[Zanzibari cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Chapurukha Kusimba, ''The Rise and Decline of Swahili States'' (Walnut Creek, California: AltaMira Press, 1999)\n* Don Petterson, ''Revolution in Zanzibar'' (Boulder, Colorado: Westview Press, 2002)\n* [[Emily Ruete]], ''[http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11754/ Memoirs of an Arabian Princess from Zanzibar]'', 1888 (many reprints). The author (1844\u20131924) was born Princess Salme of Zanzibar and Oman and was a daughter of Sayyid Said.\n* H. S. Newman, ''Banani: the Transition from Slavery to Freedom in Zanzibar and Pemba'' (London, 1898)\n* W. W. A. FitzGerald, ''Travels in the Coastlands of British East Africa'' (London, 1898)\n* R. N. Lyne, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_HtENAAAAIAAJ ''Zanzibar in Contemporary Times''] (London, 1905)\n* J. E. E. Craster, ''Pemba: The Spice Island of Zanzibar'' (London, 1913)\n* [[Godfrey Mwakikagile]], ''Nyerere and Africa: End of an Era'' (Pretoria, South Africa: New Africa Press, 2010); ''Tanzania under Mwalimu Nyerere: Reflections on an African Statesman'' (Pretoria, South Africa: New Africa Press, 2006); ''Why Tanganyika united with Zanzibar to form Tanzania'' (Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 2014); ''The Union of Tanganyika and Zanzibar: Formation of Tanzania and its Challenges'' (Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 2016) \n* Pearce, Francis Barrow (1920). [https://archive.org/details/zanzibarislandme00pear ''Zanzibar, the Island Metropolis of Eastern Africa''] New York, NY: E. P. Dutton and Company.\n* ''Hatice U\u011fur, Osmanl\u0131 Afrikas\u0131'nda Bir Sultanl\u0131k: Zengibar'' (Zanzibar as a Sultanate in the Ottoman Africa), \u0130stanbul: K\u00fcre Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, 2005. [https://web.archive.org/web/20080220110433/http://www.kureyayinlari.com/Icindekiler.aspx?KID=23 kureyayinlari.com] For its English version, see [http://seyhan.library.boun.edu.tr:80/record=b1268198 Boun.edu]\n* Wolfgang Scholz, ''Challenges of Informal Urbanisation. The Case of Zanzibar/Tanzania'' (Dortmund, 2008) [https://www.amazon.de/dp/3934525504 Amazon.de]\n* Christopher Gallop, ''Letters from East Africa'' (UK, Grosvenor House Publishing 2013) {{ISBN|978-1781486283}} [https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/178148628X]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Sister project links | b=no | n=no | q=no | v=no | voy=Zanzibar | species=no | d=Q1774 | mw=no | display=Zanzibar}}\n* [http://www.wunderground.com/weather-forecast/TN/Zanzibar.html Current and forecast weather for Zanzibar]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091213041637/http://zanzibar.go.tz/ Government of Zanzibar]\n* [http://www.ikuluzanzibar.go.tz/ President's office]\n\n{{Zanzibar topics}}\n{{Portuguese overseas empire}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n{{Tanzania topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|6|08|S|39|19|E|display=title|type:adm1st}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zanzibar}}\n[[Category:Zanzibar| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Zanzibar Archipelago|*]]\n[[Category:Islands of Zanzibar| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Islands of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Former member states of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Arabic-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:Former Portuguese colonies]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1963]]\n[[Category:Swahili city-states]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "173.174.25.169", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zanzibar"}
{"title_page": "Fabian Ware", "text_new": "{{Short description|British Army general and founder of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Sir Fabian Ware\n| image         = Fabian Ware.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Major General Fabian Ware in October 1916\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1869|06|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Clifton, Bristol]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1949|04|28|1869|06|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Barnwood, Gloucestershire]]\n| placeofburial = \n| allegiance    = United Kingdom\n| branch        = [[British Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1918\u20131948\n| rank          = [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = [[First World War]]\n| awards        = [[Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]<br/>[[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Honour|Grand Officer of the Legion of Honour]] (France)<br/>[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]] (France)<br/>[[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Commander of the Order of the Crown]] (Belgium)\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major General]] '''Sir Fabian Arthur Goulstone Ware''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCVO|KBE|CB|CMG}} (17 June 1869 \u2013 28 April 1949) was the founder of the Imperial War Graves Commission (IWCG), now the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] (CWGC). Born in [[Clifton, Bristol]], he graduated from the [[University of Paris]] in 1894, and travelled to the [[Transvaal Colony]] where, as a member of [[Milner's Kindergarten]], he became Director of Education. Ware next became editor of the [[The Morning Post|''Morning Post'']], being fired in 1911 after several controversies.\n\nWhen the [[First World War]] started in August 1914, Ware attempted to join the [[British Army]] but was rejected because he was too old. With the assistance of [[Alfred Milner, 1st Viscount Milner|Lord Milner]], he obtained command of a mobile [[ambulance]] unit provided by the [[British Red Cross Society]]. In this role he began marking and recording the graves of those killed. Ware and his graves' registration organization were transferred to the [[British Army]] in 1915. This was to become the Imperial War Graves Commission. Ware ended the war as a major general, having been [[mentioned in despatches]] twice and continued to work with the commission. In [[World War II]], he was appointed director-general of Graves Registration and Enquiries. He fully retired in 1948, and died the following year.\n==Early life==\nWare was born in [[Clifton, Bristol]] on 17 June 1869,<ref name=\"Veterans Agency\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veterans-uk.info/remembrance/ware.html|title=Major General Sir Fabian Ware|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Veterans Agency|Ministry of Defence Veterans Agency]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112162637/http://www.veterans-uk.info/remembrance/ware.html|archive-date=12 November 2014|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> to Charles Ware, a chartered accountant, and his wife, Amy Carew, {{Nee}} Goulstone.<ref name= \"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|title=Ware, Sir Fabian Arthur Goulstone|id=3674|ref=harv|date=2008|first=A. J. A.|last=Morris}}</ref> He was [[Tutor|privately tutored]] until his father died when he was 18. Ware then taught in private schools to pay for attending the [[University of London]]. When he saved enough money, he began attending the [[University of Paris]],{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=17}} graduating as a {{lang|fr|bachelier-es-sciences}}.<ref name=\"CWGC\"> {{Cite web|url=http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Persons&id=DS%2FUK%2F2|title=Sir Fabian Arthur Gouldstone Ware|last=|first=|date=|website=Commonwealth War Graves Commission archives|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201223836/http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Persons&id=DS%2FUK%2F2|archive-date=1 December 2018|access-date=21 September 2018}}</ref> He then spent several years as an assistant schoolmaster at [[Bradford Grammar School]] and several other [[secondary school]]s. While working there, he was occasionally employed as an examiner for the [[Civil Service Commission (United Kingdom)|Civil Service Commission]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" />{{Sfn|The School World|1917|p=94}} On 1 August 1895, he married Anna Margaret,<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> with whom he would have a daughter and a son.{{sfn|Byrne|2014}}\n\nIn 1899 he started writing articles for the ''[[Morning Post]]''. He became the representative of the Education Committee of the Royal British Commission at the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle]] of 1900 in [[Paris]]. After the exhibition, Ware worked as an inspector of schools for the [[Board of education|Board of Education]].{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=17}} He then became a member of a group of young Britons later known as [[Viscount Milner]]'s [[Milner's Kindergarten|kindergarten]]{{Sfn|Stamp|2010|p=72}} and in October 1901 was appointed assistant director of education in the [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]].{{Sfn|Worsfold|1913|p=79}} On 5 July 1902, [[Edmund Beale Sargant]], director of education for the Transvaal, wrote a letter to the [[Council of Education, Witwatersrand]], requesting their cooperation in selecting a committee regarding technical education. A committee was then formed, with Ware as the chairman. It recommended the establishment of a technical institute.{{Sfn|South African School of Mines and Technology|1910|pp=1\u20134}} In late 1902, the report on a technical institute  reached the [[Lieutenant Governor]] of the Transvaal who in January 1903 created a second \"Technical Education Commission\" again with Ware as a member. They again recommended a technical institute, and as a result the [[Transvaal Technical Institute]] was created with Ware as the chairman of the Institute's council.{{Sfn|South African School of Mines and Technology|1910|pp=1\u20134|p=}}{{Sfn|Page|1904|p=627}}\n\nIn early 1903 he became acting director of education when Sargant, in failing health, returned to England,<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|Worsfold|1913|p=81}} and in July was made permanent director.{{Sfn|Worsfold|1913|p=84}}{{sfn|Malherbe|1925|p=305}} On 17 June 1903 he was made a member of the Transvaal Legislative Council.{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 23 June 1903}} Under Ware, the number of children in education in the Transvaal doubled in less than four years.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=21}} As director, he advocated a de-centralized system of education with responsibility largely in the hands of local authorities.{{sfn|Malherbe|1925|pp=305, 326}}\n\nIn 1905, he was offered the editorship of the ''Morning Post.'' He accepted, and moved back to England.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}} Ware aimed to make the paper \"the authority on all colonial questions.\"{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=113}} When [[Lord Glenesk]] made him editor, the ''Morning Post'' had no offices, working instead in temporary wooden sheds.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}} He began expanding the paper by hiring [[Richard Jebb (journalist)|Richard Jebb]], who then hired many other correspondents. The two began focusing the paper on the British Dominions, a move they felt would increase circulation; they were proven wrong, though it did increase advertising revenue.{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=|pp=113\u2013117}} Ware hired [[Robbie Ross]] as an art critic for the paper.{{Sfn|Fryer|2000|p=199}}\n\nAfter the [[First Moroccan Crisis]] in 1905, Ware campaigned heavily against war with Germany. He later said that {{quote|we threw the whole weight of the ''Morning Post'' against war with Germany. I am ashamed that I did not understand what we were doing at the time. I now believe that England ought to have fought Germany then{{em dash}}at any rate she is every month becoming less prepared, relatively to Germany to fight her than she was then.{{sfn|Wilson|1990|p=15}}|sign=|source=}}\n\nWare supported [[Social reform|social]] and [[tariff reform]] and he invited radicals such as [[William Beveridge]] and [[R. H. Tawney]] to contribute to the paper.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}}\n\nWare was disliked by some members of the paper's staff,{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=|pp=113\u2013117}} particularly [[Spenser Wilkinson]].<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> After coming into conflict with prominent members of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] over tariff reform, endorsing Richard Jebb (a move which cost the paper readership) and a failed fundraising campaign to buy the United Kingdom an [[airship]], he was forced out of the editorship and left the paper in 1911.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}} Ware then planned to form an independent weekly paper with funding from the countries of the [[British Empire]]; [[E. E. A. Duvernet]] proposed creating a \"United Empire Publishing Co.\" The project did not succeed.{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=27}} After leaving the ''Morning Post,'' he became a consultant for [[Rio Tinto Limited]], negotiating with the [[France|French]] government.<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/><ref name= \"ODNB\"/>\n\n==First World War==\n\n=== Mobile ambulance unit ===\n[[File:Sir Fabian Ware 1869-1949 Founder of the Imperial War Graves Commission lived here 1911-1919.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Blue plaque marking Ware's residence at 14 Wyndham Place, Marylebone]]\nWhen the [[First world war|First World War]] started in August 1914, the [[Royal Automobile Club]] under its chairman [[Arthur Stanley (politician)|Arthur Stanley]] began assisting the war effort with the creation of the [[Royal Automobile Club Volunteer Force]].{{Sfn|Hall|2017|p=110}} On 12 September 1914, several members of the club volunteered their services to the [[British Red Cross]]. As a result, the Red Cross established the Motor Ambulance Department.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.redcross.org.uk/~/media/BritishRedCross/Documents/Who%20we%20are/History%20and%20archives/British%20Red%20Cross%20transport%20during%20the%20First%20World%20War.pdf |title = British Red Cross Transport during the First World War |last1 =  |first1 =  |last2 =  |first2 =  |date =  |website = British Red Cross |publisher = British Red Cross Society |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171104042234/http://www.redcross.org.uk/~/media/BritishRedCross/Documents/Who%20we%20are/History%20and%20archives/British%20Red%20Cross%20transport%20during%20the%20First%20World%20War.pdf |archive-date = 4 November 2017 |url-status = dead |access-date = 14 October 2016}}</ref> Ware, who had been rejected from serving in the [[British Army]] because he was too old, obtained command of a mobile [[ambulance]] unit with the assistance of Lord Milner.<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/> Though one of several such units in France, Ware's unit in [[Northern France]] was operated under a \"quasi-autonomous command\" with much independence being afforded by the joint finance committee of [[St John Ambulance]] and the Red Cross; he was given his own operating budget for three month periods.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=31\u201332}}\n\nAccording to the historian [[David Crane (historian)|David Crane]], the original object of the unit was to \"search for British wounded and missing in the district which had been overrun by the Germans during the retreat from [[Battle of Mons|Mons]], and to convey them back to the British lines or to a British base.\" However, by early October 1914, the unit had begun extensively working with the French, and by mid-October, it had added a mobile light hospital and medical staff. When the unit was disbanded in 1915, it had dealt with 12,000 casualties.<ref name=\"Veterans Agency\" />{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=33}}\n\n=== Graves Registration Commission ===\nWare was struck by the lack of an official mechanism for marking and recording the graves of those killed.<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/> In September 1914, following British defeats at [[Battle of Mons|Mons]] and [[Battle of Le Cateau|Le Cateau]], Ware's unit began sharing information with [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Robert Cecil]], the head of the Red Cross's Wounded and Missing department.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=38\u201342, 50}} In March 1915, with the support of [[Nevil Macready]],{{Sfn|Stamp|2010|p=72}} the British Army formally recognized a Grave Registration Commission (GRC). The commission represented a joint effort between the British Army and British Red Cross.{{Efn|Crane writes that \"in some ways the GRC remained a curious hybrid, semi-detached sort of unit - the Red Cross continued to supply men and vehicles, while Ware was given the local rank of major... and the army took on the costs of crosses, rations and fuel\" {{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=52}}|name=|group=}}{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=50\u201352}} On 22 May, he was made a temporary [[major]] in the British Army.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 21 May 1915}} On 9 September, the promotion was [[antedated]] to 22 February 1915.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 7 September 1915}} \n\nWare's work continued to expand: by May 1915, 4,300 graves had been registered. He was extensively involved in early organization of the commission, dividing it into two main parts and seven sections. That spring he began serving as an intermediary between the French and British governments over grave-related matters. The organization began handling requests at a headquarters in [[Lillers]], and the sections worked on grave maintenance. The organization was soon exempted from a ban on [[War photography|photography]] and a department of three photographers was created to photograph graves; by mid-August, six thousand graves had been photographed and eight hundred photographs sent to families. A further 18,173 graves had been registered. Around the same time Ware became unable to continue work with the Mobile Ambulance Unit, and began to solely focus on the commission. On 6 September Macready recommended transferring the organization completely to the Army; the transfer was completed by late October.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=50\u201352, 54\u201356, 59}}  \n\nIn his role in the commission, wares served as \"the sole [[intermediary]] between the British Army in the Field and the French Military and Civil Authorities in all matters relating to graves.\"{{Sfn|War Graves|1929|p=15}} Throughout 1915 and 1916, Ware led negotiations between France and Britain, resolving various issues, particularly that of [[land expropriation]]. Around June 1915, his efforts resulted in an 'expropriation bill' that began to be debated by the French government. Ware shepherded the bill through its passage, urging prominent figures such as the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister]], the [[Adjutant-General to the Forces|Adjutant-General]], the [[King of the United Kingdom|King]], and the editor of the ''Times'' to support it.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=59, 64}} The law passed the French government on 29 December 1917.{{Sfn|NYS Assembly|1918|p=548}} It gave Britain the ability to control their war graves in \"perpetuity of [[sepulture]]\"{{Sfn|Miles|2017|p=51}} and provided for the establishment of a British authority to manage the cemeteries.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=65}} \n\nWhen [[William Glynne Charles Gladstone]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] and the grandson of former Prime Minister [[William Ewart Gladstone]], was [[killed in action]] near [[Laventie]] on 13 April 1915, his family attempted to have the body [[Exhumation|exhumed]] and returned to England. Despite a ban on exhumations established by [[Joseph Joffre]], his family received special permission to take the body and bury it in [[Hawarden|Hawarden, Wales]]. In response, Ware secured an order that banned all future exhumations.{{Sfn|Elborough|2017|p=55}}{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=68\u201376}} \n\nOn 10 September 1915 he was appointed a chevalier of the [[Legion of Honour]] by the Government of France.{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 10 September 1915}} By October 1915, the new Graves Registration Commission had registered over 31,000 graves, and 50,000 by May 1916.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/content.asp?menuid=2&submenuid=11&id=11&menuname=Records&menu=sub|title=Records|publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060807043150/http://www.cwgc.org/content.asp?menuid=2&submenuid=11&id=11&menuname=Records&menu=sub|archive-date=7 August 2006|access-date=17 September 2006}}</ref> On 11 February 1916 Ware was promoted to temporary [[lieutenant colonel]].{{Sfn|The London Gazette 28 March 1916}} After passage of the bill, [[Alfred Mond, 1st Baron Melchett]], the [[First Commissioner of Works]], and Ware competed for responsibility over the graveyards.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=81}} As the war continued, Ware and others became concerned about the fate of the graves in the post-war period. Following a suggestion by the British Army, the government created the National Committee for the Care of Soldiers' Graves in January 1916, with [[Edward VIII|Edward, Prince of Wales]] agreeing to serve as president.{{sfn|Summers|2007|pp=15\u201316}} It was set up with the intention of taking over the work of the Directorate of Graves Registration and Enquiries after the war. The government felt that it was more appropriate to entrust the work to a specially appointed body rather than to any existing government department.<ref name=\"IWC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/catalogue/externalrequest.asp?requestreference=WO32/9433|title=WO 32/9433 \u2013 Text of Memorandum put before the Imperial War Conference in April 1917|work=The Catalogue|publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307173755/http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/catalogue/externalrequest.asp?requestreference=WO32%2F9433|archive-date=7 March 2009|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1916, the GRC was formally integrated into the Army as the Directorate of Graves Registration and Enquiries (DGRE).{{Sfn|Messenger|2015|p=244}} Representatives from various relevant government departments were included and in September 1916 representatives from [[Dominion|the Dominions]] were included.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=81}} Ware was made director of Graves Registration and Enquiries at the [[War Office]] on 15 May 1916, a post he held until the end of the war.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 20 February 1920}}{{Sfn|The London Gazette 7 July 1916}} While director, he was made a temporary [[Brigadier-general (United Kingdom)|brigadier-general]] on 12 August 1916.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 13 October 1916}} The DGRE heavily regulated graves, making every aspect from spacing of graves to marking the graves uniform.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=84}} Ware also worked to resolve disagreements between various ethnicity, decreeing for instance that: \"On no account should [Egyptian] [[Mohammedans]] be buried in Christian [[consecrated ground]]. . ., [[Jewish]] graves were to be marked with a double triangle on a stake,\" and \"under no circumstances should a cross be erected over an Indian Grave.\"{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=86}}\n\nWare further had to resolve conflicts between civil members and the Army. For example, [[Lionel Earle]], a member of the International War Graves Committee, objected to the Army's practice of marking the graves of [[deserters]] with unmarked wooden crosses. As a result the custom was abolished. In 1916, efforts to neaten the cemeteries began. Ware invited [[Arthur William Hill]], then assistant director of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]], to tour the cemeteries and advise upon further planting efforts in early 1915.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=88\u201389}} In the [[1917 New Year Honours]], Ware was awarded the [[Companion Order of St Michael and St George]].{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 26 January 1917}} \n\n=== Imperial War Graves Commission ===\n[[File:Canadian Corps - Canadian war graves.jpg|thumb|Canadian war graves near [[Ypres, Belgium]]. The crosses identify the graves as those of soldiers of the [[14th Battalion, CEF|14th Canadian Battalion]] who were killed over several days in May 1916.]]\nIncreasingly costly battles such as the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme]] and [[Third Ypres]] in 1916 and 1917 continued to put further strain on the DGRE.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=93}} By early 1917, several members of the committee believed a formal imperial organisation would be needed to care for the graves. With the help of the Prince of Wales, Ware submitted a memorandum to the [[Imperial War Conference]] in 1917 suggesting that an imperial organisation be constituted.<ref name=\"IWC\" />{{sfn|Summers|2007|p=16}} The suggestion was accepted and on 21 May 1917 the Imperial War Graves Commission was established by royal charter, with the Prince of Wales serving as president, [[Secretary of State for War]] [[Edward Stanley, 17th Earl of Derby|Lord Derby]] as chairman and Ware as vice-chairman.{{sfn|Peaslee|1974|p=300}}{{sfn|Summers|2007|p=16}} In September 1917, he was given authority to wear the insignia of a commander of the [[Ordre de la Couronne]].{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 28 September 1917}} In 1917 he was made a [[companion of the Order of St. Michael and St. George]].{{Sfn|Office of Commonwealth Relations|1919|p=485}} The Commission's undertakings began in earnest at the end of the war. Once land for cemeteries and memorials had been guaranteed, the enormous task of recording the details of the dead could begin. By 1918, some 587,000 graves had been identified and a further 559,000 casualties were registered as having no known grave.<ref> {{cite web |url = http://www.cwgc.org/about-us/history-of-cwgc.aspx |title = History of CWGC |publisher = Commonwealth War Graves Commission |access-date = 14 August 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130803025303/http://www.cwgc.org/about-us/history-of-cwgc.aspx |archive-date = 3 August 2013 |url-status = live |df = dmy-all }}</ref> On 7 October, Ware was made director-general with the temporary rank of [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|major-general]].{{Sfn|The London Gazette 1 November 1918}}\n\nIn June 1917, Ware proposed a 10 pound budget per grave, that became standard figuring for the commission.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=139}} In July 1917, a committee, consisting of the [[Director of the Tate]] [[Charles Aitken]], [[Edwin Lutyens]], and [[Herbert Baker]] toured the cemeteries in order to form a plan for post-war activities of the commission.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=103}} In 1917, [[Frederic G. Kenyon]] was made artistic director of the commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwgc.org/learn/news-and-events/news/2017/12/07/08/55/sir-frederic-kenyon-sculpture-added-to-cwgc-collection|title=Sir Frederic Kenyon sculpture added to CWGC collection|last=|first=|date=|website=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407012919/https://www.cwgc.org/learn/news-and-events/news/2017/12/07/08/55/sir-frederic-kenyon-sculpture-added-to-cwgc-collection|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> In 1918, Lutyens, Baker, and [[Reginald Blomfield]] were appointed the Commission's principal architects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KPN7n3yTJSyX9rQYkZDHHX/how-wwi-remembrance-monuments-created-beauty-from-chaos|title=How WWI remembrance monuments created beauty from chaos|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407035523/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KPN7n3yTJSyX9rQYkZDHHX/how-wwi-remembrance-monuments-created-beauty-from-chaos|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The three architects often came in conflict over their views for the commission. Kenyon often served as a mediator.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=108\u2013117}} That year, Kenyon finished his report, titled ''War Graves: How the Cemeteries Abroad Will Be Designed,'' and presented it to the commission. The report outlined many factors of how the cemeteries would be designed, particularly emphasizing equal treatment of all soldiers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/history/their-name-liveth-for-evermore|title=Their name liveth for evermore|website=Imperial War Museums|language=en|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407012925/https://www.iwm.org.uk/history/their-name-liveth-for-evermore|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nFor his work during the war, Ware was [[mentioned in despatches]] twice,<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/> once by [[Douglas Haig]] on 10 April 1919.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 8 April 1919}} In 1919 he was made a [[commander of the Order of the Bath]],{{Sfn|Sillar|1959|pp=926\u2013927}} and in 1920 a [[knight commander of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/>{{Sfn|The London Gazette 20 February 1920}} He received the [[Croix de Guerre]] and was made a [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|commander of the Order of the Crown of Belgium]].{{sfn|Byrne|2014}} On 1 March 1921 he relinquished his commission and was granted the rank of honorary major-general.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 8 March 1921}} In May 1922, he was made [[knight commander Royal Victorian Order|knight commander of the Royal Victorian Order]].{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 23 May 1922}} Ware was given the authority to wear the insignia of a commander of the [[Legion of Honour]] on 27 December 1933 and the insignia of a grand master on 16 December 1938.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 5 January 1934}}{{Sfn|The London Gazette 16 December 1938}}\n\n== Post-war ==\n[[File:Memorial to Fabian Ware in Gloucester Cathedral.jpg|thumb|150px|Memorial to Fabian Ware in [[Gloucester Cathedral]]]]Upon the end of World War I, the commission could fully begin work. By April 1920, there had been 128,577 re-internment in France and Belgium and the commission was handling 788 cemeteries.{{Sfn|Parliamentary Debates|1920|p=254}}  Ware continued to work for the commission.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> In March 1920, he predicted there would be over 500,000 graves and 1,300 cemeteries in France and Belgium.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=141\u2013142}} He oversaw the building of numerous cemeteries, with contributions from architects including Lutyens{{Sfn|Geurst|2010|p=184}} and  Blomfield<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwgc.org/learn/horticulture-and-works/our-architects/sir-reginald-blomfield|title=Sir Reginald Blomfield|last=|first=|date=|website=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622101005/https://www.cwgc.org/learn/horticulture-and-works/our-architects/sir-reginald-blomfield|archive-date=22 June 2019|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> and the author [[Rudyard Kipling]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/what-was-the-imperial-war-graves-commission|title=What was the Imperial War Graves Commission?|last=Smyth|first=Hanna|date=|website=National Trust|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103130636/https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/what-was-the-imperial-war-graves-commission|archive-date=3 January 2020|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> The commission faced criticism over not allowing individual memorials for soldiers and repatriation of bodies of the dead, including in a petition that was presented to the Prince of Wales with over eight thousand signatures.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=145, 148\u2013149, 151\u2013154}}\n\nWare worked with [[William Burdett-Coutts]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], and [[Harry Gosling]], a labour leader, to write statements urging Parliament to allow the commission to continue its work.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=145, 148\u2013149, 151\u2013154}} The efforts led to a debate in Parliament on 4 May 1920.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1920/may/04/imperial-war-graves-commission|title=Imperial War Graves Commission HC Deb 04 May 1920 vol 128 cc1929-72|date=4 May 1920|work=[[Hansard]]|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625173055/http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1920/may/04/imperial-war-graves-commission|archive-date=25 June 2009|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref> Sir [[James Remnant]] started the debate, followed by speeches by [[William Burdett-Coutts]] in favour of the Commission's principles and [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Robert Cecil]] speaking for those desiring repatriation and opposing uniformity of grave markers. [[Winston Churchill]] closed the debate and asked that the issue not proceed to a vote. Remnant withdrew his motion, allowing the Commission to carry out its work assured of support for its principles.{{sfn|Longworth|2003|pp=51\u201355}}<ref name=\"A History p3\">{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/wargravescommission/docs/history/1?e=4065448/5004091|title=A History of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission|publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|page=3|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231002231/http://issuu.com/wargravescommission/docs/history/1?e=4065448%2F5004091|archive-date=31 December 2013|accessdate=28 December 2013}}</ref> Ware also fought for funding for the Commission. In the 1930s, he moved to [[Amberley, Gloucestershire]].{{sfn|Byrne|2014}} \n\nIn 1932, as a result of the [[British Empire Economic Conference|Imperial Economic Conference]], the Imperial Committee on Economic Consultation and Co-operation was established.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1933-11-22/26|title=Report of Imperial Committee on Economic Consultation and Co-operation. - Motion of Approval|last=|first=|date=22 November 1933|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|language=en-ie|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509030714/https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1933-11-22/26/|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref> Ware served as a British delegate to the committee, which published a report in 1933. In July 1932 Ware urged [[R. B. Bennett]] to support an 'Imperial Economic Committee' outside the [[British Treasury]]'s control. He was the first to seriously propose something of the kind, submitting a draft charter for the establishment of the 'Imperial Economic Commission', which would function as an economic [[general staff]] for the empire. The proposal gained little support.{{Sfn|Drummond|2013|pp=219\u2013220}} \n\nHe published an account of the work of the IWGC in 1937 titled ''The Immortal Heritage''.{{Sfn|Ware|1937|p=1}} He served as chairman of the [[National Education Union]], was an honorary associate at the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]],''<ref name=\"ODNB\" />'' and a director of the journal [[Nineteenth Century and After|''Nineteenth Century and After'']]. As a director of the journal, he made the decision to appoint [[Arnold Wilson]] as editor in 1936 and later insisted on his removal for poor coverage of the [[Spanish Civil War]] in 1938.{{Sfn|Love|2014|p=1036}} He was an adviser at the [[1937 Imperial Conference]].{{Sfn|Quigley|1981|p=159}} Ware also served the county of Gloucestershire in various capacities,''<ref name=\"ODNB\" />'' including as president of the Gloucestershire Rural Community Council from 1940 to 1948,{{sfn|National Archives|2019}} chairman of the executive committee of the [[Parents' National Educational Union]] in 1939,{{Sfn|Sillar|1959|pp=926\u2013927}}{{Sfn|Journal of Education|1939|p=14}} and Chairman of the Gloucestershire Branch of [[Council for the Preservation of Rural England]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1945/feb/14/war-memorials|title=War Memorials|last=|first=|date=14 February 1945|website=Parliament of the United Kingdom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724164021/https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1945/feb/14/war-memorials|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak of the [[Second World War]] saw Ware recalled from retirement to serve as director-general of Graves Registration and Enquiries at the War Office on 30 August 1939.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 6 October 1939}} On 3 September 1939 he was granted an emergency commission with the honorary rank of major-general.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 1 December 1939}} He also continued in his role as vice-chairman of the Commission.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|Miller|2017}} Ware ceased to be director-general in 1944 and resigned as vice-chairman of the Commission in 1948 due to failing health.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|New York Times|1949}} Ware died on 28 April 1949 in [[Barnwood House Hospital]], Gloucester. He was buried in Holy Trinity Churchyard, Amberley on 2 May. His grave has a CWGC-style headstone.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> There are also memorial tablets to him in the Warrior's Chapel at [[Westminster Abbey]] and in [[Gloucester Cathedral]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-commemorations/commemorations/fabian-ware/|title=Fabian Ware|website=Westminster Abbey|access-date=2 December 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202141455/https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-commemorations/commemorations/fabian-ware/|archive-date=2 December 2018|url-status=live|ref={{harvid|Westminster Abbey|2018}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=CWGC/2/2/1/333|title=Records|last=|first=|date=|website=CWGC|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055511/http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=CWGC%2F2%2F2%2F1%2F333|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2 December 2018|ref={{harvid|CWGC Records|2018}}}} </ref> The road 'Boulevard Fabian Ware' in [[Bayeux]], the location of [[Bayeux War Cemetery]], is named in his honour.{{Sfn|Holmes|1992|p=368}}\n==Footnotes==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n;Sources\n{{Reflist|4}}\n\n==References==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* {{Cite book |title = Empires of the Dead: How One Man's Vision Led to the Creation of WWI's War Graves |last = Crane |first = David |publisher = William Collins |year = 2013 |isbn = 978-0-00-745665-9 |location = London |pages =  |ref = harv |authorlink = David Crane (historian) }}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112105033069&view=1up&seq=651|title=The Dominions Office and Colonial Office List Comprising Historical and Statistical Information Respecting the Oversea Dominions and Colonial Dependencies of Great Britain|last=|first=|publisher=Office of Commonwealth Relations|year=1919|isbn=|location=|ref={{harvid|Office of Commonwealth Relations|1919}}}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HU3-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA219&lpg=PA219&dq=Imperial+Committee+on+Economic+Consultation+and+Co-operation+%22fabian+ware%22#v=onepage|title=British Economic Policy and Empire, 1919\u20131939|last=Drummond|first=Ian M.|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136607158|location=|pages=219\u2013220|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/robbierossoscarw00frye|title=Robbie Ross : Oscar Wilde's devoted friend|last=Fryer|first=Jonathan|date=2000|publisher=Carroll & Graf|isbn=|location=|ref=harv|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Elborough|first=Travis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oZo3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|title=Our History of the 20th Century: As Told in Diaries, Journals and Letters|date=28 September 2017|publisher=Michael O'Mara Books|isbn=978-1-78243-736-9|location=|ref=harv|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UnZfMbYczpUC&pg=PA22|title=Cemeteries of the Great War by Sir Edwin Lutyens|last=Geurst|first=Jeroen|date=2010|publisher=010 Publishers|isbn=978-90-6450-715-1|location=|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/5b5419b2-1db0-4bd7-b7b8-a16a3cc00654|title=Gloucestershire Rural Community Council|last=|first=|date=|publisher=National Archives|year=|isbn=|location=|language=English|access-date=24 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724132917/https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/5b5419b2-1db0-4bd7-b7b8-a16a3cc00654|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live|ref={{harvid|National Archives|2019}}}}\n*{{Cite book |url = https://books.google.com/?id=F9AoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA110&dq=Royal+Automobile+club+Adventures+on+the+western+front:+August,+1914-June,+1915#v=onepage |title = Communications and British Operations on the Western Front, 1914\u20131918 |last = Hall |first = Brian N. |date = 7 June 2017 |publisher = Cambridge University Press |isbn = 9781107170551 |location =  |language = en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |ref =harv | title= The Unending Vigil: The History of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission |last=Longworth |first=Philip |year=2003 |origyear=1st. pub. CWGC:1967 |edition=1985 revised |publisher=Pen and Sword |isbn=1-84415-004-6 }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Miles|first=Stephen|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CTiwDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=%22perpetuity+of+sepulture%22#v=onepage|title=The Western Front: Landscape, Tourism and Heritage|date=19 January 2017|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-4738-3376-0|location=|ref=harv|language=en}}\n*{{cite book|title=Fatal Avenue: A Traveller's History of the Battlefields of Northern France and Flanders, 1346\u20131945|last=Holmes|first=Richard|publisher=Jonathan Cape|year=1992|isbn=1844139387|location=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFoLAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA3&lpg=RA1-PA3&dq=%22Transvaal+Technical+Institute%22+%22fabian+ware%22&source=bl&ots=IM3Kk-eYs1&sig=ACfU3U1ROV-_9vMtoF81SLKLChawD5qGkw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiIvbDVqNDjAhVBmuAKHa4cA5UQ6AEwAHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Transvaal%20Technical%20Institute%22%20%22fabian%20ware%22&f=false|chapter=Historical Summary|pages=1\u20139|title=Calendar for the Year 1911|last=|first=|date=1910|publisher=South African School of Mines and Technology|isbn=|location=|language=en|ref={{harvid|South African School of Mines and Technology|1910}}}}\n*{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/educationinsouth00egma|title=Education in South Africa (1652\u20131922)|last=Malherbe|first=Ernst Gideon|date=1925|publisher=Juta|others=Library Services University of Pretoria|isbn=|location=|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GpA7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA548&lpg=PA548&dq=%22the+sole+intermediary+between+the+british+army+in+the+field%22#v=onepage|title=Documents of the Assembly of the State of New York|date=1918|publisher=|isbn=|location=|ref={{harvid|NYS Assembly|1918}}|language=en}}\n*{{cite book |title = International Governmental Organizations |last = Peaslee |first = Amos Jenkins |publisher = Martinus Nijhoff |year = 1974 |isbn = 978-90-247-1601-2 |edition = 3rd |volume = 2 |location = London |ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Messenger|first=Charles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a2OzBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT244|title=Call to Arms: The British Army 1914-18|date=30 April 2015|publisher=Orion Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-78022-759-7|location=|pages=244|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |url = https://books.google.com/?id=pN5sJFKherYC&pg=PA113&dq=fabian+ware+%22Morning+Post%22#v=onepage |title = News and the British World: The Emergence of an Imperial Press System, 1876\u20131922 |last = Potter |first = Simon James |date = 2003 |publisher = Clarendon |isbn = 9780199265121 |location = Oxford |pages =  |language = en |ref = harv }}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/carrollquigley_angloamericanestablishment|title=The Anglo-American Establishment|last=Quigley|first=Carroll|publisher=Books in Focus|year=1981|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/carrollquigley_angloamericanestablishment/page/n173 159]|author-link=Carroll Quigley|access-date=26 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825171210/https://archive.org/details/carrollquigley_angloamericanestablishment|archive-date=25 August 2019|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati19411950lees|chapter=Ware, Sir Fabian Arthur Goulstone|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati19411950lees/page/926 926]-927|title=The dictionary of national biography : founded in 1882 by George Smith|editor-last1=Lee|editor-first1=Sidney|editor-last2=Nicholls|editor-first2=C. S.|editor-last3=Stephen|editor-first3=Leslie|last=Sillar|first=F.C.|date=1959|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Internet Archive|isbn=|location=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fYI27dbGdX4C&pg=PA72&dq=%22Fabian+Ware%22#v=onepage&q=%22Fabian%20Ware%22&f=false|title=The Memorial to the Missing of the Somme|last=Stamp|first=Gavin|date=6 August 2010|publisher=Profile Books|isbn=978-1847650603|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title = Remembered: The History of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission |last = Summers |first = Julie |publisher = Merrell |year = 2007 |isbn = 978-1-85894-374-9 |location = London |ref = harv }}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uHcbAQAAIAAJ&q=%22I+am+ashamed+that+I+did+not+understand+what+we+were+doing+at+the+time.+I+now+believe+that+England%22&dq=%22I+am+ashamed+that+I+did+not+understand+what+we+were+doing+at+the+time.+I+now+believe+that+England%22|title=A Study in the History and Politics of The Morning Post, 1905\u20131926|last=Wilson|first=Keith M.|date=1 January 1990|publisher=E. Mellen Press|isbn=9780889465039|location=|pages=15|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1IZQAAAAYAAJ&q=%22the+sole+intermediary+between+the+british+army+in+the+field%22+%22all+matters+relating+to+graves%22&dq=%22the+sole+intermediary+between+the+british+army+in+the+field%22+%22all+matters+relating+to+graves%22|title=War Graves of the Empire|date=1929|publisher=Times Publishing Company|isbn=|location=|ref={{harvid|War Graves|1929}}|language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1 = Ware |first1 = Fabian |title = The Immortal Heritage. An Account of the Work and Policy of the Imperial War Graves Commission During Twenty Years 1917\u20131937 |date = 1937 |publisher = University Press |location = Cambridge |edition = 1 |url = https://books.google.com/?id=Lg49AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Immortal+Heritage#v=onepage&q=The%20Immortal%20Heritage&f=false |accessdate = 7 November 2015|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo1.ark:/13960/t4wh3592b&view=1up&seq=5|title=The Reconstruction of the New Colonies Under Lord Milner|last=Worsfold|first=William Basil|publisher=Kegan Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co.|year=1913|isbn=|volume=2|location=London|pages=|oclc=5327043|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=D9Q_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA254&lpg=PA254&dq=%22128,577%22+re-interments#v=onepage|title=Parliamentary Debates: House of Representatives|date=1920|publisher=|isbn=|location=|ref={{harvid|Parliamentary Debates|1920}}|language=en|last1=Parliament|first1=New Zealand}} \n\n=== Newspapers, gazettes & journals===\n\n* {{Cite news|url=|title=Solution for war dead|last=Byrne|first=Eugene|date=18 March 2014|work=The Post|access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RDgnAAAAMAAJ&q=President+of+Executive+of+the+%22Parents'+National+Educational+Union%22+%22fabian+ware%22&dq=President+of+Executive+of+the+%22Parents'+National+Educational+Union%22+%22fabian+ware%22|title=Journal of Education|last=|first=|date=1939|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=|volume=71|location=|language=en|ref={{harvid|Journal of Education|1939}}}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Love|first=Gary|date=2014|title=The Periodical Press and the Intellectual Culture of Conservatism in Interwar Britain|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/historical-journal/article/periodical-press-and-the-intellectual-culture-of-conservatism-in-interwar-britain/147A806451D9E53E4B48952B28B631F5|journal=The Historical Journal|publisher=Cambridge University Press|volume=57|issue=4|pages=1027\u20131056|doi=10.1017/S0018246X14000429|url-access=subscription|via=|access-date=26 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906005301/https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/historical-journal/article/periodical-press-and-the-intellectual-culture-of-conservatism-in-interwar-britain/147A806451D9E53E4B48952B28B631F5|archive-date=6 September 2019|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite web |url = https://www.smh.com.au/world/war-graves-serve-as-a-reminder-of-the-cost-of-conflict-20170424-gvqvth.html |title = War graves serve as a reminder of the cost of conflict |last = Miller |first = Nick |date = 24 April 2017 |website = The Sydney Morning Herald |language = en |access-date = 2 December 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181202141455/https://www.smh.com.au/world/war-graves-serve-as-a-reminder-of-the-cost-of-conflict-20170424-gvqvth.html |archive-date = 2 December 2018 |url-status = live|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal |url = https://books.google.com/?id=KdhRAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=%22Bradford+Grammar+School%22+Fabian+Ware#v=onepage&q=%22Bradford%20Grammar%20School%22%20Fabian%20Ware&f=false |last = |title=Personal Paragraphs |first =  |date = 1917 |publisher = Macmillan and Company|volume=19-20 |pages = 94 |language = en|ref={{harvid|The School World|1917}}|journal=The School World|via=}}\n* {{London Gazette|issue=11525|date=23 June 1903|page=645|city=Edinburgh| ref={{harvid|The Edinburgh Gazette 23 June 1903}}}}\n* {{London Gazette\n| issue = 12849\n| date 